fields.obituary_body:
William passed away on April 20, 2013. He was born in Phelps, W.I. to William and Helen Anderson and was one of five children.
The family moved to Riddle, Oregon where William graduated from high school. He served in the Army for three years.
William received a Bachelor of Science degree in business and accounting from California State University, Fresno and from 1974-1993 he worked for the U.S. government as a Federal Senior Auditor, Office of Inspectors General with DoD, Treasury, EPA and SBA.
William loved both commercial and sports fishing.
He will be greatly missed by family and friends.

A celebration of life will be held for Vernon Dean Ellis, 81, of Saunders Lake, Saturday, May 18th from noon to 4pm at their home on Saunders Lake. Come share your stories. The family will be gathering afterwards to say their goodbyes to both Mom and Dad and their beloved lake house. Parking is limited, transportation from the boat ramp parking lot will be provided.

Vernon passed away surrounded by family and loved ones at the home he loved on Saunders Lake on March 21, 2013. Cremation rites were held at Ocean View Memory Gardens in Coos Bay.

He was born at home, the first of three children to Orma Dean (Pete) Ellis and Ida Mabel Welch on January 13, 1932 in Bend, Oregon.

Vernon was a proud veteran of the Korean War. On his return, he married his wife, Marion of 54 years, who preceded him in death in 2010. Together they raised three children. Vern, as he was widely known, was an avid hunter, including a record bull elk, fly fisherman and family man who enjoyed many hobbies. He was involved for years with Men’s Barbershop and was also an award winning Wildfowl bird carver with a following that reaches across the United States. He wore many hats in his lifetime; logger, hardtop racecar driver, truck driver, salesman, truck owner/operator, artist, musician, fireman first responder, father, grandfather, uncle and friend to many. He always left his charm and smile wherever he went. He always found a friend wherever he and his family might have traveled.

Vern will be lovingly remembered and terribly missed by his son, Scott and Kate of North Bend; his daughters, Shawn Reiber and Kenny of Central Point, Jo Reierson of Seattle; brother, Roger Ellis, 7 grandchildren, 9 great-grandchildren, several nieces and nephews and countless friends.

He was preceded in death by his wife of 54 years, Marion Ellis and his sister, Shirley Whitaker.

In lieu of flowers, the family would ask that contributions be made to the Hauser RFPD, 93662 Viking Lane, North Bend, OR, 97459 or to the South Coast Hospice, 1620 Thompson Road, Coos Bay, OR 97420.

Friends and family are encouraged to sign the guestbook at www.coosbayfh.com.

Arrangements are under the care of North Bend Chapel, 541-756-0440.

fields.obituary_body:
Loetta May Southworth passed away peacefully, on April 22, 2013. She was born January 23, 1933 in Eakly, Oklahoma to Harlan & Marcell Smith.
A Memorial Service is planned for Saturday, April 27th at 11:00 AM at Musgrove Family Center in Eugene. 
Loetta was a homemaker, she is survived by three daughters, Dorothy Dill of Eugene, OR., Carolyn Asti of Mulino, OR., and Joanna Maixner of Denver, CO. Also seven grandchildren, Shelly, Stacie, Mandy, Deanna, Jill, Cody & Katie and ten great grandchildren.
She was preceeded in death by her husband, Everett Southworth and grandson, Michael.
Memorial Contributions can be sent to HOSEA Youth Services, PO Box 1401,Springfield, OR 97477.

Roy Barr, age 66 of Redmond passed away in Portland on April 21, 2013.
He was born to Bird and Margaret (Bachard) Barr in Portland, on November 22, 1946.
He married Anna Steiner on September 21, 1971 in Eugene.  We worked as a Fire Fighter during his working years.  In  his retirement he spent a lot of time as a Gym Supervisor and Study Hall Teacher at Willamette High School.
He is survived by his wife Anna, sons; David of Albany, Brian (Misty), and Jason both of Eugene and 9 grandchildren.  
Memorial contributions can be made in Roy's name to the Center for Hematological Malignancies at the OHSU Knight Cancer Institute by calling 503-494-7071.

William T. "Corky" Johnson was born on October 31, 1925, to Robert Alva Johnson & Addie Berle Craig, in Saline, Missouri. He died April 21, 2013, in Eugene, Oregon. 
Corky was married to Dixie Lee Bresler on May 15, 1952, in Eugene, OR., they divorced in 1957. He then married Marian W. (Pritchard) Wilks on November 5, 1958, in Eugene, OR. 
He is survived by his wife, Marian, his children, Shawn Thornton Johnson of Eugene, OR., and Ronna Lee Johnson, of Springfield, OR. He was father to, Robert A. Wilks, Ellen M. (Wilks) Wilson, Lillian D. (Wilks)(Kohlmeier) Kennedy and Shelley E. (Johnson)(Webb) Niemi of Eugene, OR. 
He was preceeded in death by two brothers, James Henry Johnson & Robert Benjamin Johnson, two sisters, Margaret Lavinia Montgomery & Elizabeth Beryl Smith. He has 22 grandchildren, 49 great-grandchildren and six great-great-grandchildren. Plus many nephews and nieces.

Marvel passed away peacefully on April 20th at her home in Springfield due to heart failure. She was 83. She was born on March 23, 1930 in Naponee, Nebraska to Hobart Hays and Mary (Landreth) Hays. She was one of twelve children.
The family moved to Oakridge, Oregon where Marvel graduated from Oakridge High School. 
On March 28, 1959 she married Lawrence (Bud) Aitken. They moved to Springfield where Marvel worked as a secretary and bookkeeper for Roseboro Credit Union. 
She leaves behind her beloved husband, three sons, two daughters, nine grandsons, ten great-grandchildren, and a large extended family. 
A memorial service will be held at Buell Chapel in Springfield on Friday, April 26th at 1:00.

Lois Ann Prince, age 91, passed away on April 19th 2013 in Eugene, OR.
Ann was born at the original Eugene Hospital in 1922. She was raised in Eugene, Portland and Bend, OR where she graduated from Bend High School.  
Ann attended the University of Oregon where she studied art.  She was a member of the Delta Gamma sorority.  
Ann married Frank R. Prince Jr. from Bend in 1946.  They moved to Eugene where she was a member of the Eugene Welfare League, which later became the Junior League.  Ann was a supporter of the Eugene Symphony Guild.  She was a dog lover, an avid piano player, needle point and petit point designer and a gifted artist in the mediums of oil, charcoal and pastel.
After her first husband Frank passed away in 1988 Ann remarried Arthur D. Stump in 1994.
Ann is survived by her husband Art and her three children, Deborah from Seattle, WA; Charles from Salem, OR and David from Eugene, OR.
The family wishes to thank Cascade Manor’s Health Care Center and Sacred Heart Hospice for the loving care she received in the last months of her life.
A Graveside Service will be held, Tuesday, April 23, 2013 at Rest Haven Memorial Park, 2:00 PM.

Phillip Madero Quinteros (1926-2013)

Phil passed away peacefully on Friday, April 12, 2013 in Eugene, Oregon. He was born August 21, 1926 to Manuel and Rosa (Madero) Quinteros, in San Francisco, California. 

Phil was a United States Army veteran, serving in WWII (1945-1946).  He married Eva Pollock in 1953 and they had three children.  They later divorced in 1960.  He married his second wife, Mary McCole in 1975.  He worked for the City of San Francisco for twenty years and then went to work for Joaquin Moraga School until his retirement in 1993.  Phil loved his family, friends and 49ers.

He leaves behind one daughter, Linda (Robin) Alexander; daughter-in-law, Janet Quinteros; grandchildren, Robin Marie Alexander (Johl), Clovis Alexander (Marissa), Shannon (Desi) Quintano and Michael Quinteros (Amber); great-grandchildren, Connor and Kendyll Quintano and Leila and Karissa Quinteros; and brothers, Walter (Nellie) and Bernard (Sara).  He was preceded in death by his wife, Mary (2004); his sons, Phillip Michael (1986) and Joseph Anthony (1978).

A funeral mass will be held on Thursday, April 25, at 10:00 a.m., at St. Alice Catholic Church, 1520 F St, Springfield, Oregon.

James JL Hodge (Jim to all his friends) of Elmira, Oregon passed away April 17, 2013 at his home due to complications from diabetes and heart disease at the age of 76.   He was born August 24, 1936 in Atkins, Arkansas. 
He grew up in Russellville, Arkansas.  At the age of 14 he moved to St. Louis Missouri and at age 17 moved to Tillamook, Oregon.  He joined the Navy in 1956.  He returned on leave to his hometown of Tillamook where he met his beautiful bride- to- be Margene.  They married August 2, 1958.  They were stationed at Treasure Island, San Francisco, CA until his honorable discharge from the Navy in 1962.  They moved to Noti (previously called Starcamp) and then settled in Elmira where they have resided at the same residence for 50+ years.  James worked for International Paper in Vaughn, Or for 25+ years and then Rosboro, Springfield, OR until his retirement.  
James enjoyed his love and hobby of building and restoring antique cars of which he just completed a 1936 Ford, wheeling and dealing, being involved with the antique car clubs of which he was a founding member of each, working and tinkering around his property, and spending time with his grandchildren. 
He is survived by his wife of 54 years, Margene and their dog Shorty, his son Calvin and daughter-in-law Katie and their children Kody and Kayela all of Springfield, Or; daughter Sharon and son-in-law Brian and their children, Derik, Jeremy, and Tyler all of Rocklin, CA; and son James (Buddy) from Elmira, Or and his children, Lacey of Grants Pass, Oregon, and Jesse of Eugene, Oregon.  

A memorial service will be held at Lane Memorial Gardens, 5300 West 11th Ave, Eugene, Or on Tuesday, April 23, 2013.  Private viewing will be at 9am and 11am for Graveside Services.  A Celebration of Life Gathering immediately following at Elmira Grange Hall, 88764 Sprague St, Elmira, Oregon.

Patsy Ruth Webb, the best mother ever in the whole wide world, passed away April 18thfrom lung cancer. She was 84 years old. Patsy Ruth Keenan was born October 18, 1928 to Goldie and Patrick Keenan and moved to Oregon with her parents when she was 17.
She married Jack Sasser in 1947 after meeting him where she worked for his parents at Sasser's Cleaners in Springfield, Oregon. Patsy and Jack had two sons and a daughter before he passed away in 1959.
In 1963, Patsy married Chester Webb, a widower who had two sons. In 1964 they welcomed a baby girl to the family. In 1969 Pat and Chet adopted 3 more children.
Patsy was a mom who always listened to her kids and never judged them. She was always open to talking things through. She had a fantastic sense of humor and could find humor in many things. She could always laugh at herself too. She was just a total blast to be around. 
She learned to play bridge in her 40's and became a fantastic bridge player with a sharp wit. She could remember every hand she played, even a day later. Everyone always wanted her for a partner, because she always treated people nicely even if they were miserable players. Her bridge partner, Marj Strupp and she played for many years at the Eugene Bridge Club, and even recently have been playing cards together. Marj was her best friend.
In 1985 she went to work for her daughter Cris at Cris Pettit Insurance in Springfield. She got her insurance license and was very proud of passing the test for it the first time she took it. She worked there for many years, and there wasn't a customer that didn't love her. She always had an easy and common sense way about her. 
Another thing she was quite good at was baking. She and her daughters got together every year the week before the Lane County Fair and entered as many as 40 baked goods a piece some years. She loved getting together and kicking the guys out for those few days while they baked, and laughed, made messes, laughed, dropped flour everywhere, and laughed and entered her entries. She took Grand Champion at least twice during this time. 
One of Patsy's other favorite things to do was go fishing. She spent a lot of time down on the river and taught her kids and grandkids how to fish. She liked to fish, but didn't eat it. Go figure.

Patsy is survived by her children, Mike Sasser (Cindy) of Medford, Mark Webb (Diane) of Anchorage, Cris Pettit (Lynn) of Sweet Home, Keri Davis (Ted) of Springfield, Price Webb of Eugene, grandsons Patrick, Joseph, and Keenan, grandaughters Rachael, Jennifer, Tiffany, Amber and Alisha, & great-grandsons Oscar and Isaiah. She is also survived by her sister in law, Zola Hamm, whom she thought of as a sister and wonderful friend. Husband, Chester and sons Mike Webb, Jim Sasser, Troy Webb and daughter Sundee Webb preceded her in death. She is also survived by brothers Ron, Jerry, Joe and sisters Frances and Sue.
We would like to thank Jean & Keith Gorton for being such a good friends for so many years and helping our mom out. Jean has been there when Pat needed her and was there when we all needed her. She is really more a part of our family as well as a good friend. Thank you Jeannie. 
We would also like to thank Cascade Hospice and Home Instead Senior Care for their love and tenderness they showed to our mom during the short time they knew her.
In lieu of flowers please make contributions in Pat's name to Rotary International or Marion County Dog Shelter, 3550 Aumsville Hwy SE, Salem, OR 97317.

Irene May Holley, 90, of Springfield went to be with the Lord on April 10th at her home with her family at her side.  She was born to Loren and Thelma (Link) Jordan on December 24, 1922 in Goble, OR.
She moved to Eugene in July of 1939 at the age of 16.  She married three wonderful men. Irene was buried with James on April 17th at Willamette National Cemetery in Portland.
Irene was a member of the Springfield Eagles Auxiliary, the Moose Auxiliary, and the Red Hat Society.  She loved to crochet, embroider, garden in her roses, go camping, and fishing.  She square danced for 10 years and ballroom danced for 60 years. 
She is survived by, sons, Dick Jones (Edna) of Vancouver, WA; Kenneth Jones (Debra) of Creswell; daughters, Joanne Vincent (Gary) of Portland; Thelma Bailey of Springfield; sisters, Dolores Masengill, of Junction City; Virginia Murphy of Roseburg, OR; Darlene Toysen of Monroe, WA; Lynda Hedrick, of Eugene; 10 grandchildren; 34 great grandchildren; and 9 great-great grandchildren.
She is preceded in death by her three husbands, Clarence Jones, Milton Chetwood, James Holley; sister, Lucille Graville; brother Loren Lengacher; and son-in-law Bernald Bailey.
A memorial service will be held at Ebbert Memorial Church in Springfield on April 27th at 2:30 pm.  A reception and gathering will follow.  
Mom, Grandma, you will be missed by all.

Floyd was born to William & Sarah Zehner-Fisher at home on the family homestead, located on Bodenhamer Road in Eugene, OR. He was the youngest of four brothers and one sister, who all preceeded him in death.
He attended the old one room Malabon School on Fir Butte Road, Crow High School and Eugene High School.
June of 1937, Floyd married Lucille M. Schooling. They enjoyed 62 years of marriage. Lucille passed away in 1999.
Floyd had many careers in his lifetime. Cutting shakes, farming, dairy worker. He owned and drove his own log truck for a few years and worked for Zip-O-Log Mills as a catskinner for many years. Floyed also owned an apple-peach-cherry orchard and Fisher Florist Greenhouses, where he raised Chrysanthemums, Cyclamens, Easter Lilies, Pointsettias, Azaleas and bedding plants. Some were sold to local florists and some plants and plant cuttings were shipped to commercial greenhouses out of state. 
He was still farming, mowing and bailing hay and planting a large garden each year, in fact he had seeds started for this years spring garden, before becoming ill.
Floyd was a faithful Christian, active with his 'Christian Family' to the end. He never retired from the work of this world or the Lord's work.
He is survived by his two daughter's, Delores Park (Jon) of Eugene and Carole Watson of San Diego, CA. Two grandchildren, ZoAnn Reinmuth (Steve) of Eugene and Jon Park Jr. of Hillsboro and one great-grandson, Dezmond Reinmuth. "We will all miss him"!!
A Family Graveside Service to be held at Oak Hill Cemetery and a Memorial Service will be Sat. April 27th, 11:00 AM. at Sonrise Christian Church.

Lois Mary Johnson of Reedsport, OR died of natural causes April 15th, 2013 at the age of 95. She was born in Gardiner, OR on September 22nd, 1917 to Alys and Nelson Hogan, affectionately known to the family as Muzz & Bop. Upon her graduation from the University of Oregon in 1939 she moved first to Ashland, OR, working as a junior high school teacher before returning to the area of her birth and working as the librarian of the Reedsport High School until her retirement in 1979. 
	
While in high school Lois met and fell in love with her future husband Irving G. Johnson. The couple was married on September 6th, 1941 at the home of her parents. They made Reedsport their home and together raised two  daughters, Lynette and Susan.  The couple enjoyed 47 wonderful years of marriage until Irving’s death in August of 1998. 
	
Lois eventually moved to Eugene in order to be closer to her family and live out her remaining years. She is survived by her daughters Lynette Saul and Susan Williams, and her grandchildren Michael and Matthew Saul, and Allison and Evan Williams. She will be remembered most for her warm devotion to friends and family, her kindness and generosity, her quick wit and even quicker smile. 
	
A celebration of her life will be held privately at a later date. The family wishes to thank the staff of both the Fox Hollow Residential Care Community and The Hospice of Sacred Heart for their excellent level of care. In lieu of flowers contributions can be made in the name of Lois Johnson to the Hospice of Sacred Heart.

Roland D. Clarke passed away on April 15th, 2013 at the age of 62. He was born in Portland, Oregon on July 10th, 1950.  Roland lived most of his life in Eugene, graduating from Churchill High School.  He worked for Emerald Pool and Patio before moving to Seattle, where he built baseball fields.  He then moved to Minnesota where he owned his own business supplying parts and  machinery  to the railroads.  He returned to his hometown of Eugene where he married Charlene Wallis.  He worked for InnSight Hotel Management before starting his own business, Asset Maintenance Group. 
Roland loved to work, most often with his faithful dog Charlie by his side. He enjoyed spending time with his wife working at their Happy “Our” Ranch, which included rescued potbelly pigs, horses, donkeys, chickens, dogs and cats. He enjoyed spending time with his grandkids and always managed to crack them up with his quirkiness. 
Roland is survived by his wife of seventeen years Charlene Wallis, his stepson Dan Wallis and wife Vanessa, stepdaughter Rachelle Nicholas and husband Steve and his grandchildren Kyler, Taylor and Jacob Wallis and his nieces Tara and Joey Clarke and their children, who loved him very much. 
A memorial service will be held a West Lawn Memorial Park, 255 S. Danebo St.,  Saturday,  April 20th, at 2:00 p.m.  A small reception will take place immediately following the service.

fields.family_contact: John Brasuell or son Barry Brasuell
fields.obituary_body:
Ruth Ella Brasuell passed away on April 14, 2013.  She was born in Clarksville, Arkansas to Elma and Henry McSwain.  Her parents passed away when she was young so she was raised by her grandmother and aunt.  During World War II she began nurses training paid for by the military.  During her training the war ended and she went on to graduate from Sparks Nursing School and became a registered nurse.

During her training she met her future husband John while she was caring for his father.  They were married in 1946 and moved to Oregon.  She continued her nursing career in Klamath Falls, Albany and finally in Eugene where she worked for Sacred Heart Hospital for 43 years.

She was preceded in death by her brothers Heartsill and Tom and her sister Drucella.

Survivors include her husband John, daughter Sandra Thorsen and her husband Dennis, of Lake Oswego, Oregon, son Barry Brasuell of Phoenix Arizona.  Two grandsons, Scott and Sandy and three great-grandchildren, Devyn, Emma and Trevor.

Ruth was quick witted and kept her sense of humor even during her last days.  She and John loved to square dance and travel.  She enjoyed soap operas, reading and had a great love for animals, especially cats.  In honor of Ruth please "hug a nurse" the next time you meet one!!

A Memorial Service will be held Saturday, June 1, 1:00 pm at Sacred Heart Medical Center @ RiverBend Chapel in Springfield.  In lieu of flowers please contribute to Greenhill Humane Society or the Alzheimer's Association Oregon Chapter.

Pat was born October 16, 1927 in San Francisco, to Thomas Joseph Lennon MD and Katherine Mary (Buckley) Lennon. She received a Bachelors degree in Biology from Dominican College, and her subsequent Nursing training at St. Mary’s in San Francisco and Georgetown University in Washington, D.C.  

Pat married John Mountz on January 30th, 1954. When he died in 1969, she returned to work, raised her 3 children and saw them through college.  She married Jean Allard in 1997; they later divorced. Pat worked as a Registered Nurse at Alameda Hospital and was promoted to Associate Director of Nursing there. She retired to Sweet Home, OR and later moved to Eugene, OR. 

Pat was an avid gardener, quilter and seamstress, and card player. She was a fabulous cook and is survived by aspiring cooks that share her enthusiasm.
Pat served as President of The Sweet Home Garden Club, President of the Catholic Women’s Society of Sweet Home, Member of the Council of Governments Senior Health Services Advisory Board, Founding volunteer for Dinner With Daisy (a local soup kitchen), Member of the Jolly Stitchers Quilting Club, and Volunteer for the Red Cross. She was instrumental in the expansion and updating of the Sweet Home Senior Center, and was quite active supporting church activities. 

Pat is survived by her brother Daniel Lennon of Sonoma, California; son Thomas (Dawn) Mountz of Prineville, daughters Katherine (Dean) Vendrasco of Eugene, and Patricia Almason of Sweet Home. She leaves behind her beloved 8 grandchildren and 5 great-grandchildren, as well as many nieces and nephews. She was preceded in death by her sister Katherine Greenhalgh and her husband John Mountz.

Pat died April 15, 2013 in Springfield OR of Alzheimer’s Disease.  Private burial will be held at a later date in San Rafael CA.  Arrangements are by Musgrove Family Mortuary.  

The family wishes to thank ElderHealth and Living for their compassionate care of Pat for the past several years. Donations may be made in Pat’s honor to Food for Lane County (www.foodforlanecounty.org) or The Alzheimer’s Association (www.alz.org).

Thomas J. Loome age 91 passed away April 15, 2013 of age related causes. Tom was born December 5, 1921 in Chicago Illinois. He was married to Marie H. Heritsch Jan 12, 1946 in Chicago. Tom served in the US Navy during World War II. He practiced as a Physical Therapist to polio victims prior to practicing as a Podiatrist in Eugene & Roseburg since 1956. He was active in the Oregon Duck Club, Lions Club, Ems baseball, Knights of Columbus, Cascade Chorus Barbershop, and Oregon State Forensic Services Division.  Survivors include: one sister Gina Kassler, one Daughter Sharon, three sons Patrick, Brian & Bill, two daughters in law: Sue & Julie, one Son in-law Lowell, Six Grand Children: Andrew, Stephanie, David, Leah, Brooke & Deborah. 	 
Funeral Services held at St. Mary’s Catholic Church in Eugene April 24, 2013 at 12:15 pm

Doris Fay Swafford of Crow passed away April 15, 2013. She was 90.  She was born October 18, 1922 in Eugene, OR to James W. Haynes and Lila (Armstrong) Haynes. She grew up on Nelson Mt. Rd. where she attended Chickahomney School until the 8th grade. 

She married William “Bill” Swafford in 1939, they later divorced. She then married Chester Winter in 1943. He died in WWII. She then re-married Bill Swafford in 1945.

She enjoyed attending and volunteering at the Senior Center in Veneta. She was a homemaker. She enjoyed her grandkids and great grandkids.
 
She is survived by 2 sons; Leslie Swafford of Junction City and Chester Winter of Elmira, 1 daughter and son in law; Darlene and Rick Turnbo of Veneta, 8 grandkids, 18 great grandchildren, and numerous great-great grandkids. 

She was preceded in death by 2 husbands; William Swafford and Chester Winter, 1 son; Calvin Swafford and 1 granddaughter; Wendy Turnbo.

Wendell E. Brown passed away April 14, 2013, he was 91.  He was born February 14, 1922 to Erle D and Jessie Nora Brown in Airlie, Oregon, in Polk County. He attended OSU and graduated from U of O and did graduate studies at the School of Social Service Administration at The University of Chicago.  He retired from State employment in 1980 after 28 years with the Department of Adult and Family Services. He served during WWII in the Army in the States and on Shemya in the Aleutian Islands. 
He is survived by one brother Marlen Brown and a sister Marlene Brown Payne and numerous nieces and nephews. He was preceded in death by his brother Norman in January of 2004. 
Wendell was intensely interested in the constant change in the world as it affected friends as well as humanity in general.  His outlook on life was “I love humanity as a group, but there are some people who do things I take strong exception too."  
Inurnment will take place at Eagle Point National Cemetery. No services will be held at his request.

After a joyous life, Lois Margaret Anderson, of Eugene, passed away on Friday, April 12th, 2013 at the age of 80. 

Lois was born to Harold and Margaret Fawver on August 3, 1932. After graduating from Elmira High School, Lois earned a degree from Oregon College of Education in 1952 and a Bachelor of Science from the University of Oregon in 1961. She was passionate about education and taught primary school for more than 30 years in Lane County. Along with core academic subjects, Lois believed that children should also learn social and financial responsibility. She maintained lifelong friendships with many of her students and retired from teaching in the late 1980s. 

In 1962, Lois married the love of her life, A. O. “Bud” Anderson. Together they enjoyed traveling around the country, bowling, and spending time with their many friends. Although they never had children, Lois loved kids and doted on her nieces and nephews, and later on, her great nieces and nephews. 

After Bud died in 1980, Lois remained devoted to her family and to the many organizations she volunteered with, including Alpha Delta Kappa, the Emblem Club, and the Eugene Hearing and Speech Center. She also enjoyed gardening and flowers. 

Above all, Lois Anderson lived her life as a generous role model and an inspiration to the countless people whose lives she touched. We will miss her every day.

Lois was preceded in death by her brother Courtland and her sister Mildred. She is survived by her brother, Don, and many nieces, nephews, great nieces, and great nephews. 

Visitation will be at West Lawn Memorial Park (225 S. Danebo, Eugene, OR) on Monday, April 22nd from 9am-12pm with a memorial service to follow at 1pm. Burial will be at Lane Memorial (5300 West 11th, Eugene, OR) following the memorial service.

Memorial contributions can be made in Lois' name to the Eugene Hearing and Speech Center.

Our amazing Wife, Mother, Grandmother, Great-Grandmother, Sister, Aunt, Cousin, and friend passed away on April 12, 2013 due to Leukemia (AML). She was born on February 1, 1930 to George and Charlotte Barlow in Great Falls, Montana. On September 14, 1956 she married Glenn Alan Case in the LDS Los Angeles Temple. They resided in San Leandro, CA where they raised their 6 children. When Glenn retired in 1988 they moved to Oregon.
Joyce was a very active member of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints. She served in many leadership positions, was a wonderful teacher and filled four full-time missions for the church.
She is survived by her eternal companion Glenn and 6 children: Diana Denton (Tony) of Nacogdoches, TX, Debra Astle (Randy) of Kennesaw, GA, Kathleen Case of Springfield, OR, Marlene Stewart (Clair) of Las Vegas, NV, Alan Case (Linda) of Ashland, OR, and Christine Davis (Carl) of Hillsboro, OR, 19 Grandchildren and 8 Great-Grandchildren. One brother Raleigh Barlowe of East Lansing, MI and two sisters Sally Cragun of South Weber, UT and Shirley Taylor of Spokane, WA. Her brother Maurice preceded her in death.
Joyce will be remembered for her testimony of Jesus Christ, her strength, independence, service, love, and dedication. She was a fabulous cook, baker, and seamstress; pies and bread were her specialties.
A viewing will be held on Friday, April 19th from 6-8 p.m. at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home. The funeral will be held at The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints: 1155 President Street in Eugene, OR on April 20, 2013 at 11:00 a.m. with a viewing starting at 10:00 a.m.
In lieu of flowers please contribute to The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints General Missionary Fund as per Joyce’s request. See www.ldsphilanthropies.org./missionary/ to donate.

A Celebration of Life Service and potluck to follow will be held at 2:00 pm, Saturday April 20th at the Crossfire Family Worship, 942 28th Street in Springfield for Lazaro "Larry" Ontiveroz of Springfield, who passed away April 11, 2013. He was 66 years old.

He was born on December 17, 1946 in Carlsbad, New Mexico to parents, Aurelio and Josephine Ontiveroz. He married Treavis "Trigger" on August 16, 1969 in Springfield, OR.

He worked at the University of Oregon for 23 1/2 years until his retirement in January 2011. Larry was also the Director of Hands of Hope Food Ministry.

Survivors include his spouse, Treavis "Trigger", sons; Shawn and Cody, daughter; Elizabeth, 4 brothers, and 7 sisters, and grandchild, Cordell.

Rememberances to the Benevolence Fund, Crossfire Church, for family.

Born in Niles, Ohio to Alice Nestich Birskovich and Stephen F. Birskovich Sr., second child in a family of nine children. Graduated from Vienna Ohio High School in a class of 21 students. Graduated from John Carroll University in Cleveland, OH. in 1958 with a premed degree. At this point he was considering going into the priesthood but made the decision he would prefer to have a wife and family. He graduated from Stritch School of Medicine Loyola University in Chicago in 1962. He married his long time girlfriend Jacqueline Rowder in 1960 in Vienna, Ohio. A year was spent at Fresno County General Hospital for an internship and returned to Chicago for a 3 year Internal Medicine residency at Hines Veterans Hospital.  
He spent two years at Madigan General Hospital in Ft. Lewis WA where he started a Rheumatology Clinic. Time to make a decision. Where to settle down and practice medicine? He chose the Eugene Hospital and Clinic in 1968. By then they were blessed with six children. He practiced for twenty-six years at the clinic where he chaired many committees including the building committee. In 1991, he left the Clinic and went into solo practice in Rheumatology. In 1998, he retired to a full life of traveling, gardening, the ever-present community committees including the local water board. Above all he got great enjoyment from his children and grandchildren.
He and Jackie traveled to Italy, Kenya, China, Japan, Guam, Australia, New Zealand, Ireland, England, Canada, Artic Circle, and Croatia. He particularly enjoyed Croatia as he had the opportunity to visit with newly discovered relatives. His Catholic faith was a driving guide for his life and desire to travel to Israel to travel in the footsteps of Jesus and his disciples. In the early 1970’s, helped advise and build St. Jude Church and rectory in Eugene.
Steve was a member of the Delta Rotary and enjoyed participating in their projects. He especially enjoyed the Owen Rose Garden project and frequently took family there for picnics. He was an avid DUCK FAN for over 40 years. Trips were planned around the DUCKS football and basketball schedule.
Stephen is survived by his spouse, Jacqueline, daughters Marie Steinmetz, Debi (Ja-Kael) Luey, Becky Mantanona of Kennewick, WA and Cathy Waterer of Reedsport and sons; Stephen Birskovich of Vida, and Daniel Birskovich of Coos Bay. Sisters Marian (Robert) Turner of Mansfield, OH, Marge Koval of Burlington, VT, Teresa (John) Scotchie of Millsboro, DE, Veronica (Travis) Finch of Rio Vista, CA, Bernadette (Joseph) Paukovich, and brother; Gregory (Mary) Birskovich of Youngstown, OH and 5 grandchildren. 
He is proceeded in death by brothers; Joseph and Thomas Birskovich and grandchild; Star Waterer.
In lieu of flowers, donations may be made to: Eugene Delta Rotary Scholarship Fund and St. Benedicts Church Building Fund.
Celebration of Life will be April 22 at St. Benedicts Church at McKenzie Bridge at 11:00 am. Refreshments following service.

Mardell Elaine Gygli (1921 – 2013) of Vida passed away peacefully April 10th from Congestive Heart Failure, she was 91. Mardell was born April 18, 1921 in Haugen Wisconsin to John and Olga Gygli. Mardell served in the Navy during World War ll. She attended College at Eau Claire Business School and also did bookwork for her father for his wood working business. Mardell worked for Armour & Co. in Eau Clair Wisconsin, transferred to Portland Oregon where she worked for 40 + years. While working at Armour she also worked the night shift at US Bank for 25 of those years. After retiring in 1988, Mardell moved to the McKenzie River to be near her sister Helen. She was active in Neighborhood Watch, Food for Lane County, McKenzie River Lions Club, and a member of the Upper McKenzie Community Center. Mardell liked to knit, play pinochle, tease and loved food. She was an Independent, Spirited, Loving Caring person and will be missed. She is survived by her sister Helen Juza, nephews John Juza, Jim Juza, Carl Juza, Alan Juza, Dan Juza and niece Jane Bills.
A celebration of Life will be held May 4th at the Upper McKenzie Community Center at 2:00 pm. Contributions can be made to The Upper McKenzie Community Center or Food for Lane County.

Craig Helgeson, age 60, passed away April 12, 2013 at his home. Craig was born November 13, 1952 in Eugene, Oregon to Harris and Nellie Helgeson.
Craig lived in the Eugene area his entire life, graduating from North Eugene High School. He served in the US Navy aboard the USS Saratoga, receiving the National Defense Service Medal, Vietnam Service Medal, and Vietnam Campaign Medal.  At the time of his death he was employed by A&K Development, Eugene, as a millwright.
Craig enjoyed music and reading. He always knew he was much more intelligent than his three siblings, and never passed up a chance to remind them of that fact.  Craig was a fierce defender of human and animal rights. 
Craig loved, and was loved by, a small black Pug named Stewie that he co-parented with his close friend, Becca. They enjoyed many hours together walking at the dog park and exploring the banks of the Willamette River.  Stewie was with Craig during the final minutes of his life, the knowledge of which gave comfort to his family. The family wishes to express their gratitude to Becca for loving Craig and giving him joy and laughter.
Craig is survived by his sister Carol Helgeson Lutz and her husband Mike of Medford, Oregon, sister Janet Helgeson Tokich and her husband Willie of Eugene, Oregon, and brother Kevin Helgeson and his wife Pam of Eugene, Oregon; also nephews Jason, Tyler, Drew, niece Kendra, and numerous cousins.
At Craig’s request, no memorial service is planned. A family memorial gathering will take place sometime this summer. Memorial contributions may be made to the Greenhill Humane Society, Eugene, Oregon.

Marilyn Tibbitts, loving wife of Terry, died of complications of multiple myeloma on April 11, 2013. She was born December 23, 1936 in Deluth, Minnesota to Andrew and Anna (Craven) Ege. She was a graduate of Springfield High School. She married her High School sweetheart, Terry Tibbitts, on October 23, 1954. They were totally devoted lovebirds for 52 years until his death in 2007. They loved salmon fishing on the coast and camping and hunting with their family. She is treasured by her son, Mike Tibbitts, daughter Janet McIntyre and grandchildren Jason, T.J, Andie and Whitney. Private services were held at West Lawn Mausoleum.

fields.obituary_body:
Jayne E. Cooper, 64, of Eugene, Oregon, passed away on April 10, 2013. 
The Celebration of Life will be held at the University of Oregon Alumni Center, Room #202 on Sunday, April 14, 2013 at 1:00 pm 
Jayne was born in Girard, Kansas on June 29, 1948 to Earl and Myrtell (Hume) Cooper. She graduated from Sheldon High School and from the University of Oregon. 
She worked as a music teacher in various elementary and middle schools, throughout the Eugene School District for over 30 years. 
She is survived by three sisters, Carolyn Smith (Larry) of Lamar, Colorado, Rosemary Ball (Chet) of St. Joseph, Missouri and Nancy Hinke (Randy) of Grants Pass, Oregon, eight nieces and nephews and many great nieces and nephews and other family and friends. She was preceded in death by her parents and brother. 
I lieu of flowers, memorial donations can be made in her honor to the American Cancer Society. The family would like to thank the compassionate doctors and staff at the Sacred Heart RiverBend Hospital. 
She loved God, music gardening and the sound of children laughing. She was loved and is loved.

Laurel Erleen Crenshaw of Junction City passed away on April 9, 2013 at the age of 65 from lymphoma.  She was born May 28, 1947 in Eugene, OR.  A memorial service will be held on Sunday, April 14, 2013 at 2:00 at The United Methodist Church in Junction City.  She will be interned at Lane Memorial Gardens, 5300 W. 11th Ave. in Eugene, OR.  She is survived by her husband of 47 years, Melvin Crenshaw, her sons Mark and Doug Crenshaw, and her parents Nathan and Artie Albertson.  Laurel was a very active community member, including appointments to the Junction City Planning Committee and the City Council for which she was recently elected to serve a 2nd term.  She also was an active volunteer in many local organizations such Soroptomist, Moose, and BPW.  Professionally, she touched many lives as a school bus driver, helping to mentor Junction City's youth for over 20 years, and then offering her expertise in tax accounting through her tax prep business in Junction City.  Online condolences may be made at www.musgroves.com.

Robert “Bob” Glen Shelton, 79, of Springfield, died April 4, 2013.  Bob was born on March 21, 1934 in Stayton, Oregon to Glen and Bertha (Valencourt) Shelton.  
Bob served in the US Army where he was stationed in Fort Sill, OK and Fort Bliss, TX.  He graduated from Oregon State University in 1959 with a B.S. degree in Pharmacy. He worked as a Pharmacist for over 50 years and was the owner and operator of stores in San Jose, CA and Sunriver, OR.
Bob enjoyed hiking, traveling, gardening, watching the Beavers and Duck games, and spending time with his family and grandchildren.  He was also an Elder and member of the Northwood Christian Church and he volunteered at Volunteers in Medicine. 
Bob married Vera M. Loucks in Mill City, OR on May 15, 1954.
He is survived by his wife, four children, daughter, Catherine Marshall (Jim) of Henderson, KY; son, Steven Shelton (Val) of Bend, OR; daughter, Lori Hawker (Barry) of Gilbert, AZ; and daughter Karen Shelton-Mur (Andres) of Arlington, VA; sister, Vivian Miller of Hillsboro, OR; sister Doris Hoff of Vancouver, WA; brother, Tom Shelton (Ruby) of Gresham, OR; sister, Ellen Jull of Salem, OR; 7 grandchildren, and 3 great grandchildren.
His parents and sister, Frieda Bassett preceded him in death.
Memorial service will be held at 3pm on May 24, 2013, at Northwood Christian Church in Springfield.  
Memorial contributions can be made to Northwood Christian Church Youth Camp or Sacred Heart Hospice.

Dorothy Lou Palmer of Eugene, passed away on April 2, of complications related to cancer.  She was 79.  A celebration of life was held.  She was born on March 3, 1934 in Claremore, Oklahoma to Richard and Fannie Allene Glory. 
She married Richard Palmer on Oct. 7, 1950 in Stevenson, WA.  
Survivors include her husband of 62 years; two daughters, Denise Ballenger (Tony) and Dixie Avery (Scott), both of Springfield; 9 grandchildren, 13 great grandchildren, and 3 great-great grandchildren. 
She is preceded in death by her oldest daughters Debbie Allemang and Deanna Clark.

Kenneth passed away April 8, 2013 of age related causes at the age of 92. He was born May 6, 1920 in Klamath Falls, Oregon to Lorus & Clara Miller. A visitation is planned for Friday April 12, 2013 from 11:00-1:00 pm with a Funeral Service to follow at 1:00 pm at West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home at 225 S. Danebo Avenue in Eugene. Ken graduated from Pleasant Hill High School in 1939. Soon after graduation Ken enlisted in the US Navy prior to WWII where he served proudly on Destroyers escorting Air craft carriers in the South Pacific. After the war Ken spent many years in the Naval Reserves. In 1948 he married Bette Walsh who preceded him in death in 2007. A son, Dean also passed away in 2007. Survivors include Daughters Pamela Darcy of Springfield, Melanie Bennett of Eugene, Sons Lloyd of Eugene and Scott of Tucson, Arizona. A brother, Gerald of Eugene, 11 grandchildren and 5 great grandchildren. Memorial contributions may be sent to Greenhill Humane Society.

Elvin passed away peacefully Tuesday, April 9, 2013 at Marquis Care in Springfield. He was born October 16, 1923 in Eugene Oregon to Clayton and Mable (Ward) Nestle. He was 89. Elvin was a pilot serving in the Army Air Corps, stationed in Florida at the end of WWII. He worked in Los Angeles at Bakers and Confectioners for twenty years and then went to work for the Los Angeles School District as a warehouse supervisor for seven years before returning to the McKenzie Valley to retire. 
Elvin is survived by his wife of nineteen years, Phyllis (Clay) Nestle, his children Donna Graham of Austin, Tx, Douglas Nestle of Vida, OR, Michael Nestle of Vida, OR. He is also survived by his grandchildren Christine, Robert, Cheryl, Carla, Marc, Daniel, Hollie and Tim as well as his siblings Ennis Nestle & Ellen Fischl.

fields.obituary_body:
Martha Chism of Eugene, died April 9, 2013 of complications due to old age, at the age of 98 years.
She was born June 14, 1914 in Ames, Iowa, to Charles & Lucretia (Mellor) Nichols. 
A memorial service to be determined, inurnment at Story Memorial Gardens, Ames, Iowa. 
Martha graduated from High School in Ames, Iowa, and attended Iowa State University. She was a homemaker and Library Assistant at Newton Public Library in Newton, Iowa and the Eugene Public Library in Eugene, Oregon. 
She married Earl Chism on June 9, 1937, he died June 21, 1997. 
She is survived by three sons, Ralph Chism, Stanley Chism & Warren Chism and a daughter, Beth Prescott and five grandchildren and six great-grandchildren. 
Memorial contributions can be made to the Eugene Public Library.

Jo Boehm passed away peacefully at age 85 at her home on April 9th from adenocarcinoma lung cancer. Wanda “Jo” Garner was born at home February 8, 1928 to Robert Lee Garner and Eula Ada Robinson Garner in Slow Fork, Arkansas. She was the middle sibling of five. Jo and her family moved to Carlsbad, New Mexico in 1937 for two years and then settled in Junction City, Oregon.
She graduated early in January 1946 from Junction City High School and in June 1946 married Ernest “Dutch” Guy Leaton. She worked in a variety of jobs over the years; picking various fruits, vegetables, raking nuts and picking cotton. Jo worked in many restaurants in the Eugene area including Snappy Service. She also carried hod for Dutch in his brick mason business. One of her proudest accomplishments was receiving her Tax Consultant Certification at the age of 41. She thoroughly enjoyed working with her clients over the following 15 years.
Jo moved to Lewistown, Montana in 1954 and resided there for 5 years. After her divorce, she moved back to the Eugene area. She met and married Robert “Bob” Boehm in 1961 and moved to her current home of 53 years.
Jo was the mother of two children; Dr. Michael G. Leaton (Tracy) of Carmel, CA and Marcella K. Schlegel (Michael) of Novato, CA. She also had a step-son, Robert A. Boehm (Sharon) of Springfield, OR.
Jo loved to garden and would plant and weed from dawn to dusk. She enjoyed travel; her favorite travel destinations were the Oregon Coast, Sisters, and a road trip to pretty much anywhere. She was able to experience many cultures and had fond memories of her African Safari that took her through 8 countries. She dressed in fabulous hats to attend Red Hat Club luncheons, hardly ever won at Bunco night and was proud to strut at the Country Club Friendship events. She was considered a fun-loving friend by many and a real “go-getter.”
She is survived by her children, 9 grandchildren, 15 great-grandchildren, dozens of nephews, nieces, cousins and friends. She was preceded in death by her husband, parents, and siblings: Madeline Brinkman, Frankie Lowry, Charles Garner, Betty White, and Glendon Garner.
Services will be held at 11:00am at Lane Memorial Gardens and Funeral Home on Monday, April 15th. A viewing will be held on Sunday, April 14th from 12:00-4:00pm at the funeral home. Ladies, please don you favorite hat in her memory.
Jo’s smile, vim and vigor will be missed sorely by her family and friends.

Michael "Mike" G. Ainsworth, born July 22, 1958 to parents, Donald and Barbara Lundstrom (Burton) passed away April 1, 2013 at age 54.

Michael's education included Irving Elementary, Shasta Jr. High, and Willamette High School.

He worked with Golden West and Palm Harbor from 1980 - 2003. He started in building and worked his way up to management, before his illness forced him to retire. 

Survivors include parents, Gerald Ainsworth and Donald and Barbara Lundstrom, Children; son Michael, daughter Jennifer, and step daughter Jessica, and siblings; Craig E. Ainsworth of Stillwater, OK; Bryon O. Ainsworth of Albany, OR; Rick Lundstrom/Ainsworth of Lompor, Coly.

Betty Mae Hope, known to friends and family as Bim, of Eugene, Oregon, passed April 9, 2013, at the age of 93. She was born March 8, 1920, in Portland, Oregon, to Joseph and Mable Lind. She was married to Ralph A. Hope Jr. on December 3, 1944. 

Bim attended Eugene area schools, including Edison Elementary and University High School. She received her Bachelor of Arts degree in Journalism from the University of Oregon in 1942. 

The Hope family owned Oakway Golf Course for many years. Bim worked and played in Ladies Golf. She was the Women’s Club champion several times. Bim enjoyed spending winters with her husband, Ralph, in Sun City, Arizona, where they lived on a golf course. Bim’s interests included traveling the world, gardening, and making decorations. She was involved with Camp Fire Girls. 

Bim is survived by her grandson, Benjamin J. Kordon, and his wife, Melissa M. Allen, as well as her great-grandchildren Aerin Gardner, Grace Kordon, and Henry Kordon. She was preceded in death by her husband, Ralph, in 1997 and her daughter, Laurie Hope-Kordon-Harrison, in 1999. 

Per her request, no memorial service is planned. A family memorial gathering will take place later at Gillespie Cemetery. Memorial contributions may be made to Shriners Hospitals for Children or Daughters of the Nile, Nydia Temple.

fields.obituary_body:
Bernadine Rose Queen passed away on April 6th, 2013 in Redmond Oregon where she had resided for the past 18 months. Previously she lived in the Springfield area for over 50 years. She was a loving wife, mother, sister, grandmother, great-grandmother and friend. 

Born July 20, 1927 in Sydney, Nebraska to Leon and Rosa Thompson, she was the middle child. Bernadine (Bum) was sandwiched between Merna (Bunny) Daley, who preceded her in death, and Rhoda (Pooch) Smith. 

Bernadine married Harry Conrad in 1946 and together they had four children, Teddie, Lynn, Randy, and Cindi. Harry preceded her in death in 1969. 

In 1976, Bernadine married Ralph Queen, they were married until his death in 2006. 

Bernadine enjoyed spending time with her grandchildren and great grandchildren who loved her dearly. In addition to that time, she enjoyed shopping, going out to lunch with her family, and time spent at the casino. 

She is survived by her children, Teddie Crippen and Dan Myers, Lynn and Duane Ott, Randy Conrad and Amanda Briggs, and Cindi and Leo Howard; seven grandchildren; and sixteen great-grandchildren. 

A funeral will be at 11 a.m. Thursday, April 11, at the Buell Funeral Chapel in Springfield. A Visitation will be at 3 p.m. Wednesday, April 10, at Buell Funeral Chapel in Springfield. Arrangements by Andreason's Cremation & Burial Service in Springfield.

Nicole Colleen Scott, age 42, died at home in Springfield, OR on March 31, 2013.
Nicole was born in Astoria, OR on October 8, 1970, to Lisa Scott Smart. Nicole grew up in Oregon and has lived in the Eugene-Springfield area for 25 years. 
Nicole was a warm-spirited woman and she will be fondly remembered by her family and friends as a good hearted, loving person. She will be deeply missed. 
Survivors include her husband, Bartolo Tumax, daughter Chelsea Smart, age 19, son Enrique Tumax, age 13; her mother Lisa Scott Smart, numerous aunts, uncles and cousins.
Services will be held on Saturday, April 13, 2013 at 2:00 pm at Unity of the Valley, 3912 Dillard Road, Eugene, OR (at 39th & Dillard).
Memorial contributions or flowers are welcome in care of Nicole's mother, Lisa Smart, at Andreason's Cremation and Burial Services, Springfield. 
The family is very thankful for the love and support of countless friends and family.

Patsy Wilson passed away April 6, 2013 of age related causes at age 79. She was born February 14, 1934 in San Francisco, California to William & Florence McCoy. 
A Funeral Service is planned for Friday, April 12, 2013 at 1:00 PM at Musgrove Family Center in Eugene. A private burial will follow. 
Patsy graduated from Lebanon High School, Class of 1951. She married Walter Doug Wilson on July 20, 1952 in Lebanon, Oregon. 
In high school she worked as a secretary for an insurance company in Lebanon, OR and later in Klamath Falls, OR. She then raised her two girls. After the girls were in high school she went to work for the City of Eugene Fire Department as a secretary in the records department. 
She is survived by her husband, Walter, two daughters, Kathy Wilson and Lori Wilhelm both of Eugene, OR. and a sister, Ardy Stagemeyer of Lebanon, OR and brother, James Pierce of Camas, WA., three grandchildren and two great-grandchildren. 
Memorial contributions can be sent to Eugene Mission or St. Vincent dePaul.

Muriel “Merle” L. Evans was born December 5, 1918 in the city of Fossil, Oregon.  Her parents spent their entire married lives in Fossil and became prominent town fixtures: Will Evans became City Marshall and Maude Busby Evans became town librarian, at one time the oldest working librarian in the United States.

Muriel married Bob Johns in 1939, and the union produced sons Bill (born 1941) and Chuck (born 1943).  This marriage ended in divorce, and she married Dean Reed on June 13, 1946.  They lived in Mitchell and Portland before ending up in North Bend, where Dean’s trucking company (Asbury) assigned him in 1956.  North Bend was the family’s home for many years.

By the time Dean retired, Muriel and Dean lived in Eugene.  For the next 25 years, they wintered in Arizona.  The Yuma senior park was a busy place for them.  Muriel was a championship shuffleboard player and they both loved to attend the weekly dances.  Their favorite “dancing tune” was ‘Elvira’. 

Most people would say “smart” and “funny” when asked to describe Muriel.  She continued to excel at crossword puzzles for into her 90s, despite being legally blind.  But more than anything, she loved telling a good joke.

Muriel is survived by sons Bill and Chuck; grandsons Kelly, Chuck, Jimmy and Michael; granddaughters Kate and Heather; and 13 great-grandchildren.  One of her joys was assisting with a family summer camp, which entailed teaching some of the great-grandkids her favorite old songs, participating in tea parties in fancy hats and necklaces, and acting in the summer play at the end of camp.  It won’t be the same without her.

A funeral service is to take place Saturday April 13, 2013 at Fossil Methodist Church, at 1pm.

Betty "Jean" .Goodright, passed into the loving hands of the Lord on April 8, 2013 after a short aggressive form of cancer.
Born 2/11/1926 to Opal Ankrum. Jean was adopted 8 months later by William and Ella Brooks, raised in Cambridge Ohio. She told many wonderful memories of rolling skating with her friends in the summer and ice skating in the winter. Brown High School 1944,Jean met and married William Austin Goodright on Jan 1, 1949. They had 4 children, William David, Michael Brooks, Scott Lee and Tamara Jean.9 grandchildren Richard, Katie, Shantell, Rochell, Sarah, Jason Kappenman, Lindsey,  Branden Moore and Micheal Caven. 6 great grandchild.The family moved to the Eugene area in 1965 After raising their family, Jean went back to work Hickory farms and ran their holiday gift pack sales. Many teenagers loved Jean and enjoyed working for her.Jean went on to earn her C.N.A degree in 1984 which she was very proud of. Sacred Heart Hospital was the place she dearly loved to volunteer. Many wards were given to her, during her long service with the emergency room. Doctors would request her help because of her skill level. 
Jean was preceded in death by her husband Bill, son and daughter in law Michael and Carla. Also her son in law Richard Gribling (Tamara).
Jean loved the Lord and will be greatly miss by all that knew her.
Because I live, ye shall live also John 14:19
Jean requested no service to be held

Joan Gregory Snell of Eugene died April 5, at age 86. Joan was born December 15, 1926 to Leon and Junia (Young) Loehr, in Eugene. She was preceded in death by her parents, two brothers, Robert and Marion Loehr; and a sister Marilee Loehr Sonderstrom. Joan is survived by her husband, Gerald Snell; a son, Brian Gregory; a daughter, Linda Gregory Fessenden; and two step-sons, Jeffery Gregory Loehr and Steven Snell; 7 grandchildren and 22 great-grandchildren.
A Celebration of Life Visitation will be held Wednesday April 10 from 2:00 to 6:00 PM at Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield.

Walterville:  A celebration of life will be held at 2 pm on Saturday, April 13 for Richard Conway who passed away peacefully in his sleep on April 2 of heart and lung failure.  It will be held at his home at 88715 Potter Lane, Springfield.  He had just had his 91st Birthday.
He was born on March 27, 1922 in Tulsa, Oklahoma to Averd and Nancy Conway.  He married Jean Elliott on April 18, 1942.  She passed away July 1, 2005.
He was a graduate of Berkeley High School, was in the Navy in WWII and worked as an engineer for Pacific Telephone and AT&T for 40 years.  He retired in Oregon in 1983.
He is survived by a son, Jeff of Napa, CA, two daughters, Marsha Gresham of Brentwood, CA and Irma Spencer of Chandler, AZ; seven grandchildren and 18 great-grandchildren.  He lived with his granddaughter, Kim Moseley and her family for the past 7 years.
Donations may be made to the American Lung Association.

Roscoe Mayberry born June 21, 1927 died Thursday April 4th, 2013 of natural causes.  He is survived by his wife Eva Mayberry, his children Sue & Leon Batey, Bob & Barb Mayberry ,Viki Mayberry all of Eugene, grandchildren; Laura, Rocky, Cheri, Robert Jr, Kristine, Janette & Tiffany and 13 great-grandchildren.Graveside Services will be held on Monday April 8th, 4pm at Oak Hill Cemetery with a Celebration of Life potluck at Peterson Park Barn in Eugene. Condolences may be made on line at www.musgroves.com. Arrangements by West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home.

fields.obituary_body:
Nancy Rae MacDowell age 78, passed away April 4, 2013 in Eugene, Oregon. She was born April 5, 1934 in Multnomah County to Rachel & Harry Baldridge. A graveside service is planned for Thursday, April 11, 2013 at 2:00 at Rest Haven Memorial Park in Eugene. A Celebration of Life to follow at Gainsborough Community Center. 
Nancy married William Edwin MacDowell on February 24, 1951 in Gardner, Oregon. They were married for 56 before his death October 27, 2007.
She worked as a nurse prior to having her children, at which time she became a mother and homemaker.
Nancy loved roses and gardening, cooking & baking. She loved spending time with her granddaughters. She enjoyed camping and the outdoors when her children were young, loved life and entertaining her friends at BBQ's, she was very active with the kids sports programs.
She is survived by her son Scott MacDowell and daughter In Law, Tina, of Cottage Grove, OR., two granddaughters, a sister Betty of Springfield, OR.,and a nephew, Dan of Gold Beach, OR. She was preceded in death by her husband William and son, Mike MacDowell. 
Memorial contributions to the Diabetes Association.

Delmer H. Myers, 87, of Cottage Grove, OR passed away April 4, 2013.  He was born March 18, 1926, in Cottage Grove to Henry D. and Lorena C. (Moade) Myers.  He went to school through the 8th grade and then joined the US Marine Corps. and was a Corporal during WWII, serving in the occupation of Japan and Iwo Jima.   Delmer worked as a logger for Weyerhauser and other companies.  He enjoyed hunting, fishing, and he enjoyed being with his grandchildren and great-grandchildren as well as his children.  Delmer was a life member of the Cottage Grove VFW.  He married Jane A. Davidson, Sept. 14, 1947, in Cottage Grove, OR.  He is survived by his Spouse, Jane A. Myers, Cottage Grove,  Daughter, Nita A. Myers, Springfield, OR, Daughter, Kay L. Tucker, Cottage Grove, OR, Son, Tom L. Myers, Drain, OR, 10 Grandchildren, 22 Great-granchildren and 7 Great-great-grandchildren.  He was preceded in death by Son, Arlon R. Myers and Grandson, Gary W. Myers.  A Memorial service will be held April 7, 2013, 1:00 PM at the Cottage Grove Masonic Center.  The burial will be April 8, 2013, 1:00 PM at the Silk Creek Cemetery, Cottage Grove.  Service arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR 97424.

Forrest Platt was born in Detroit Michigan and spent his chilhood years there through the Depression.  As he graduated from High School in 1939, war was just breaking out in Europe.  He joined the army and was deployed to Europe as a Communications Tech in the 84th Infantry Division.  He was awarded the Bronze Star for heroism under fire in November of 1944 near the Ardennes in Belgium.
After the War, he moved to Springfield, Oregon from Detroit, Michigan where he married his wife and soulmate, Mary Phyl on June 19, 1948.  They were just a few months shy of their 65th anniversary when he passed.  When asked the secret of their long life together, he answered with one word, Jesus.  He and his wife attended First Evangelical Church on 8th and Monroe in Eugene for their entire married life until the Savior he loved so much called him home.  Our comfort is knowing that this parting is only temporary and that we will see him again.
He joined the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 379 and was a member for over 65 years and owned and ran Platt Electric Service for 25 of those years.  He finally retired at the age of 79.
He is survived by his wife, Mary Phyl; his son, Clifton of Eugene; his daughter, Michelle Barnes of Portland; and his grandchildren Andrew and Linda Barnes.
There will be a Memorial Service on Saturday, April 13, 2013 at 11:00 AM at the First Evangelical Church in Eugene.  A graveside service with Military Honors will be on Monday April 15, 2013 at 1:00PM Willamette National Cemetery in Portland.  Remembrances to the Gideons International Society.

Bobbie Dean Moore passed peacefully at home surrounded by his loved ones on April 3, 2013.  He was 89 years of age.

Bobbie was born to Earl Moore and Alta Likens Moore on March 13, 1924, in Barnes City, Iowa.  The Moore family moved to Dawson, Oregon, when Bobbie was 6 years old.  Bob attended Bellfountain Grade School and Monroe High School.  He served as a gunner's mate in the US Navy during World War II and was honorably discharged after the close of the war. 

Bob married Marie Barbee on January 6, 1954, in Eugene.  He was employed by EWEB for over 21 years prior to his retirement.  Bob was a faithful member of the Eugene Elks Club for over 65 years, where he enjoyed socializing.  He also enjoyed rock hounding and traveled widely collecting his specimens.  He was a Jim Beam bottle collector and amassed an enviable variety of bottles.  He will be fondly remembered for his beautiful orchard and vegetable garden and for happily sharing his produce.

Bob is survived by his wife of over 59 years, Marie, his son Marten, his daughter Ardys Matthews, his sister Mary Rice, one grandchild, and two great grandchildren.  Private interment will be at Lane Memorial Gardens.  A memorial will be held at the Eugene Elks hall from 2-4 p.m. on Saturday, April 13, 2013.  All of Bob's friends and family are invited. 

Remembrances to Eugene Mission or Greenhill Humane Society.

Betty Snider passed away peacefully on April 1, 2013. Betty was born in Tacoma, WA. August 14, 1923.  Her parents were Charles and Kathryn Cantrell.  She graduated from Puyallup High School class of 1942 and worked on B-24’s for Boing during WWII.
She married Everett R. Snider December 24, 1946, in Salinas CA. They moved to Richland WA in 1960.  She worked many years as a Pharmacy Tech, retiring to Florence OR in 1986.  She moved to Eugene in 1990 after the passing of her husband.
She is survived by the following relatives. Her three children Michael of Modesto CA; Richard (Donna) Snider of Eugene; Patti (Tom) Miller of Richland WA; grandchildren, Christie Covarubias, Devon Mager, Jared Snider, April and Robert Miller, and four great grandchildren.   She is remembered for her kindness and generosity and her love of cooking and baking.  A service will be held at Grace Manor 2811 Bailey Lane Eugene, OR on April 6th at 6:30pm.

Herbert Thomas ‘Tom’ Wagoner passed away peacefully on April 3, 2013 at the age of 92 surrounded by family. Tom was born in Newport, Rhode Island on October 1, 1920 to Leon and Edith Ransom (Kellen) Wagoner. He grew up in Plainview and Hicksville New York.
A celebration of life is planned for 6:30 PM Saturday, April 6, 2013 at the Veteran’s Memorial Building, 1626 Willamette St., Eugene, OR 97401. 
Tom served in the US Army from 1938-1941 and 1943-1945. He was stationed at Schofield Barracks, Hawaii and also served on the ships Ainsworth and Howell Cobb with the Army Transportation Corp. After the military he moved to San Francisco where he met Petra Austrebertha Tirado Mena who was vacationing. He traveled to Mexico City to ask for her hand in marriage. They were married on December 30, 1949 in Mexico City.
They lived in Mexico City where Tom studied at Mexico City College, later moving to New York City and working at Bank of America. Later they moved to Arizona where he was a telegrapher with the Southern Pacific Railroad. They settled in Eugene in 1965 where he later retired.
Tom is survived by his wife of 63 years Petra. His six children, daughters Linda M. McFarland (Husband Ron) of Eugene, Edith F. Houghton (Husband Bruce) of Springfield, Charlotte I. Apparcel of Eugene, Darlene P. Gardner (Husband Lenny)of Springfield; sons Robert K. Wagoner of Eugene and Dale M. Wagoner (Wife Suzy) of Eugene.
Twenty one grandchildren, Cybil C. Farr of Plainview, TX, Bruce A. Houghton Jr. of Eugene, Melissa M. Cifuentes of Albany, OR, Ryan T. McFarland of Eugene, Michelle I. Apparcel Damon, Nathaniel R. Apparcel, Lauren R. Apparcel, all of Eugene, William R. Hinkle of Springfield, OR, Danielle Deas of Eugene, Payshence Wagoner of Eugene, Precious Wagoner of Portland, OR, Isiah Wagoner of Eugene, Autumn Halbrook of Eugene, Kiona Prigan of Springfield, OR, V. ‘Vanessa’ Wagoner of Springfield, OR, Selina Horn of Eugene, Dale M. Wagoner, Jr. of Eugene, Iman Williams, Micah Williams, Shani Razor of Eugene, Kiyah Williams of Eugene. 
Twenty four great grandchildren, Sam, Max and Sidney Farr; Gabriel Houghton, Caleb and Noah McFarland, Moses and Bella Cifuentes; Alec J. Apparcel Damon and Athen J. Damon; Hunter and Emmakenzie Deas; Constance, King and Nehemiah Sherbino; Jordan Hamilton, Alyssa Woods, Lauryn and Alexys Halbrook; Nakai and Luka Horn; Simone, Sylas, Ayasha Williams.
Nephews Fernell Lopez Tirado of Eugene and Julio Jauregui Lopez of Puyallup, WA; Nieces Iliana Lopez and Lizbeth Metteer both of Eugene.
