fields.obituary_body:
Patricia "Pat" Jane Smith passed away March 30th at her home in Eugene, Oregon with her loving family by her side.  She was 83.

Pat was born on August 28, 1929 to Robert and Alice Cline in Enid, Oklahoma. She is survived by her son David Smith and grandson Austin Smith; sisters Velma Hopkins and Dolores Hainer; she was preceded in death by her brothers Percy and Ralph Cline.

Pat graduated from Oakridge High School and moved to Eugene where she graduated from business college. 

She worked for the local cement mason and bricklayers union and later worked at the University of Oregon library until she retired.

Pat's most loved interests included square dancing, crossword puzzles and reading. She also enjoyed gardening and just being anywhere that her family and friends were; she loved to laugh. We will all miss that laugh.

A celebration of life will be held at a later date.

Wayne was a loving husband to C.J. Pierce of 46 years and a loving father to 5 children.  Wayne had three surviving children, Vicki, Fawn, Jack with wife Jacki and two preceding him in death, Dani Jo and Jacqueline (Reb). Wayne graduated from Marshfield High School and served in the Marine Corps for 3 years in Vietnam. Wayne was a truck driver for 50 plus years, driving a log truck and long haul. Wayne loved and was very proud of his grandchildren and great grandchildren. Wayne enjoyed trips to the beach, flying kites, camping and keeping himself busy around the house, working on many projects he always had going. Wayne loved his brother Walt and treasured the times they go to spend together. Wayne will be severely missed and is dearly loved from his family and friends. A memorial service will be at noon Saturday, April 13, 2013 at the West Lawn Memorial Park in Eugene.

Paul Vincent Templeton passed away March 30, 2013 at the age of 72.  He had a heart attack while coming home on Highway 36.

	Paul was born September 3, 1940 in Junction City, OR at the clinic of Richard R. Rogers, M.D., to the proud parents, William Gerald Templeton and Thais Katherine (Kay) Mahony Templeton.  He grew up on the family farm west of Cheshire, OR,  that had been acquired by Templeton forebearers, Irish immigrants in the late 1860’s, which included homesteads and purchased land.

	Paul attended grade school at Crown Point, District 110 and Junction City High School, graduating in 1958.  Work on the family farm was interrupted with U.S. Army Reserve service, with his assignment being cooking.  Paul acquired land and developed a logging business in addition to farming and livestock.  He married Norma Jean Bells August 2, 1969.  The couple resided near Alderwood State Park until their current home was built in Cheshire, OR.

	Paul was an astute businessman, a professional logger and enjoyed working out in the woods.  He loved the outdoors and was an avid hunter.   Paul disliked boring, lengthy, unproductive meetings and committee work.  He could be relied upon for lengthy, private counsel, and could provide quick, terse comments at meetings that he felt needed his input.  He provided voluntary quiet assistance to many individuals whenever needed.

Paul is survived by his wife Norma of 43 years, his sisters Judith A. Templeton (Elmira), Norma J. Adams (Springfield), and brother R. Brian Templeton (Junction City), along with many nieces and nephews and many close friends and neighbors.

A public memorial service will be held Saturday, April 6, 2013 from 1:00-3:00 pm at Oaklea Middle School Cafeteria, 1515 Rose Street, Junction City, OR.  Donations may be made to The Salvation Army, St. Vincent de Paul, Eugene Mission or your choice of charity.

The family extends thanks to Lane Fire District staff, Lane County Sheriff deputies, and Oregon State Police officers for their prompt, courteous and responsible help.  Also thank you to all the many neighbors and friends for your support.

Paul, you will be very missed.

Condolences may be made on line at www.musgroves.com.  Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home.

Howard W. Berge, age 93, died peacefully in his home on March 20, 2013. He was born in Taylors Falls, Minnesota, to Harry and Ottilie Berge. He graduated from St. Olaf College in Minnesota, and was drafted into the U.S. Army shortly thereafter, entering the service in 1941. Assigned to basic training in Camp Roberts in California, he then served at Camp Adair in Oregon from 1942 to 1943. While attending a USO dance, he met his wife Beth. They married in May 1944, shortly before he shipped out for Okinawa and the Philippine Islands. After his discharge, Howard and Beth spend one year in Minnesota before eventually returning to Oregon, where they settled in Eugene, and raised three daughters. Howard’s business career was spent entirely in Eugene, a community he loved, were he worked as an independent insurance agent. Beginning at Tromp & McKinley Insurance Agency, he moved to Montgomery Insurance Agency for several years, before establishing J.K. Pratt – Berge Insurance Agency, which he co-owned until his retirement. In 1971, Howard was honored as The Boss of the Year by Insurance Women of Eugene. 

Throughout his life, Howard gave of himself to his family, his church, and his community. He was a proud member or Eugene Kiwanis for 57 years, setting a personal example of great service and great cheer. He served as president in 1970 and was awarded the prestigious Hopkins-Hollis Award of Excellence in 1998, for his many contributions to the organization. As a strong supporter of several local charities, he believed in giving his time, energy and resources. Howard and Beth were members of First Christian Church since 1947, where he served as treasurer for more than twenty years. He enjoyed a good game of golf, and was a member of Shadow Hills Country Club for many years. A supporter of U of O teams, he attended many games at Autzen stadium, as well as the 1995 Rose Bowl game. In retirement, he and Beth travelled around the U.S. and Europe, and shared 62 years of loving marriage before her death in 2006. A wonderful father and grandfather, his greatest happiness was being surrounded by his family. 

Howard is survived by two daughters, Jamie McCornack and husband Steve, of Eugene, and Tracy Kempf and husband James of Riverbank, California, and five grandchildren. He was preceded in death by his sister Irene O’Kane, wife Beth (DeLapp) Berge, and daughter Jody Orlick. 

Howard exemplified a life of joyous love for his family, deep faith, and dedicated service to his community. He will be greatly missed by all who enjoyed his wonderful smile, loyal friendship and most generous spirit. 

A Celebration of Howard’s life will be held Sunday, April 14th, at 2pm, at First Christian Church, 1166 Oak St. Eugene. Memorial contributions can be made to First Christian Church.

Ida E. Braatz was born Dec. 27, 1922 to John F. & Edna Schmidt in Hayward, Wisconsin. Her folks moved to a farm near Litchfield, MN in 1927.
She went to a one room school through the 8th grade. She worked her way through High School to pay her bus fare to go to school. After high school graduation she worked in a Woolen Mill and made blankets for the army. She worked at bookkeeping until her marriage to Charles Ralph Braatz in 1947. They farmed for 16 years and moved to Oregon in 1963. She started her own Income Tax business in 1973.
She was a member of Tax Consultants, PGMA, The Pointe Church, the Former Whist Club.
She had 3 sons, Duane of Elmira, OR, Ronald of Scio, OR,  Richard of Eugene, OR 7 Grandchildren, 14 Great Grandchildren
She and her husband loved to travel, play cards. She loved Gospel music concerts and loved to be with her friends. She loved her yard and flowers and her family.

A visitation is planned for Friday April 5, 2013 from 10:00 – 5:00pm and Monday April 8, 2013 from 12:00 – 2:30pm. A Funeral Service is planned for Monday April 8, 2013 at 4:00pm at West Lawn Chapel.  Private Family entombment, West Lawn Mausoleum.

Vera Seideman Slick

 

Vera was 90 years young when she passed Saturday March 30th, 2013. She was born in Alliance, Nebraska on May 14th, 1922. She moved to Fresno, California in 1936 where she went to school and college then started her family life. She moved to Springfield, Oregon in 1988 with her husband Lloyd Seideman.

 

After his passing, she married Vern Slick of Springfield, Oregon. Sons Harold O’Neal and his wife Nagene of Fresno, California; Dan R. O’Neal and his wife Linda of Springfield, Oregon survive her. Two bothers, a sister and two daughters precede her in death. Her Grandchildren and Great Grandchildren are far to many to count. Vera was a licensed vocational nurse most of her life. She loved working in labor and delivery. After retiring, she volunteered much of her time at The Willamalane Adult Center, teaching and helping with everything imaginable. Vera was all about dancing, having fun and helping others. We will miss her but I know there is another angel in heaven. Viewing will be on Friday April 5th, 2013 from 1:00 P.M. to 4:00 P.M. at Buell Funeral Chapel

John Lloyd Ryan, 69, passed away on Wednesday, March 13, 2013 in Eugene, Oregon.  He was born May 16, 1943 to Lloyd and Doris Ryan in Eugene.  John attended Francis Willard grade school, Roosevelt Junior High and graduated from South Eugene High School in 1961.

John worked for Safeway at 18th & Oak from 1961 to 1968.  He worked for American Steel from 1968 to 1981 and for Consolidated Freightways from 1981 until retirement in 2002.

John's legacy is his deep faith in God, his love of family,and his church for 64 years, the First Church of the Nazarene at 8th & Madison in Eugene, which included the bus ministry that he served in for many years.   John's hobbies included Chevys, Corvettes and Lionel Trains.  In addition to his many church friends, John had friends throughout Eugene during his 69 years and many toy train enthusiasts during the past 25 years.

John is survived by his brother Tom, his sister-in-law Joan, three nieces, Ketha, Lynn & Christie and one nephew Mike.  He is survived by five great nieces, Ariel, Gabrielle, Isabelle, Emilee and Madison as well as two great nephews, Javen and Josef.

A Memorial Service to celebrate and honor John's life will be held on May 4, 2013 at 2PM at the First Church of the Nazarene at 8th & Madison in Eugene.

Cremation and interment  were provided by Rest-Haven Memorial Park at 3900 Willamette Street in Eugene.

In lieu of flowers donations can be made to the First Church of the Nazarene Building Fund or to the Kidney Cancer Association at www.KidneyCancer.org.

Walt died a week to the day he was placed on hospice, too weak, at age 92, to ‘rage against the dying of the light’. He confronted death as he confronted most things in life with a sense of humor and that laid back Tennessee way of his that endeared him to all who knew him. 
Walt was born in a remote farmhouse in the back hills of Tennessee to Walter Parker Harding, Sr. and Annie Lee Byars. The old farm house was twenty miles from the nearest high school, too far away for Walt to attend, so he began his working career in a rock quarry at the age of sixteen. He was good with his hands, good with engines, had a knack for making things work, and quickly became that company’s lead mechanic. When he was old enough to join the Navy, he asked to be trained as a pilot. He met all the qualification criteria except for a high school diploma. It was a major turning point in his life, but, as always, he took his disappointment in stride. 
Walt met Mary Emma Moore, a surgical nurse at Kaiser-Permanente hospital in Oakland, during WWII while waiting to be shipped overseas with the Navy. She became a tireless helpmate and companion until her death in 1989. The two of them converted an old school bus into living quarters before it was fashionable to live in converted buses and when the two of them crossed the Oregon border to make a new life together after the war, they had one dollar and thirty-two cents between them.
Walt found work as a millwright, boiler tender, and mechanic for Harold Jones and later for Georgia-Pacific for almost 30 years. Working swing shift six and seven days/week, Walt would come home, watch Johnny Carson, get some sleep, a light breakfast, and then go to work restoring houses that he would then rent out. Ultimately, he built Mary’s dream house on Whitbeck Boulevard where she died of cancer after forty-three years of marriage.
After caring for Mary at home until her death, Walt, already retired from G-P since 1982, then went back to Tennessee to care for his mother in her late nineties at her home. It was there he reconnected with ‘the girl next door’, Mildred Irene Sparkman-Farris, whom he married in Reno in 1991. They had twenty-two active, music filled years together, church every Sunday and a trip to Maui. 
Walt was preceded in death by both his parents and his younger brother, Edward B. Harding. He is survived by his wife, Mildred, a half sister, Doris Grandey, a half brother, John K. Jones, and a nephew, Eddie Jr., all residing in Tennessee; one child, Cara Zane McKenzie of Eugene, two granddaughters, Allison Eslyn McKenzie-Lawrence of Bellevue, Washington and Christina Renee Seber-Nelson of Jackson, Wyoming, and one great granddaughter, Annika Rose McKenzie-Lawrence of Bellevue, Washington. 
A graveside service for Walt will be held on Friday, April 5 at Lane Memorial Gardens at 3:00 pm. In lieu of flowers, donations would be welcomed by the Oregon Old Time Fiddlers Scholarship Fund or Cascade Hospice.

Charles Raymond Glaspie, 79 of Springfield, died March 30, 2013. A funeral service will be held at 3:00pm Sunday, April 7, 2013 at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home. A visitation will held Saturday, April 6th, from 4-7pm at the funeral home. Burial will be at Springfield Memorial Gardens.
Charles was born December 17, 1933 in Waterloo, Iowa to Robert and Leola (Dietz) Glaspie. He married Norma Jene Pratt on March 15, 1953 in Waterloo. 
He attended schools in Waterloo, Iowa and worked for different contractors in Eugene as a plasterer and was a member of Local #82 in Portland, Oregon. He also worked for Benny Bartell for 24 years.
Charles loved fishing, hunting and camping, in addition to gardening and helping people.
He is survived by his wife; a daughter, Laura Russell of Hollister, California; two grandsons, Eddy Russell of San Jose, California and Erik Russell of Plantation, Florida; one great-grandson, Lincoln Russell of Plantation, Florida; and one brother, Ronald Eugene Glaspie of Cottage Grove, Oregon.
He was preceded in death by his parents, Robert and Leola Glaspie; three sisters, Darlene Wood, Bonnie Barker and Charlotte Grady; and son-in-law, Edward Eugene Russell.
Memorial contributions may be made to Cascade Hospice: 2650 Suzanne Way, Eugene, OR, 97408 or the Springfield Salvation Army. 
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Nanny was a wonderful, forgiving and caring wife, mother and grandma who dedicated her life to family and friends.  Nanny loved to visit with her extended family, and the friends that she treated as family.  She enjoyed gardening, and especially cooking.  A person could not visit Nan’s house without at least 3 offers to be fed by this caring woman, and you were always met at the door with a smile.
	Lenora was born in Avard, Oklahoma and had 4 sisters and 2 brothers, all who are previously deceased.  She married Joe Francis Wagoner in 1947, who passed away in 1978 after 31 wonderful and happy years of marriage.  Nanny is survived by her 5 daughters: Elaine Barnes of Boardman, OR; Patricia Lassen of Manteo, NC; Sandra Stokes, Julie Sanne, and Pamela Burris all of Springfield, OR.  Nanny also was a loving Grandmother to her 12 grandchildren and 16 great-grandchildren.
	There will be a Celebration of Life at Lane Memorial Gardens at 5300 W. 11th Ave. in Eugene, OR on Friday April 5th at 2:00 PM.
“Forever with the Angels, Always in our hearts”

fields.obituary_body: Robert Lenard "Tex" Templeton died on March 29 at the age of 84.  He was born on February 26, 1929, in Paint Rock, Texas to Richard D. and Flora Fay (France) Templeton.  He was a truck driver and logger, and also worked for Yoncalla schools doing maintenance for 16 years.  He married Barbara J. Pennington on January 6, 1951 in Reno, NV.  He loved walking in the desert sun, and especially enjoyed his family and friends.  He is survived by his wife, Barbara; daughter and son-in-law, Dianna and Tomy Coggswell of Yoncalla, son and daughter-in-law, Michael and Helen Templeton of Yoncalla, and son, Robert W. Templeton of Eugene; 8 grandchildren and numerous great-grandchildren.  He was preceded in death by 2 brothers and 3 sisters.

Russell Franklin Dennick passed away March 28, 2013 at the age of 50 from Lou Gehrig's Disease (ALS). He was born March 19, 1963 in Uniontown, Pennsylvania to William & Mary Lou (Miller) Dennick. A funeral mass is planned for Wednesday, April 17th at 12:15 at St. Mary's Catholic Church. A private inurnment will be at Mt. Calvary Cemetery. 
Russell was a graduate of St. Joseph's College in Indiana, with a Masters Degree from Pepperdine University. He was former C.F.O. of Oregon Community Credit Union. He married Kristina Newald on June 27, 1998 in Las Vegas, Nevada. 
He is survived by his wife, Kristina Dennick; parents, William & Mary Lou Dennick of Uniontown, Pennsylvania; two sons, William of Temecula, CA and Mitchell of Eugene, OR.; a brother, William of Uniontown, Pennsylvania and a sister, Kimberly Pellick of Richmond, VA. 
Memorial contributions to ALS Foundation - Oregon/Washington Chapter.

The family of Dennis Edward Ahlstrom regrets to announce his unexpected passing in Eugene, Oregon in mid-February 2013, as a result of a sudden heart attack. He was 64 years of age. A viewing will be held Friday April 10th from 3-5. The immediate family will have a private viewing from 2-3. A memorial service for Dennis will be held at the Willamette National Memorial Cemetery in Portland, Oregon on Monday, April 11, 2013 at 1:00 p.m. 
He graduated in the top 10% of his class from Marshfield Senior High School in 1966. He attended Southwestern Oregon Community College, and in 1967--1968 served as the Associated Student Government President.  
Dennis enlisted in the Army and was stationed in Japan during the Viet-Nam conflict, where he served in intelligence. After being honorably discharged, Dennis attended Oregon State University, where he majored in administration, and received two bachelor’s degrees from OSU, one for athletic administration in 1975, and another for health care administration in 1981. While attending OSU, he served as an athletic department intern and as an assistant coach in the women’s softball program. 
His great, great maternal grandfather, Nathan Huntley Edgerton, received the Congressional Medal of Honor for his valor on the battlefield during the Civil War and as a member of the honor guard during President Lincoln’s funeral. Denny was very proud of his family’s military service history.
He is survived by his brothers and their significant others, Gary Ahlstrom and Dianne Light (Grass Valley, California) and Richard Ahlstrom and Raandi Andersen (Cottage Grove, Oregon), his sister and her husband, Nancy Anders-Sterle and Anthony Sterle (Las Vegas, Nevada), his niece and husband, Michelle and “J” Sellers, and their children, Alexander, Lillian, and Quinn (Huntersville, North Carolina), his nephew and wife, Dr. Joseph and Amanda Anders, (Las Vegas, Nevada) ---and a large extended family of cousins and their families. He is preceded in death by his parents, Harold E. Ahlstrom in 1999, and Lillian C. (“Chris”) Ahlstrom in 2006.

A funeral service will be held at West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home at 11:00 am, April 2, 2013 for Herbert Wilson Medlin, 83, of Eugene who died March 28, 2013. 
He was born October 7, 1929 in Dallas County, Arkansas to Josie Langley and William E. Medlin. He married Trubie E. Halpain on January 13, 1951 in Malvern, Arkansas.
Herbert was a sawmill worker before working as a firefighter and fire chief for Lane Rural Fire District from 1962-1980.
Herbert is survived by his wife, Trubie Medlin; their five daughters and one son; fourteen grandchildren, twenty-two great-grandchildren and eight great-great- grandchildren.

John Lyle Marvin passed away at the age of 71.  He was surrounded by loving family and friends.  John was born in Centralia, WA in 1941 and he and his brother, Jim, spent the majority of their childhood in Eastern Washington.  He graduated from WSU in 1964 and moved to Eugene, Ore. where he married Lois Barto Marvin and started the beginning of his 38 year career with Weyerhaeuser.  They had 2 daughters.  They moved the family to Puyallup in 1979 and then returned to Eugene in 2009 for retirement.  John is survived by his wife of 49 years, Lois Marvin, two daughters, two sons-in-laws and 4 granddaughters:  Kim and Eric Thomas, and granddaughter, Mara, of Springfield and Gwen and Randy Blank and granddaughters, Madison, Alyssa, and Lily of Puyallup, WA.  He is preceded in death by his parents Norman and Louise Marvin.  Funeral Services to be held  April 2, 2013 at Restlawn, Junction City.  In lieu of flowers, please send donations to St Jude’s Children’s Hospital and Cystic Fibrosis Foundation.  Online condolences may be made at www.musgroves.com.  Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home.

Theona N. Jessen longtime resident of Eugene, died at her home on Monday, March 25, 2013, at the age of 97.
She was born January 11, 1916 in Albany, Oregon to LeRoy F. and Vesta V. (Eastburn) Newton. She lived in Portland, OR for most of her childhood but moved with her family to Eugene when she was 15. She graduated from Eugene High School in 1933, returned with her parents to Portland and on May 21, 1939 she married Wilbur Jessen, her former neighbor in Eugene,  She worked as a legal secretary after attending the U of O and later as secretary at Cal Young Jr. High. She was the administrative secretary at South Eugene High School from 1957 until her retirement in 1982. A natural leader, she served as President of the Oregon Association of Educational Office Professionals and was a national conference delegate. She was also active in Le Jeune Coterie, a women's social club, and the Masonic Order of the Eastern Star. As officers of the Lane County Audubon Society, the couple made many trips birding in U.S. and abroad. They also traveled with the Eugene Gleeman. Although raised in the Christian Church (Disciples of Christ), she and Wilbur were active members of United Lutheran Church after their marriage. She was treasurer of the Mission Society for several years, and later filled that role at the church and participated in Church Women United. She loved to cook and spent countless hours nurturing her flower garden. As a senior she enjoyed her Tai Chi classes and worked hard to maintain her health throughout her life.
She is survived by her husband Wilbur and daughter, Mary Ann (Gary) Hanson of the home; three grandchildren, Richard Costa of Japan, Ryan Hague of Hillsboro, Oregon, and Donna Tobar (Luis) of Huntington Beach, California and two great grandchildren. She was preceded in death by a brother, Wilbur, in 1974.
A memorial service will be held at United Lutheran Church on April 20, 2013 at 2:00 PM, with Rev. Tom Dodd officiating. The family suggests memorials be made to the Jessen Memorial Scholarship Fund in care of the church at 2230 Washington Street, Eugene, Oregon 97405..

Carolyn Vaaler died of a massive stroke at the River Bend Hospital on March 24, 2013 at the age of 74.
She was born on July 27, 1938 in Thompson Falls, Montana, the daughter of Adrian W. and Pauline R. Vaaler. They moved to Eugene in 1940 where Carolyn received her education, graduating from South Eugene High School in 1956. She attended the University of Oregon for 3 years where she was a music major in violin performance. She moved to New York City in 1966 where she worked for 18 years as a medical records clerk for the Amalgamated Garment Workers Union. She returned to Eugene, 1984 to help her parents in their aging years.
Carolyn was a gentle soul who loved her family and spent her vacations every summer traveling to Eugene from New York via train to be with them. In the early 1960’s she joined a Friends Service Committee expedition that climbed to the top of Long’s Peak in Colorado. Family marathon bridge sessions made Carolyn and excellent competitor. Many happy hours were spent in her garden where she grew corn, zucchini, blueberries, etc. And she loved flowers such as poinsettia, gladiolas, roses and a magnolia tulip tree which grew around the home.
Long drives on family trips around the Oregon countryside, to the beach and the mountains were special pleasures. Her faithful attendance at concerts completed a musical dimension in her life.
She is survived by her sister, Miriam Schafler and her brother, Adrian Vaaler, both of whom she lived with in the family home. Her brother, John Vaaler, lives with his wife, Barbara, in Portland, Oregon. She has many cousins around the country, and was known for her remarkable memory and keep of the family history.
She had many hobbies which kept her busy: embroidery, tatting, knitting, quilt making, sculpting, various art projects, and reading. She took care of her long time pet, Muffy, a Lhasa Apso terrier mix, who preceded her death last October. She became an excellent cook which her family celebrated as “the best restaurant in town.” She was a member of the First Congregational Church of Eugene.
A memorial service will be held in the chapel of the First Congregational Church on Tuesday, April 9, 2013 at 11:00am, 1050 East 23rd Ave., Eugene, OR 97405. In remembrance, donations may be sent to the Greenhill Humane society.

Ernest Lattymer, 71, of Springfield, died on March 27th at his residence.  He was born to Hobert and Sylvia (Cobble) Morrow in Prairie City, Oregon on March 8, 1942.  He married Linda Ellingburg in Springfield on January 27, 1977.
Ernest worked as a mill worker and heavy equipment operator for Stone Forest Products.  He loved fishing, hunting and playing chess.  Ernest also was the captain of a pool team in Springfield. 
Ernest is survived by his spouse, Linda; daughters, Linda McMullen of South Carolina, Juanita Vensen of Alaska, Lawana Durand of Ohio, Rose Buckholz, Christina Lattymer, Leona Lattymer, and Mary Lattymer, all of Springfield; son, Ernest Jamie Lattymer of Springfield; sisters, Clara Lattymer of Prairie City, Cleo Larkin of North Powder, and Gene Hanlon of West Fir; 26 grandchildren and 4 great-grandchildren.  
A memorial service will be held at a later date.
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home of Springfield.

Donald L. James passed away peacefully at home on March 20, 2013. He was born June 17, 1917 to Kirk & Grace James, in Alpine, Washington. Don grew up in Everett, Washington and graduated from Everett High School in 1936. It was in high school Don discovered his skill in tennis and his love for the sport. In 1943 he married Mary Cahill and they had one son, Bob. Don worked for the Burlington Northern Railroad for 38 years, until he retired in 1981. In 1975, Don married Jean Weese. Don had a deep faith and was a longtime member of Living Grace Christian Fellowship Church. An avid tennis player, Don enjoyed playing at the YMCA several times a week until the age of 94!
Don loved people! He had a warm ready smile for all, a twinkle in his eye and a great sense of humor. He will be greatly missed by many people whose lives are richer for having known him. 
Don is survived by his loving wife, Jean. Also mourning his passing are grandchildren, Joanna (Mike) Penney, Annita (Steve) Brown, Bryce James, Doyle James, Jean's daughter, Linda Roth and son, David Weese, several grandchildren and great-grandchildren. Don was preceeded in death by his son, Bob James. 
A memorial of Don's life will be held on Saturday, April 13th at 1:30, at the Asbury Methodist Church, 1090 Berntzen, Eugene.

Wayve O'Neal Denny died on march 26, 2013 in Eugene, Oregon at the age of 88 due to comlications fro a stroke. She was born to Clyde and Thelma O'Neal in Raymond, WA on December 3, 1924. She graduated from University High in 1942

Linda B. Koffman of Eugene, died March 23, 2013 at the age of 70. She was born July 13, 1942 in Valhalla, New York, to Edward & Beatrice (Paschal) Braisted. A Funeral service will be Thursday, April 4th at 11:00 A.M. at Musgrove Family Mortuary in Eugene. There will be a viewing before the service from 10:00 to 11:00. A  Burial will follow services at 2:30 at Oakhill Cemetery. 
Linda married William George Koffman on June 20, 1962 in Hartsdale, New York. She worked for San Gabriel Community Hospital, which is now San Gabriel Valley Medical Center as a LVN from 1964 to 1984. Then she worked at Sacred Heart Medical Center as an LPN for 20 years until she retired in 2004.
She loved genealogy, camping, gardening, doing water aerobics, enjoyed cooking, traveling and cherished time spent with her family. She was a very giving person and put others before herself. She was a traditional, strong and courageous woman. 
She is survived by her daughters, Sharon L Koffman-Hampton of Huntington Beach, CA. and Jacqueline S. Koffman of Eugene, OR., five grandchildren, Jordan, Dylan, Noah, William and Kirsten. 
She was preceeded in death by her husband, William and two sisters, Carolyn and Mary and a brother, Edward.

Stanley Stennis Ottinger, Jr, 38, died in his sleep at home on March 25, 2013 after a nearly 5 year battle with soft tissue sarcoma.   Stanley’s beloved cat, “Mama”, died just hours later.  Stanley loved playing billiards and in 2012 he won the Open “A” regionals becoming a Master which won him a birth to the Nationals in Las Vegas.  
Stanley lived a colorful life, and his battle with cancer made him a better person.  After the initial failure of traditional western medicine to treat his illness, Stanley became a true and unabashed believer in holistic and natural medicine which he believed prolonged his life.  Family and friends witnessed how strongly Stan fought his illness and admired him for that.  For the past two years, Stanley and his wife, Cheri, lived with her parents Jaime and Jody Wearin on the family farm on the McKenzie River.  Stanley enjoyed helping on the farm, growing an organic garden, raising chickens and goats.
Stanley worked construction for most of his life and liked helping others, fishing, animals, cartoons, and was the ultimate Star Wars “Yoda” fan. During Stanley’s illness he found comfort from his wife, family, friends, God, and Bach’s “Cello Suites.”
Stanley touched many peoples’ lives and leaves behind many family and friends who loved and will miss him including his wife, Cheri Wearin of Springfield, mother Gayle Lynn Sandoval of Santa Maria California, father Stanley  S. Ottinger, Sr (Tami) of Springfield, sister Kellie Ottinger of Springfield, sister Melissa Miller (Rob) of Santa Maria, California, daughter Annie Lynn Lenore Glenn living with her adoptive parents and brother in Forest Grove, and brother-in-law Jason Wearin (Jennifer).  
Stanley adored his nieces and nephews: Nathan, Isabella, Danielle, Marcus, Daxton, Brodie, Jacob, and Jordyn.
Stanley was born on March 13, 1975 in Redlands, California, and lived in Colorado and Oregon.  He graduated from Thurston High School in 1993.  In lieu of flowers, Stanley would have wanted others to have been helped, so please consider a donation to your local homeless shelter or animal shelter.
A celebration of life will be held on May 4th with more details to follow. 
Arrangements by Sunset Hills Cemetery, Funeral Home & Crematorium, Eugene OR.

Harlin E. “Dutch” Schlosser died March 27, 2013 at 80 years old due to age related causes. He was born July 21, 1932 in McPherson County, South Dakota to Rudolph and Hilda (Neiffer) Schlosser. 
A Memorial Service is planned for 11:00 AM Saturday, April 6, 2013 at West Lawn Memorial Park Chapel, 225 S. Danebo Avenue, Eugene, OR 97402. A private inurnment will be at a later date. 
Harlin was born and raised on the family farm near Frederick, South Dakota. Harlin served in the US Army during the Korean conflict where he was stationed in Germany building bridges. After the military, Harlin moved to Los Angeles, California where he married Marcella Lopez. The family relocated to Junction City, Oregon in 1963. Harlin and Marcella later divorced.
Harlin met Patricia Ann Brenden in 1968 and they were married on April 19, 1969.
While in Southern California, Harlin worked at Northrup where he helped build the feet for the Apollo landing craft which later landed on the moon in 1969. After moving to Oregon he worked as a Heavy Equipment Mechanic and retired from Delta Sand & Gravel in 1992.
His passion in his retirement years was restoring vintage era John Deere tractors. He enjoyed bowling, fishing and camping and was a member of the Eugene Eagles Lodge. 

Harlin is survived by:
His Wife of 44 years Pat, Daughters Mary Engel and Kathy Schlosser (Husband Robert Atkins) of Sacramento CA; Sons Wallace St. Julian (Wife Teri) of Eugene OR, Anthony St. Julian of Sacramento CA, Eddie Schlosser (Wife Jill) of Eugene OR and Mike Schlosser (Wife Joesette) of Springfield OR; Brothers Harvin Schlosser of Westport SD, Vern Schlosser of Frederick SD, Gene Schlosser of Aberdeen SD and Bill Schlosser of Bath SD; Sisters Evelyn Olson and Shirley Wagemann of Aberdeen SD, Mary Jensen of Duluth Minnesota and Loraine Dorman of Carson CA; Grandchildren Raina Banuelos, Savannah St. Julian and Ryan Atkins of Sacramento CA, Jocelin Engel of Queens NY, Janessa Schlosser, Wally St. Julian lll, Pam St. Julian, Alex St. Julian, Tisha Feeley and Lyndy Feeley of Eugene OR; Great Grandchildren Austin and Elissa St. Julian of Vancouver Washington and (34) Nieces and Nephews.

Harlin was preceded in death by his son Joseph, Parents Rudolph and Hilda, Brother Delbert and Sister Joyce.

On March 23, 2013, Teri D. Tomlinson succumbed to a sudden illness. She was comforted in her final days and hours with her friends Bev and Kevin, Gordon and her neighbors. Her vivacious personality will be missed by her friends and family.

In lieu of flowers, please consider a contribution to your local food bank.

Ethel L. Fleetwood, 92 of Springfield, died March 23, 2013. A visitation will be held at 12:00pm, Saturday, March 30, 2013 at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home. The funeral service will follow at 2:00pm at the funeral home.
She was born January 21, 1921 in Corning, Arkansas to Willis and Javanda (Satterfield) McKinney. She married Donnie Allen Fleetwood April 10, 1937. He passed away October 26, 1995. 
Ethel loved gardening, quilting and sewing.
She is survived by two sons, David Fleetwood of Pinellas Park, Florida and Joseph Fleetwood of Springfield; three daughters, Glenda Noble of Springfield, Patricia Brown of Florence, and Barbara Merigis of Rainier, Oregon; eleven grandchildren, twenty-four great-grandchildren and six great-great-grandchildren.
Burial will be at Springfield Memorial Gardens.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Peter Paul Eberle died Sunday, March 24, 2013.  Pete married Kathie while working on the Alaskan Pipe Line as a Metallurgy Engineer. Pete's son, Jonathon, still lives in Alaska. Pete was an avid sports fan, an outdoorsman, and he loved C & W music, but most of all he enjoyed meeting with and talking to his friends at the Blind Pig Tavern. 

Pete is survived by Jonathon and siblings Rich, Lil, Roy, Dave, Dan, Anna, Joe and Eva.

Homer D. Rose of Springfield died March 26, 2013 at age 87. He was born to Richard and Emma Rose Jan. 18, 1926 in Antlers, Oklahoma. Homer served in the Navy. He married Francis James in Myrtle Pointe, Or. 1949. He is survived by his daughter Carolyn Eden of Junction City. He is preceded in death by his wife Francis and two daughters LaWanda and Gloria Jean. A private burial will be held at Mt. Vernon Cemetery. Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield is in charge of arrangements.

Sandra was a wonderful wife and mother, and the creative core of her family. She loved to walk along the Delta Ponds, taking pictures of the birds and was a supporter of the local "Raptor Center." She was a pubished fabric artist/quilter, who based her work on animal and nature themes. Sandra was a social person, leading Girl Scouts, attending church, joining quilting groups and teaching art classes. 
Born in Salem, Oregon and raised on the Oregon Coast, she honeymooned in Alaska with husband, James L. Soleim and set down family roots in both states, plus South Dakota. She loved long walks on the beach, Pacific Northwest Art, reading and gathering supplies for her art projects. View her work at storiesincloth.wordpress.com. She is survived by her two children, Shade Nelson and James Soleim. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Ruth Margaret Relyea died March 25, 2013 at the age of 92 of age related causes. She was born March 4, 1921 in Curtin, OR to James & Ella (Clinefelter) Wilhelm. 
A Private Graveside service is planed for Tuesday, April 2nd at Walton Cemetery. 
Throughout Ruth's life she worked as a cook and in bakeries. She loved spending time with her family, gardening, fishing & she enjoyed her time traveling in Europe & the U.S. 
She is survived by her daughters, Dixie Willcut of Springfield, OR and Linda Goodman of Oronogo, MO. Ten grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.
She was preceeded in death by her parents, James & Ella Wilhelm; two brothers, Harold & Carl Wilhelm and a sister, Helen Sherman. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Margaret (Marge) Krewski
Jan. 1, 1922 – March 23, 2013

Margaret Nina Teresa Desmarais Murray Krewski passed away peacefully March 23rd  at the age of 91 after complications from a fall.  She was the oldest of 14 children born in Manchester, New Hampshire to French immigrants Arthur Desmarais and Marie Antionette La Porte; later she was adopted by William Murray Sr.  

Marge grew up during the depression, attending Catholic school, helping raise her siblings while working 3 jobs.  She ended up falling head over heels for a full blooded Pollack, Edmund Krewski and married after high school graduation.  Two daughters were born, Carolyn in 1942 and Sandra in 1944.  While Ed was in the army, she kept a home, raised her children and loved to cook, sew and garden.  When he left the service he took a job at the Portsmouth naval shipyards as a welder and then for health reasons was transferred to the San Diego naval shipyards in 1956.  They sold their home close to the beach, bought a travel trailer, sold most of their belongings and drove across country, landing in Imperial Beach, California where they lived for 2 years.

Together they found a house in Spring Valley, CA and had another daughter, Jerrilynn in 1959.  Marge made wonderful lifetime friends in her10 years there and volunteered for the local schools and the Girl Scouts.  To earn spending money she did housekeeping for the neighbors and friends.  When Ed retired in 1969 they sold their home again, bought another travel trailer, sold their possessions and started heading towards Oregon where he could hunt and fish.  After drifting through Bend then Rogue River, they found another home in Sunny Valley, where she lived for the next 36 years.

Marge worked hard on that third of an acre, planting fruit trees, flowers, roses, berries, bulbs, anything she could get her hands on as she could make anything grow.  The rocky, hard clay soil by a year round creek was transformed over the years to a blooming, fruit bearing yard.  There she also helped raise chickens, rabbits, cats and forged more lifetime friends and extended family.  She also enjoyed going to the plays at the Shakespearean Theater in Ashland a few times every year.  

In 1974 she divorced and had to support her youngest and herself.  At 52 years of age she finally learned to drive and got her first driver’s license.  Her dream was to be a nurse someday which led her to Rogue Community College in Grants Pass where she earned a degree to become a Certified Nurse’s Assistant.  After graduation she found a job at Royal Gardens Nursing home where she loved helping the seniors while working for a wonderful owner.  There she worked for about 11 years until she retired at 65.  For health reasons in 2007 she moved to Eugene to be closer to her daughter.  Mom had been fairly secluded in Sunny Valley and missed a dear neighbor after she had passed.  Being the people person she was, upon moving to Eugene was “reborn” at Grace Manor with all her new friends.  There she enjoyed activities, volunteering her time, playing games, attending events, going shopping, enjoying music and especially being surrounded by all the people she could do things with. 

Mom was caring, compassionate, giving, appreciative, never critical and believed everyone has value even if you had to look hard to find it.  She was always encouraging and supportive even if she didn’t agree with your decisions.  She kept sewing as long as she could see and even after losing her eyesight, continued to make baby hats, sweaters and booties for Stitches from the Hearth in San Diego.  She also made children and adult hats that were donated to the Mission and local foster programs.  She made sure cards were sent to all her friends and family for every occasion and gave anything she had even when she didn’t have much to give.  She was even involved with the National Women’s Relief Corp to help Veterans, who held a special place in her heart.  

Margaret is survived by her three daughters, Carolyn Karpowicz (husband Richard) of Spring Valley, CA; Sandra Krewski of Orangeville, CA and Jerri (husband Bob) of Cheshire, OR.  She has 3 grand-children and 3 great grand-children.  There are three surviving brothers, David Murray (wife Judy) of East Bridgewater, MA, Robert Murray (wife Loretta) and William Murray Jr (wife Annette) of Nashua, NH and two surviving sisters, Delia Bergeron of Nashua, NH and Anna Nancy Duhamel of South Carolina.  Brothers and sisters of late are Richard, Joseph, Michael and Francis Murray,  Kathy Hegarty and Jane Bonnette and two children who didn’t survive birth.  

Our mother will be truly missed by all her family and dear friends.  Her kindness and generosity touched many lives.  She was a gifted sewer, making hand and machine sewn quilts, clothing and bed dolls.  She loved to crochet making afghans, table clothes and doilies and enjoyed knitting and embroidery as well.  Gardening, raising children, crafts and giving of her time were her passions as she moved gently through life.  But it was her strength, courage, drive, hard work, determination, strong will and can-do attitude that carried her through the rough times as there were many.  She looked death in the eye a number of times and overcame that which could have stolen her many years earlier.  

Margaret will be laid to rest next to Ed in Grants Pass, OR Friday March 29th at 10 am where there will be a short graveside service.  Saturday March 30th there will be a Celebration of her Life at Grace Manor in Eugene at 6pm.  If you attend either please honor her memory by wearing her favorite colors of purple, blue, pink or anything having a floral design.  Contributions can be made in her honor to Meals on Wheels and Greenhill Humane Society of Eugene, OR.  

Mom, we miss you so much already.  You’ve taught us how to lead and be independent while remaining

Lorana Marie Ray passed away on March 23, 2013.  Lorana was born on March 1, 1940 to Harold Hinshaw and Esther (Hosselkus) Hinshaw in DelNorte, Colorado.   She graduated from St. Helens High School in 1958 and married James R. Ray on April 22nd, 1960, also in St. Helens.
In 1965 Lorana and Jim moved to Florence, Oregon where they lived and raised their family for 37 years.  During Lorana’s time in Florence she was a member of the Siuslaw Valley Fire Department for 24 years.  She retired from service as a Captain.  In 2002 Lorana and Jim moved to Harrisburg, Oregon to be closer to their grandkids.  Over the years she held various jobs but her proudest jobs where as a loving Housewife, Mother and Grandmother.  Lorana was a volunteer at heart.  From getting the March of Dimes Walk-A-Thon to Florence, volunteering with the Harrisburg Sports Program and supporting the youth group at the Harrisburg Christian Church where she attended.  She loved to work with ceramics, always working on something for a gift to a family member or friend.
She is survived by her husband of almost 53 years James Ray, of Harrisburg, two sons Terry (wife Kathy) and Mike (wife Mardell), also of Harrisburg, 7 grandchildren, 2 great grandchildren, 2 brothers Harold and Wayne Hinshaw, 1 sister, Linda (Hinshaw) Res and numerous nieces and nephews.  
A viewing will be held on Friday, March 29th at Musgrove Mortuary, in Junction City from 3-7pm.  A memorial to celebrate her life is scheduled for Saturday, March 30th at 10 am, at the Harrisburg Christian Church. In lieu of flowers the family asks that you make a donation to the Friends of Florence or Willamette Valley Cancer Institute in Eugene.  Condolences may be made online at www.musgroves.com.  Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home.

Richard "Steven" Brown born October 1, 1946 died March 21, 2013 due to health complications. He was born to Mary Margaret Brown and Daryl Brown. He is survived by 7 children, 28 grandchildren and 11 great grandchildren. His surviving siblings include 1 brother and 2 sisters. 

He served time as a sherriff's deputy and later moved on to become an electrician for Lane Plywood Mill Inc. where he worked for 25 years. 

Richard enjoyed the outdoors; fishing, hunting, crabbing, spending time on the Oregon Coast and going to the Lane County Fair. He also loved working in his yard. His hobbies were art and building remote Aerial Aviation planes. He enjoyed spending time with all his family and friends. 

He was a beloved father, grandfather, brother and friend who will be so dearly missed and forever in our hearts. May he be blessed by the Lord and all his grace. 

God gives us each a gift of life to cherish from our birth. He gives us friends and those we love to share our days on Earth. He watches us with loving care and takes us by the hand, He blesses us with countless joys and guides the lives we've planned. Then, when our work on Earth is done, He calls us to his side. To live with him in happiness where peace and love abide.

Ruth Ellen Huey died at age 93 on March 24, 2013. She was born on a farm near Valentine, Nebraska to Charles William Clarkson and Sara Jane Rector Clarkson on Jan 28th, 1920. She  graduated from high school in 1938 then worked as a Telephone Operator. In 1942 Ruth came to Oregon to go to bible school and graduated in 1945. She helped in a church in Washington, met and married Donald Huey Aug 7, 1946.  She then worked at Lighthouse Temple, was in charge of nursery, taught Sunday school classes, played in the orchestra, sang in the choir and was the church secretary for 15 years.  She later retired and went to Arizona during the winter for a few years and joined mobile kingdom builders (helped churches with repairs).  Ruth requested no services and will be buried with Donald Huey at Willamette National Cemetery in Portland, Oregon.  She is survived by three sons, Paul of Eugene, Oregon, Charles of Shoreline, Washington, & Mike of Fremont, California, and three grandchildren.
Arrangements By Musgrove Family Mortuary.

fields.obituary_body: Terry Toureen, 67, died on March 24, 2013 of cancer.  He was born in Bremerton, WA on July 2, 1945, to Harold and Evelyn (Alexander) Toureen. He married Lana Woody on November 27, 1969 in Cottage Grove, OR, and they were married for 43 years.  He was a self-employed contract welder who fixed heavy equipment on dirt spreads in seven western states.  He worked with Ames Construction for the final seven years in the gold mines of Nevada.  Not only was he dedicated to his work, but above all, he was a great provider.  Terry's hobbies stayed consistent with his career.  He loved riding snow mobiles and his Harley, as well as tinkering with his 1930 Model A Coupe and service truck.  He is survived by his wife, Lana; daughters, Tyran Pate and Denise Toureen, both of Cottage Grove; son, Bryan Toureen, Cottage Grove; grandson, Alex Toureen, Cottage Grove; sisters, Kaaren Toureen, Mt. Angel, OR, Shannon Dimitri, Eugene, OR, and Shelley Toureen, Florida; and 4 grandchildren, Alex, Sydney, Courtney, and Gauge.  A Celebration of Life will be held on Friday, March 29, 2013 at 1:00 p.m. at the family residence, 234 S. 11th St, Cottage Grove, OR.  Terry always said he would go from work to dead, and that he did.  Arrangements under the care of Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, Cottage Grove, OR.

Joan Grace Osuna, 86 of Eugene, OR. died Saturday, March 16th, 2013 at Sacred Heart Medical Center at RiverBend with her family by her side. She was born November 19, 1927 in Portland, Oregon to Ralph and Vernis Brown. 

Joan graduated from Vancouver High School in 1946. She married Raymond Kenneth Osuna in 1948 and moved to Eugene OR. in 1966. Joan worked as a secretary for Lane County until she retired in 1990.

To all her family and friends she will be remembered for her loyalty and dedication. 

Joan is survived by her sister Shirley Edgar from Vancouver WA., her 3 sons; Gregg, Ray and Mark Osuna from Eugene, 5 grandchildren; Jaley, Jill, Rawley, Morgan and Gabrielle, and her dog Sam. 
She was preceded in death by her daughter Shirley Ann and grandson, Tanner. 

A private celebration for family and close friends will be held.

Ethelma A. Barnes of Halsey passed away on March 23, 2013 at the age of 92.  She was born May 24, 1920 to Carl and Jessie (Goodman) Titus in Kingston, OR.  She graduated valedictorian of her class at Stayton High School.  She married Walter “Lynn” Barnes on February 11, 1939 in Stayton, OR.  Her life work was as a homemaker and farm wife.  She was survived by her husband Lynn Barnes; her sons Gerald Barnes of Junction City, OR, and Dennis Barnes of Hasley, OR; her sister Dorothy Bacon of Lincoln City, OR; her brother  Sheldon Titus of Roy, WA; 3 grandchildren, and 7 great-grandchildren.  A funeral service will be held on Friday, March 29, 2013 at 1:00 pm at Harrisburg Christian Church.  The burial will take place after the service at Alford Cemetery in Harrisburg, OR.  In lieu of flowers, there will be a memorial fund for Ethelma at Harrisburg Christian Church.  Online condolences may be made at musgroves.com.  Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home in Junction City.

Ann Stirling age 91 died in Eugene, Oregon on March 22, 2013. She was born in Dorum, Germany on June 7, 1921 to Karl & Anna (Mangels) Icken. 
A Celebration of Life is planned for Friday, April 19th at 3:00 PM at Solvang Retirement, 1202 Jacobs Dr., Eugene 97402.
Ann married Thomas George Stirling on December 15, 1961 in Corvallis, Oregon. He died February 2, 2010. 
She was a homemaker, working on her farm outside of Eugene. She had a love for animals, especially her horse's and dogs. Loved to read mystery novels, was an artist, enjoyed hiking and was an avid outdoors woman. She loved her retirement days at Solvang and enjoyed her friends and family.
She is survived by a son, Jorg Fleige of Suison City, California and many nieces and nephews. Four sister-in-laws and three brother- in-laws. One grandchild and one great grandchild. 
She was preceeded in death by her husband, Thomas.

Mary Ann Martin, 77, passed away March 18th in Eugene, Oregon. She was a long time resident of Eugene after living in California the first part of her life. She was born in Glendale, California on December 10, 1935, to Anna Laura (Mitchell) Martin and Robert Earl Martin. She leaves two sons, Kenneth Earl Johnson of Moscow, Idaho and William Emerson Shepherd of Unity Village, Missouri; sister, Kay Martin of Hemet, California and long time companion and friend, Linda Ochs of Eugene. She was preceeded in death by her brother, Marty Martin.
In high school Mary Ann was a member of the California Scholarship Federation, the National Forensic League, directed the Senior Play and was German Club President. Mary Ann was involved in the art community and women's community in Eugene. She showed her small pocket sculptures at Ruby Chasm, entered some large sculptures in the Mayor's Art Show, and had a student display of her ceramics in the U of O Fine Arts Studio. She enjoyed attending events at Mother Kali's and she wrote several letters to the editor to the Register Guard. In Grand Forks, North Dakota she taught art to mentally disabled young people in a sheltered workshop. She loved to create art and give it away. She was known for her angel paper sculptures. She loved the monthly art walks in Eugene. Mary Ann was known for her expansive vocabulary, quick wit, and wonderful smile. Although confined to a wheelchair for several years, she still loved getting out and about in her beloved Eugene. There will be no service. Memorial donations may be made to: Oregon Public Broadcasting or Habitat for Humanity.
Arrangements by Englands Eugene Memorial Chapel.
obit information here

Martin Carl Jongsma left to be with his Heavenly Father on March 19, 2013. He was born on May 25, 1934 in Artesia, California, the youngest son of Andrew and Jessie (Sterk) Jongsma and brother of Harold and Gertie (Spyksma) Jongsma. He served his country through the National Guard. On May 27, 1955 he married Evelyn Lautenbach and began their married life in the dairy business. Two daughters were born in California before they moved to Everson, Washington in 1959 where two sons followed. His spirit of adventure brought them to Sunnyside, Washington in 1973 to continue dairying. Martin continued his business ventures in telecommunications and plastic recycling when they moved to Springfield, Oregon in 1990. 
Martin’s greatest passion, after his family, was fishing and hunting and passing that love on to his children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren. The "Ducks", storytelling and hats were also high on that list.
Martin is survived by Evelyn, his wife of 58 years; children- Sharon (Rick) Morris and Johnny (Teresa Dorosh) Jongsma of Springfield and Eugene, Oregon; Karen (Albert) Don and Jerry (Kristi Brock) Jongsma of Prosser and Sunnyside, Washington; 18 grandchildren , 10 great-grandchildren and many other relatives. He is preceded in death by his parents, brother and sister.
All services are to be at Springfield Memorial Gardens and Funeral Home. Visitation hours are scheduled for Tuesday, March 26th from 4:00-7:00. The memorial service will be on Wednesday, March 27th at 1:00 with the graveside at 2:00. A luncheon will follow at 8067 Thurston Road, Springfield, OR, 97478.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Chester A. Swenson passed away peacefully on March 19th, with his loving daughters at his bedside.  He was born at home in Veneta, Oregon, Dec. 9, 1918. He was the eldest son of Roy and Grace Swenson.  He graduated from 

from Elmira High School and then attended Oregon State University studying electrical engineering for three years before leaving school to help his Dad run his mill in Swisshome, to aid  the war effort.  Chester's wife of 64

years, Irene Swenson, preceded him in death.  He is survived by his two daughters, Sharon and Sandra Swenson of Eugene, a brother Vernon Swenson  and his wife Leora of Mt. Shasta, and many nieces and nephews.

His sister, Maxine Taylor, preceded him in death.

Chester loved his daughters and enjoyed many activities with them.  He loved to listen  to one daughter play ragtime and old standards on the piano, and the other daughter play rolls on the player piano. 



Chet found great satisfaction and enjoyment raising thoroughbreds, training and racing them.  Racing horses was a family tradition that was begun by his father.  Chet and his family spent many happy days at racetracks in  

Washington, Oregon and California.  Chet liked to hunt deer, collect guns, and  search the country for old sheet music and piano rolls.

Chet was a member of the Masonic Order,  The Shriners, and he was an avid supporter of the NRA.

He will be buried on March 22nd at 1:00PM at West Lawn Memorial Park  on S. Danebo Avenue.
Arrangements entrusted to Chapel of Memories Funeral Home.

Arnold Robert Badten, 95, of Creswell, OR passed away March 20, 2013.   A Memorial will be held April 6, 2013, 2:00 PM at the Creswell Church of Christ.  Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR.

Donna June Warren passed away Feb. 15, 2013 at her home in Springfield, OR at the age of 87. She was born in Elwood, NE, to Donn Cowles and Ethel Bell Cowles in 1925.

Donna married the love of her life, Jim Warren, on Feb.21, 1943 in Norton, KS. During the course of her working life, she worked for the Oregon School of the Deaf, the Oregon Highway Dept. and an insurance agency. She also loved to cook and sew. In 1972, Jim and Donna moved to Springfield.

Donna is survived by her husband of 70 years, James; a son Michael of Veneta; a daughter, Mary Kay Johnson of Roseburg; grandsons Brandon Warren, Aaron Warren and Adam Johnson; great-grandchildren Tucker Johnson and Sammy Warren.

Mildred Finch died of natural causes at the age of 102 on March 18, 2013 in Eugene, Oregon. She was born August 16, 1910 in Clay County, Kansas and adopted by John & Bess Tidyman. 
A Celebration of Life is planned for Saturday, March 23rd. at 2:00 at the First United Methodist Church. 
Mildred held a degree in Nursing from Mt. Sinai Hospital in Chicago, Illinois. She worked as a Registered Nurse in Colorado and Wyoming until her retirement. 
She married Lester Edgett July 27, 1931 who preceeded her in death in 1987. She married Roy Finch in February of 1989 in Eugene, Oregon. 
She is survived by her daughters, Joan Doering of Eugene and Ruth Reinhart of Oklahoma City, OK. and three sons, Lester Edgett and John Edgett of Colorado and Richard Edgett of Oakridge, OR. She has 17 grandchildren and several great-great grandchildren.
She was preceeded in death by her husbands, Lester Edgett and Roy Finch and by two sons, Robert and Marvin Edgett and four grandsons.
Memorial contributions can be sent to the First United Methodist Church. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Rod was a lifelong resident of the Eugene area. He passed away on March 9, 2013 of lung cancer.
Rod graduated from Elmira High School and attended LCC as a student and later as an assistant instructor.
Rod is survived by his wife Memory Lee Toman, son Duane Toman (wife Jann) son Ken Toman (wife Diane). Precious grandchildren Kristine Lee Toman, Myles Dane Toman, brothers Clint Johnson (wife sue), Todd Johnson (wife Debra), sisters: Norma Gavick, Bekki McClintock, Dee Matteson (husband Robert). Rod was a caring person to all he met.
He had so many life interests: water/snow skiing, Charter member of the Eugene Skin Diving Club, Eugene Dune Buggy Club, Board of Directors for the Scandinavian Festival Association, Navy veteran, member of the United Lutheran Church. He worked for a Myrmo and Sons Machine Shop for many years. He owned a landscape design business for 12 years.
There will be a memorial tree planting and spreading of his ashes in the spring.

James A. (Jim) McIntyre passed away Sunday March 17, 2013 of natural causes and complications with dementia.
Born in Vancouver, B.C. in 1932, he married Carol Ann Park in Seattle Washington and moved to Eugene in 1958, they later divorced.  James was a regional representative for Lee & Wrangler Corporation selling western/work apparel throughout Oregon and the Pacific Northwest for over 40 years. He retired in 1998.
Jim’s passion was socializing & attending numerous Rodeos throughout his professional career, culminating at the National Rodeo Finals in Las Vegas each year.  
Survivors include his three sons; Gene, Brooks, (Thora) all of Salt Lake City and James “JP” (Jenny) of Springfield, 9 grandchildren and close friend Linda Gill.
A Celebration of Life will be held Saturday from 12-3 at Musgrove Family Center in Eugene.  
The family would like to thank Victoria Greene and her staff at Farmington Square for their patience and care of our dad during the last year.

Lorraine Shisler passed away from a stroke on March 9, 2013. She was born February 12, 1924 in Sheridan, Wyoming. She grew up in Roseburg, Oregon, then moved to Eugene and graduated high school from Eugene High School in 1941. She then attended the University of Oregon. 
She married Warren E. Shisler and lived in the Reedsport/Winchester Bay area for over 50 years. 
Lorraine is survived by her son's, Dale Shisler (Shirley) and Leonard Lonigan (Christine). Also her grandchildren, Lisa, Debbie, Chuck, Kathy & Molly and 12 great-grandchildren and 21 great great - grandchildren. 
She was preceeded in death by her husband, Warren and her son, Gary Shisler. 
No services are planned.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Sharon Peurach of Eugene passed away from natural causes on March 17, 2013 at the age of 74.  She was born June 20, 1938 in St. Johns Michigan to Noah and Fleita (Baker) Aiken.  Sharon received her Master’s Degree in Fine Arts.  She married John Peurach in East Lansing Michigan. John passed away in 1971.  She was a great artist and mother.
Sharon is survived by her daughter Suzy Peurach of Arlington Virginia; son Jack Peurach of San Francisco; grandchildren Jade, Rose and Mitch Peurach of San Francisco and pets Curly, Rosie and Tigger.  Sharon is preceded in death by her husband John and daughter Annie.  
In lieu of flowers contributions can be made to The Oregon Humane Society.
Musgrove Family Mortuary is taking care of all the arrangements.

JUNCTION CITY BUSINESSMAN 
LeRoy Glenn Carlson 1921-2013.  LeRoy Carlson was born in Bristol, South Dakota to Carl and Selma Carlson.  He moved with his family to Eugene in 1937 where he attended Eugene High. After graduating from the University of Oregon with a business degree, he joined the military.  He served his country as a naval officer in the pacific theatre of war during WWII. He married Ardene Wike on October 17, 1947.  In addition to his wife he is lovingly remembered by his sons, David (Flavia), Paul (Kelly) and daughter Julie (Carl), seven grandchildren, seven great grandchildren and numerous nieces & nephews.  After his military service he worked for the Eugene Equipment Co.   In 1952 he purchased Twin Oaks Building Supply in Junction City and renamed it Carlson Builders Supply.  He grew the business for 40 years, selling in 1992 to retire.  He was a lifelong member of the Lutheran Church.  He enjoyed his family and summers at Triangle Lake.   A memorial service will be held on April 13th at 1:00 pm at Shepherd of the Valley Lutheran Church, 29357 Lingo Lane, Junction City.  Memorials may be made to Shepherd of the Valley Lutheran Church or Pacific Home Health and Hospice.
