fields.obituary_body:
Michael M. Herron, 74, of Cottage Grove died on March 15.  He was born in Toledo, Ohio on April 29, 1938 to Elston and Grace (Smiley) Herron.  He graduated from Midland School in Solvang, CA, and earned some college credit.  He served in the U.S. Navy as a Photographer's Mate 2nd Class.  He married Bonnie Lee Dean on Sept. 21, 1968 in Reno, NV.  He was self-employed as a photographer, and also worked in pharmaceutical sales. Michael really loved his cat, Sidney!  He enjoyed photography, drawing, and art.  He loved airplanes and small things.  He loved his family and friends and would like them to share a glass of wine and memories.
He was a member of Toastmasters.  He is survived by his wife, Bonnie Herron of Cottage Grove.  He was preceded in death by his parents and his son, Trace Adam Herron.  Memorial contributions may be made to the Cottage Grove Humane Society.  Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel is in charge of arrangements.

Daniel Raymond Hartwig (Dale), age 81 passed away on March, 15, 2013 at his home in Crow, Oregon, from Progressive Supranucler Palsy. Dale was born on December 17, 1931 in Vida, Oregon to Charles Duncan Hartwig and Eva Matilda (Gates) Hartwig. He was the seventh child of ten.
Shortly after Dale was born his family moved several times around the state of Oregon. Dale attended grades one thru six in Gervis, Oregon and grades seven and eight at Five Rivers, Oregon. After Dale finished his freshman year at Walport High School the family moved to Crow, Oregon. Dale never finished school because he went to work logging with a cousin to help his younger siblings finish their schooling. This is when "Smith and Hartwig" Logging Co. was formed. Dale also was employed with the Lane County Sherriff's office as a Deputy and retired after 29 years of service. He also had 11 months active military service.
Dale married Bernice Marie Canaday in 1952 at Vaughn, Oregon. They were happily married for 60 years. Dale enjoyed hunting, fishing, photography, and working his land. 
Dale is survived by his wife, Bernice of Crow, Oregon, his children, Debra Hartwig of Eugene, Oregon, Linda Sledge, Daniel (Danny) Hartwig and Karen Ott all of Crow. Four of his siblings, Eveyln Carpenter of Los Angeles, CA, Robert Hartwig of Veneta, Betty Waits of Mesa, AZ , and LeRoy Hartwig of Portland, OR. Dale has seven grandchildren, John Sullivan of Monroe, OR, Travis Smith of Crow, Tami Bloom of Eugene, Kelli Weese of Florence, Jessica Hartwig of Crow, Shawn and Joe Ott both of Crow. He has six great-grand kids. Braeden Sledge, Logan and Rhianna Weese, Brogan and Amira Smith and Eli Ott.
Dale was preceded in death by his parents, Charles and Eva Hartwig, siblings, Edna Witten, Leona Everest, Clifford Hartwig, Helen Dennis, and Darlene Wooten, and three grandchildren, Brett Hartwig, Marcy Smith and Tara Smith.
A burial will be held at the Gate's Cemetery in Crow, Saturday, March 23rd at 11:00 AM, followed by a celebration of life and potluck at the Crow Grange Hall at Noon. Visitation Friday, March 22, 1:00 to 4:00, Musgrove Family Mortuary.
In lieu of flowers the family requests memorial donations be made to Cascade Health Solutions Hospice, 2650 Suzanne Way, Suite 200, Eugene, Oregon 97408.
Condolences may be left on Dale's guest book.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Marguerite Etta Maib

On March 14th 87 year old Margo passed in the arms of her daughter Erin Pelayo. Margo leaves behind Charles Maib her loving husband of 63 years, as well as her daughter and son, David, and son-in-law Salvador. She loved and was loved deeply by her two grandchildren Anna (Gabby) and Margo (Titi). 

To say Margo was a caring grandmother, mother, and wife would not do her justice. Every person that Margo met loved her joy, humor, and laughter. Through the years she gave back to her community as best she could organizing and volunteering fund raisers.  

Friends and Family will never forget this amazing women as a final prayer we say...

May the road rise to meet you 
May the wind be at your back
May the sun shine warm upon your face
May the rain fall softly on your fields, and until we meet again
May you keep safe in the gentle, loving arms of God

Final arrangements by Sunset Hills Cemetery, Funeral Home & Crematorium

Dayna Amacher passed away March 14, 2013 at the age of 75 from age related causes. She was born October 1, 1937 in Susanville, California to Don & Geraldine (Robedeau) Gott. 
A Funeral Mass will be held Thursday, March 21, 2013 at 10:00 A.M. at St. Peter Catholic Church. A viewing will be Wednesday, March 20th from 6:00 to 7:00 PM at West Lawn Memorial Park in Eugene. The Rosary will be at 7:00 PM on Wednesday following Visitation. 
Dayna graduated from St. Francis High School in Eugene, Oregon and attended classes at the University of Oregon, where she studied Geology. 
She worked for Sacred Heart Hospital in Eugene for 12 years as one of their housekeepers. 
She married Thomas J. Amacher on June 12, 1966 in Mt. Angel, Oregon. 
She was a "Rock Hound" and a member of the Obsidean club. Dayna enjoyed hiking, camping and gardening out at the ranch. She was strong in her faith and a devoted founding member of St. Peter Catholic Church.

She is survived by her husband and three son's; Tim Amacher (Katrina) of Eugene, Ben Amacher (Haven) of Eugene and Jeff Amacher (Shelley) of Springfield. Two brothers, Don Gott Jr of Eugene and Bill Gott of Texas and a sister, Diane Anthony of Eugene. 
Memorial contributions can be made to Oregon Public Broadcasting Network. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Carl Eugene Smith of Pleasant Hill, Oregon passed peacefully on March 14, 2013. Carl was born in Sedan, Kansas on July 14, 1926 to parents Carl & Viva Smith.
Carl attended Pleasant Hill High School and graduated in 1944 after 3 years. He was drafted by the US Army and served in Okinawa and Korea during WWII.  Carl’s working career started with Kimball Brothers Lumber Mill then with Bohemia Lumber Company and retired from Weyhauser in 1991.
Carl is survived by his childhood sweetheart Rose, they were married on January 30 1947 and have enjoyed 66 years of marriage. Three children, Stan and Nancy Smith of West Linn, Faye and Darrell Haberman of Fernley, NV, and Dan and Raema Smith of Pleasant Hill,  Grandchildren Ashlee, Zachary, Kyler, Aimee, Christa, Justin, Parker, Allison and 7 great grandchildren.
Carl is also survived by Brothers Paul, Albert, Larry, and sister Dola.
Carl loved his family very deeply. He enjoyed attending all of his grandchildren’s school and sporting events. For many years Carl coached youth baseball and basketball, touching the lives of many youth of Pleasant Hill. Carl enjoyed many outdoor activities and loved raising cattle on their ranch.  Carl served many years as maintenance manager for the Pleasant Hill Cemetery where he will be laid to rest. 
Carl was a member of Pleasant Hill Baptist church; his faith comforts us all in his passing. 
A memorial service will be held on Saturday, March 23 at 2:00pm in the Pleasant Hill High School Gym with refreshments following.  In lieu of flowers, please send donations to either the Pleasant Hill Baptist Church “Youth Group” or Pleasant Hill Booster Club “Baseball Program”.

A service has already been held for James Barrett, 65, of Junction City who died February 26, 2013.  He was born June 22, 1947 in Cork, Ireland to Sean and Mary White Barrett.  He married Lucy Dyche Coon on July 20, 2012 in Amity, Oregon.
James served in the Irish Army before going to work at IFI Factory and Butler Bus Tours in Ireland while he obtained a degree from the University College Cork.  Once in the U.S., he was a member of the Eugene Gleeman Choir and attended the Eugene Faith Center.  He loved to travel and sing.
James is survived by his wife, Lucy Barrett; his two sons, Declan and John Barrett; seven daughters, Caroline Littleboy, Marian, Susan and Diane Barrett and Heather, Melissa and Sarah Coon.  Three brothers, Tommy, Eddie and Stephen; eights sisters, Cathleen, Claire, Hilary, Lou, Marie, Nuala, Helena and Paula.  Nine grandchildren and two great grandchildren.  He was preceded in death by his brother Finbar and sister Sheila. 
Remembrances can be made to the Jim Barrett Memorial Account at any Wells Fargo Branch.

Ellen Camenzind was born on January 13, 1920, in Dawson, North Dakota.  She passed away March 14, 2013, in Springfield, Oregon. She is survived by 3 children, 6 grandchildren, and 5 great grandchildren.  She married her husband Carroll on November 24, 1944; he preceeded her in death in 2003.  
There will be a Memorial Service on April 6, 2013 at 11:00 a.m. at Messiah Lutheran in Eugene.  
Funeral arrangments entrusted to Lane Memorial Gardens.

EPITAPH…BELIEVE IN YOUR DREAMS
 
On March 11, 2013 at about 11pm, Gordon T. Obie went over the great divide. He was born in Hill (now Liberty) County, Montana on May 10, 1917. Place of birth was a Homesteader’s shack, in north central Montana, 28 miles north of Joplin and 3 miles south of the Canadian border. His dad Edwin Olaf Obie was Norwegian and mom Ann Rose Yoctorowic, Polish; they were both born to immigrants from the “home country ". Northern Montana was cold hardscrabble prairie, settled by those accustomed to hard, hard work and looking for adventure with a better life. Gordon's early education was a one-room schoolhouse that covered grades 1 thru 8, all taught at the same time. Transport to school was horses, a buggy or two legs. Entertainment was teasing the teacher, who was only slightly older than the students.
 
Long cold winters brought the National Geographic and other magazines, from which his desire to be an artist and travel the world was kindled.

Gordon's first business was a trap line that produced weasels, muskrats and the occasional beaver. Prior to becoming a teenager, the only town he had seen was mostly a grain elevator. Saturday night dances were held at schoolhouses and granges; it was at one of these that he met Mildred Lillian Huestis. He worked his way through high school in Joplin, 20 miles from the homestead and went on to Northern Montana State College in Havre, Montana. Mildred was working close by as a housemaid and romance soon blossomed. As a way to express his art, he began to paint signs for campus activities and small businesses around Havre. One day a circus came through town, in need of signs to be painted, they were told of Gordon's ability and low prices, so they immediately hired him for the work. While it was only a few days work, the circus saw his value and zest for life, and suggested he join them. He quickly saw the merit in the idea and told Mildred he would write her along the way. Her response was “If you’re going-I'm going " and away they went with the circus. He became the snake charmer from Borneo, she a seller of tickets, a few days later, August 6, 1937 they were married by a $2.00 Justice of Peace, in East Helena Montana. He was 20 years old, she won't say.
 
As a married couple, they decided to settle in Bozeman Montana, and their first child Gary, currently of Springfield Oregon, was born a year later. Gordon adopted sign painting as a trade and opened his shop, in the back end of a hardware store, in downtown Bozeman. A second son, former Eugene Mayor Brian Obie, was born in the fall of 1941. 
With the bombing of Pearl Harbor, the sign shop was quickly closed and the family moved to Salt Lake City Utah, as Gordon went to work in the wartime effort at the Naval Supply Depot there. While there, a third child Florene was born to complete the family.
Gordon continued to work in war industries as a pattern maker in the shipyards in Long Beach, California and then Van Port when wartime shipbuilding came to the Northwest in Vancouver, Washington. Each fall the family would return to their roots in northern Montana to help with harvest, as that was also a wartime priority. Gordon was in the line with other draftees, receiving his medical check up, the day Japan surrendered, they were all told to go home. 


Following the war, the family returned to Bozeman and Gordon reopened his business “The Obie Sign Company ". Gordon was a very driven and creative entrepreneur and for the next decade, that business grew, to the point of owning, selling and maintaining signs throughout Montana. The business was sold in1960, the same year Gordon acquired with his brother-in-law Marion Streeter two outdoor advertising companies...one in Salem, Oregon the other in Eugene. Two years later Gordon and Marion expanded the business and asked family members to join them.
 
With Gordon's leadership and a dedicated family effort, the company rapidly grew into a multi state operation. In the late sixties, he became the Chairman of the Board and decided to at last pursue his interest in Travel and Art. Throughout the next 30 years, he circled the globe six times and studied many cultures. From his residence in Sun City, Arizona, he became immersed in Mexican history and culture, living and painting in villages throughout that country.

Gordon was an accomplished artist, businessman and explorer. An advocate of the power of positive thinking, he held leadership positions in many industry activities, charitable organizations and pursued with zest his many hobbies 

He is survived by his wife Mildred of 76 years, sons Gary and Brian, brother, Laurence Obie, Eugene, OR and sister, Gillette Ritter, Bozeman, MT. He has 9 grandchildren, 26 great grandchildren, 6 great, great grandchildren. His daughter Florene an accomplished artist in her own right preceded him in death.

Many thanks to our wonderful caregivers for their care and love they gave him.  
 
A Private Family Service was held and burial at Lane Memorial Gardens in Eugene.
In Lieu of flowers please send memorial contributions to Parkinson's Disease Association.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Nora E. Willis passed away peacefully at age 90 in her home in Springfield. 
She was born in Paola, Kansas, traveled and moved to Oregon in 1947. She was a woman of many talents and enjoyed experiencing life. She was proud of her role as a Rosie the Riveter during WWII.
Nora is survived by her spouse Darrell and extended family of five generations.
A viewing will be held on Monday, March 18th at 9:00am at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home followed by a remembrance of her life at 10:00am.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Wallace “Wally” Townsend, 95, of Creswell, passed away on March 13, 2013 at his home of natural causes.  He was born on September 21, 1917 in Gardiner, Oregon.  He was one of 4 sons.  

He is survived by one daughter, Ginger Jennings of Portland, step-daughter, Harvianne DeGreave of Sun City West, Arizona; 9 grandchildren, 9 great-grandchildren and 3 great-great-grandchildren. 

A funeral service will be held at Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield at 11:00 AM on Monday March 18.

James Merle Ratterree was born September 29, 1924 in Brownsville, OR to James and Bessie (McDaniel) Ratterree. He attended Mohawk, High School. On November 11, 1943 in Marcola, OR, he married Erma E. Spicer. 
He served in the U.S. Navy during World War II in the South Pacific in the Sea Bees.
During his working life he was a truck driver, hauling heavy equipment. His pastimes were hunting, fishing, working on a family ranch and he was a great gardener. He loved horses and enjoyed riding whenever he could. 
He was a member of the Veterans of Foreign Wars, the Marcola Grange and the Springfield Elks.
He is survived by his wife Erma E. Ratterree of Marcola; a daughter Sharon Wilkins and her husband Wiley A. Wilkins; two grandchildren, Wayne Ellis of Redmond, OR and Kim Wallace of Yreka, CA; and Two great grandchildren, Duke Lance and Clancee Lance both of Marcola, OR.
A funeral followed by the burial will be held at 11:00am, Friday March 22, 2013 at Springfield Memorial Gardens and Funeral Home.
Please make donations to Sacred Heart Hospice.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Alice Andersen of Springfield, Oregon died March 10, 2013 of undetermined causes at the age of 35. There will be a Celebration of Life on Friday, March 22, 2013 at 11:00 A.M. at Musgrove Family Center with a reception following. Inurnment to follow ceremony at Mt. Calvary Cemetery, Eugene, Oregon.
Alice was born in Springfield, Oregon to John & Wali (Odziemek) Branson on March 9, 1978. 
She graduated from Thurston High School and received her Associates Degree from Lane Community College. Alice worked as a C.N.A. and was very passionate about her work. She loved crafts & spending time with her children and family and spending time at the coast. 
She is survived by her significant other, Eric Scott of Springfield, her ex-husband, David Andersen of Eugene, her parents, John & Wali Branson of Springfield, OR., A daughter, Jasmyn of Eugene and two son's, Jaxen & Gavin both of Eugene. Grandparents, Kathy Odziemek of Pocatelo, ID and Shirley Branson of Yuma, AZ. 
Memorial Contributions to Willamette Family Center or Neurofibromatosis Network. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary

Lucille Hins Nielsen, affectionately remembered as "Lucy" passed peacefully from acute ischemic colitis with her children and grandchildren at her bedside on February 23.

Lucy was born on a farm near Parkston, South Dakota on November 24, 1924 to Otto and Marie Hins.  Her parents and her younger sister, Edna Johnson, predeceased her.  Lucy's experiences as a child growing up on a farm during the Depression shaped her values and her approach to life during her adult years.

Education was integral to her life.  At a time when many farm children completed their formal education in the eighth grade, Lucy left the family farm to live with relatives and to attend high school in a nearby town.  After graduating as a salutatorian of her high school class, she attended Yankton College where she received a Bachelor of Science degree with honors in mathematics.

Following college, Lucy taught high school math and business classes in South Dakota.  Shortly after World War II ended, she married Ralph F. Cobb.  They moved to Eugene, Oregon where Ralph started a law career and they began a family.  In addition to raising four children, Lucy was an active community leader and was involved with a Junior Service League and Jaycettes.  She volunteered for United Way and the Pearl Buck Center, and served on the board of directors for the Eugene Public Library, Laurel Hill Center, and Cascade Manor.  Lucy was a member of the First Congretational Church and PEO Chapter CA for many years.

Lucy entered graduate school in her mid-forties and received a Masters of Education from the University of Oregon in 1968.  She became a counselor and math teacher at Shasta Junior High in the Bethel School District for one year, and then accepted a job with the Eugene School District as a counselor at North Eugene High School.  During the next eighteen years of her counseling career at North Eugene, Lucy served as deparment chairperson and counselor.  She was very passionate about providing students with career development possibilities.  In the midst of a busy career, she continued her own education and received her doctorate in Counseling Psychology from the University of Oregon in August, 1981.  

Upon Lucy's retirement in 1987, North Eugene High School honored her service by dedicating the Lucille H. Nielsen Career Center that continues to this day.

Lucy remarried Robert Nielsen in 1977, and they enjoyed thirty-five years of marriage prior to Robert's death in May, 2012.  During their marriage they traveled extensively throughout Europe and the United States.  One of their favorite activities was cross-country skiing at Mt. Bachelor near Bend.  They were actively involved in the lives of their grandchildren and immensely enjoyed familty gatherings at their home.

Following her retirement from the Eugene School District, Lucy established her own private career counseling practice  and also was employed as an adjunct professor at the University of Oregon and Lane Community College.  She was devoted to helping others improve their lives by making successful career transitions in midlife, and she found this period of her life to be extremely fulfilling.

Lucy was a kind and humble woman of great character and accomplishment.  She will be remembered always with great love and affection.  Surviving are her children: Barbara Stater (Bill), Nancy Webre (John), Cindy Silver (Richard), and her son, Kevin Cobb,  Lucy is also survived by her niece, Denise Weir, and her five gandsons: Brian Stater, Adam Stater, Aaron Webre, Westin Webre, and Benjamin Zoller.  Also surviving are her stepchildren: Kris Elliott (Tom), Marti Willis (Jim), and Scott Nielsen (Lorrie).

Lucy's family is appreciative of the compassion and dedication that caregivers and the staff at Cascade Manor provided her at the end of her life.

A Celebration of Life is planned for Friday, April 12 at 2 p.m. at the First Congregational Church of Eugene with a reception to follow.  In lieu of flowers, contributions may be made to the First Conregational Church or to the PEO Oregon Marguerite Scholarship Fund, in care of Rest-Haven.  Arrangements have been made by Rest-Haven.

Sue Dybens passed away peacefully surrounded by her family on 3/10/2013. She married the love of her life, Paul Dybens in 1974. She is survived by her husband Paul, of 39 years; her siblings, Dorothy, and Robert; 2 children: Kerry, of McKenzie Bridge; Sue was preceded in death by Karla Cantrell, her daughter in 2009. Sons by marriage- John Winningham, Ray Cantrell,  both of McKenzie River, OR; and 5 grandchildren and 5 great grandchildren.

Sue was the nicest person you could ever meet and always had a kind and encouraging word for everyone. She devoted her life to her family and enjoyed every minute with them-she made sure holidays were always special. She particularly enjoyed fishing and catching up with her grandchildren.

Sue worked at the Tokatee Golf Course for many years.  She loved her job on the beverage cart-so much, making many friends along the way at Tokatee.  She truly was the sweetest person-to everyone wanting a beer.
Sue will be missed by her family. In lieu of flowers, memorial contributions may be made to the Tokatee Junior Golf Program.  Services will be held privately.
We will miss you, Mom, Grandma, GG, GMA, and Gram!
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Marilyn Denise Daily Died March 10, 2013, born January 16, 1958 in Grand Rapids, MI. Survived by her mother, Patricia Daily, brother John his wife Sarah and nieces Riley and Mason and nephew Taite Daily. She got a bachelor of Arts in graphic design and working on a Masters of Divinity at Marylhursts university. Marilyn was a very active member of the Unitarian Universilist church in Eugene. A celebration of Life will be on March 24, 2013 at 3 PM at the Unitarian Universilist Church in Eugene. In liu of flowers can be made to the Unitarian Universilist Church or the American Cancer society.

Letha Frances (Frederick) Nice passed away on March 12th, 2013. She was born to Victor and Ruth (Cooper) Frederick in Gibbon, Nebraska on January 22, 1924. She moved to Oregon with her family in 1938 and graduated from Eugene High School in 1941. Letha worked as a telephone operator and a clerk at a local clothing store. 
She married Robert (Bob) Nice in 1947 and raised three children. Letha loved crafts and sewing, her hands always working on her latest project. Almost all of her creations were gifts for family and friends, including her latest tiny knit hats for newborns in the Neonatal Intensive Care Unit. 
Letha and Bob enjoyed traveling all over the United States in their motor home. She enjoyed fishing, playing horseshoes, quilting, knitting and playing cards with their many good friends. She frequently said, “Don’t invite me if you don’t mean it because I am always going to say, “Yes” to any invitation.”
Letha was preceded in death by her husband, Bob, her daughter Victoria Rae Lively, three sisters and a brother. She is survived by daughter Terri Pena (David), son Martin Nice (Alice), son-in-law Gene Lively, and sister-in-law Cle Frederick. Letha found great joy in spending time with her 5 grandchildren and 5 great grandchildren. An open house will be held in her honor Saturday March 23rd, 11-2pm, at Eugene Faith Center 1410 W. 13th Eugene, OR. 97405
Arrangements entrusted to West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home.

Corinne “Connie” Marie Charland Bienvenue      9/23/12-2/24/13
She was born September 23, 1912 in Manchester New Hampshire, the youngest of 9 children.
She attended St. Marie Catholic School where she was educated in both French and English by Nuns. Her passion and love for music started when she was very young, performing as a singer on stage in Boston with her sisters during the 1920s. Through music, she ultimately met the love her life.  Corinne married Irving C. Bienvenue in 1933, and they were married almost 50 years until his death in 1982. 
Connie was a homemaker who, as a young mother of 7, took in ironing, cared for many other children and later in life as a widow, cared for the elderly. She was very active in her Catholic Church community, an active member of the Legion of Mary, becoming the first woman Eucharistic Minister in her parish. She devoted many years in volunteering, visiting the sick in the Eugene-Springfield community and hospitals as a Eucharistic Minister until she was physically no longer able to do so. Connie was a resident of Eugene for 42 years and loved by all who met her.
Survivors include all seven children--Donald Bienvenue (Pauline), Annette Wyrick (Jim), Cecile Johnson (Mike), Paul Bienvenue, Denise Boyer (Mike Morse), Andrew Bienvenue (Karyne), and Jean Bienvenue. She is also survived by 14 grandchildren, 23 great grandchildren and 8 great, great grandchildren. 
A Rosary will be held on Saturday March 23, 2013 at 10:30am, with a mass to follow at 11am at St. Mark Catholic Church, 1760 Echo Hollow Rd, Eugene, OR 97402

fields.obituary_body:
A home funeral service was held for Dennis at his home in Cottage Grove. Dennis passed away peacefully with his family at his side on Saturday, March 9, 2013. He was 73. Survivors include his wife of 18 years, Katrina (Grossman) Thomason, sons; James, Joshua, Eric, and Jeff Thomason as well as his grandchildren Jaina & Bradley. He will also be missed by his sister Marilyn Delzer of Wenatchee, WA. 

Dennis earned his PHD in Natural Resource Management from the University of Washington in 1972, with a minor in history. He served in the US Air Force, US Army and retired from the Oregon National Guard.  Dennis saw combat in Vietnam serving three tours of duty earning a Silver Star, Bronze Star and three Purple Hearts. 

Dennis went on to work for the State of Alaska in Natural Resource management from which he retired in 1989. He taught college geography in Alaska and at Clark Community College in Vancouver, WA. 
After retirement He went back to BLM and worked as a summertime park ranger in Clay Creek, Lane County. 

He was preceded in death by his sister Sheryl.

Arvin Ray Cowger of Eugene, Oregon, passed away on Friday, March 1, 2013, due to a long battle with ALS.
Arvin was born on December 15, 1959, in Lakeview, Oregon to Robert R. and Elnora Wiggins Cowger.  He attended Sheldon High School.  He was a treating engineer at McFarland Cascade for 15 years and ended his working career at Locating, Inc.  He enjoyed fishing, hunting, sports and traveling with his friends and family while he was able.
Arvin is survived by his mother, Elnora Cowger, daughters, Jenifer Lyn Cowger, Kasondra Cowger and step-son Cory Mego.  He is also survived by his sister, Carole Nice Walker of McMinnville, OR, brothers David P. Henderson of Goldsboro, NC and Eric L. Cowger of Eugene, OR., his granddaughters Gracie Cowger and Jaya Cowger, two uncles, Leroy Wiggins of Milton-Freewater, OR, and Richard Wiggins of Boonville, MO., many nieces, nephews and cousins.  He was preceded in death by his father.
Burial will be in the IOOF Cemetery near Coburg, Oregon.

Gerald “Jerry” Sirois, 71 of Springfield, died March 10, 2013. He was born May 23, 1941 in Waterbury, CT to Gilbert and Mary Sirois. 
Jerry married Carol Turnbull October 19, 1991 in Springfield. Together they celebrated 256 months of marriage. He worked as an advisor at Lane Community College.
Jerry was one of ten children with six preceding him in death and three remaining. He is survived by many nieces and nephews.
A funeral service will be held Saturday, March 16th at 11:00am at St. Alice Catholic Church in Springfield. Remembrances may be made to Lane Community College Foundation or Greenhill Humane Society.
Arrangements entrusted to Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Deborah Lynn Halterman passed away March 10, 2013. She was 58. A memorial service will take place Wednesday March 20, 2013 at 1pm in the Musgrove Family Center. Deborah was born February 23, 1955 to William and Gail (McGuire) Plymale in Oxnard California. She was a high school graduate and attended college classes to further her career. She married Bob Halterman on August 16, 2012 in Eugene Oregon. Deborah had a love for animals of all kinds and sizes. She also loved to raise tarantulas.  She worked for Banfield Animal Hospital as one of their Customer Service Representatives for about 1.5 years. She also worked for Creswell Veterinarian Hospital for many years. 
Deborah had a knack for words, phrases and puzzles, which came out when she watched ‘Wheel of Fortune’ and ‘Jeopardy’ or beating her family at ‘Scrabble.’ She was a jewelry designer and loved growing and talking about plants and listening to Rock and Roll music. 
She is survived by her husband Bob Halterman of Eugene Or.; daughter Michelle Kessinger; sons Chris Ewens, Eric Ewens and Toshie Viloria; Step daughters Julieann Halterman and Charlene Laroux. Also surviving are her two sisters Beverly Adams; Jacki Nieman; three brothers Richard Plymale; Jim Plymale; Bob Plymale; and two grandchildren Nathali and Jarreth. She is preceded in death by her brother Bill Plymale and granddaughter Kylie. 
In lieu of flowers, memorial contributions may be made to West Coast Dog and Cat Rescue. 
Musgrove Family Mortuary is handling all of the arrangements.

Greg Zwettler, 66, died at home on March 9th.  He was surrounded by loving family and friends.  

Greg was born on January 4, 1947 in Madison, Wisconsin and moved to Eugene in 1974.  He received his undergraduate degree from the University of Wisconsin and his Master’s degree from the University of Oregon.  He was a loyal Badger, Packer, Duck and Trailblazer fan.  Greg worked in Eugene 4J as a middle and high school special education teacher for 28 years and retired 6 years ago.  After retiring he worked as a volunteer mentor for youth and became a master gardener.  He was an athlete who exercised every day of his life.  He enjoyed the outdoors in many ways, including hiking, skiing, rafting, swimming, biking and roller skiing.  His long morning walks took him through nearly every neighborhood in Eugene.  He loved to read, garden cook and travel.  Greg was known by all for his generous and kind spirit and his tolerant attitude of acceptance.  He enjoyed spending time with his family and friends, and he will be missed by all.  

Greg is survived by his wife Judy Newman, his children Rachel Wheeler and Gabe Zwettler, and  two grandchildren, Solomon and Cassidy  and  step children Sara Degler and Micah Newman two step grandchildren, Luna and Elora his son-in-law Mike Wheeler and step son and daughter -in-law Lucien Delgler and Megan Brewer, his mother Cora Zwettler and his four brothers and two sisters.  

There will be a gathering to remember and honor his life on Saturday, March 16th from 4 - 7 pm at the Unitarian Universalist Church, 1685 W 13th Ave, Eugene, OR, 97405.

Donations can be sent in his honor to:  United Way of Lane County,  
Committed Partners for Youth/Big Sister Lane County, Birth to Three or ShelterCare, or a charity of your choice.

Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Leona Turner Smith of Springfield and Eugene died March 11, 2013 of age-related causes. She was 96.
She was born November 21, 1916 in Weatherby, Missouri to Robert and Della Fitts Flanders, the second of three daughters. The family moved to Lenora, Kansas in 1926 and to Eugene, Oregon in 1933. Leona attended Eugene High School.
She married Raymond D. Turner September 18, 1937 in Eugene. They had been married 39 years when he died February 16, 1977. She married Jack Smith January 12, 1980 in Las Vegas, Nevada. He died October 22, 1996.
Leona worked for Eugene Fruit Growers, later known as Agripac Cannery, for 41 years. She took great pride in her yard, especially the rhododendrons. Leona liked to have fun and brought fun to everything she did: bowling, hunting, fishing, dancing, playing cards, sewing and crafts. She enjoyed traveling and was always ready to go. She and Jack spent many winters in Arizona and she continued after his death, driving the last trip in 2007-2008. Leona loved having family and friends at her home.
Survivors include stepchildren: Theda Tawney, Dallas, Oregon; Carole Hickman, Salado, Texas; Ray Smith, Arizona; numerous step-grandchildren and great-grandchildren. Many nieces and nephews including JoAnn Culp and Connie Tish of Eugene; Verla Kay Reed of Big Lake, Minnesota; Marion Weidman of Wichita, Kansas; Bob Diess of Crow and Bill Diess of Eugene. Leona was preceded in death by her sisters Nellie Erickson and Myrtle Diess.
No services are planned. Interment at Lane Memorial Gardens. Donations may be made to Sacred Heart Hospice.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

Kathleen Kealanohea Meredith passed peacefully at Samaritan Evergreen Hospice House in Albany on Wednesday, March 6, 2013 from complications of Diabetes at the age of 58.
Kathy was born on January 11, 1955 in Honolulu, Hawaii to Edward & Millicent Vickery. Kathy moved to Oregon in 1970 to live with her Aunt and Uncle in the Coburg area. Kathy graduated from Sheldon High School in 1972 and attended Lane Community College. She was known to family as Miss Kathy, Kathy or Aunt Tassy. She came into our lives and stayed for a lifetime because she found her place to make a difference in this world serving others. Her calling was not without sacrifice of self and she will be remembered in the days and years ahead as that person we counted on in so many ways. Kathy did not have children of her own and she made all of our children her children. In life, she worked like a man and loved like a mother. She could be out working in the harvest one minute and the next at the grocery store with a cart full of groceries and a kid or two in tow. All of these things gave a richness to her life and created purpose and self worth for her. Kathy wove herself into each of our lives and she will stay part of our family forever. 
Our family gives a special thanks to Ron Scott who was her friend and companion for the past 8 years.
She is survived by her brother, Edward Vickery of Tacoma and sister, Gretchen Killeen of Gig Harbor, WA. An aunt, Aileen Day of Eugene, OR. Cousins Robert Kragness, James Kragness, Laura Bristow & Cheryl Brost. Nieces & Nephews, Kelsey Killeen, Madison Killeen, Jordan Kragness, Mary Kragness, Ian Bristow, Andrew Bristow, Alexander Brost, Malia Brost, Carissa Rudolf , Jada Kirk & Kimberly Kline. 
A Celebration of Life will be at 1:00 PM, Sunday, March 17, 2013 at the Song Brook Community Center, 4055 Royal Avenue, in Eugene. Inurnment will take place at a later date at Oahu Cemetery in Honolulu,Hawaii. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary in Eugene. Remembrances to the Diabetes Association.

Kathleen Margaret Kane-Wilcox, 95 of Springfield, died March 8, 2013 of pneumonia. She was born April 13, 1917 in Pawnee City, Nebraska to Maude E. Mooney and Martin W. Kane, along with three sisters and two brothers. She attended Burchard High School in Nebraska, followed by 13 years of service at Chase Gardens. On May 27th, 1936, she wedded Herald S. Wilcox in Pawnee City, Nebraska (Herald passed on November 3, 2000). In 1956, Herald and Kathleen moved from Beattie, Kansas to Springfield, OR, where they lived the remainder of their lives.
Kathleen was involved with various church groups, particularly St. Alice Catholic Church in Springfield. She very much enjoyed travel and spending valuable time with her family. Kathleen is survived by her son Paul (Sharon) Wilcox (Eugene, OR), her daughter Cheryl Kane-Banke (Tucson, AZ), and youngest daughter, Karen (Dave) Druckenmiller (Louisville, KY).
Kathleen brightened the lives of 16 grandchildren, 14 great-grandchildren, and 2 great-great grandchildren. Her Irish tenacity, love and support will be remembered and missed by her family. Donations may be made to St. Vincent DePaul in her memory. 
A Rosary will be held on Thursday, March 14 at 7:00 PM at Springfield Memorial Gardens Chapel. Viewing time is 5:00 PM to 7:00 PM prior to the Rosary. Funeral Service on Friday, March 15 at 11:00 AM at St. Alice Catholic Church in Springfield, Oregon.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Former life time resident M. Lucile Koerner, 96 passed away in Portland on March 8, 2013.  She was born to True and Cleon (Morris) Partridge in Seattle on December 10, 1916.  Lucile was called Mabel during her youth.    She attended and graduated in 1936 from Seattle’s Roosevelt High School where she played on the girl’s basketball team; this led to a passionate love of the game.  While in Seattle she attended the University of Washington for a year or so.  
She met I. John Davies in Los Angeles when they were both working for Sears. They married on August 1, 1940.  Their children John and Mary were born in Los Angeles; another son Rick was born after a move to Eugene.
Lucile and I. John Davies were divorced in the late 1950’s.  She married Howard Dirks and divorced him several years later.  On May 7, 1976 she married Ernie Koerner, they were together until his death in April of 1980.  Ray Keen was a special friend for many years until his death.
Lucile lived and worked in Eugene for over 68 years.  She worked for the Lane County Assessor’s Office for many years until retiring in 1978.  Lucile made many close friends, co-workers, and neighbors.  She was a member of the Eagles; shot a hole in one on their course; and enjoyed their Saturday night dances.  Lucile loved pinochle and  watching U of O basketball.  
When she left Eugene in 2011 it was to be closer to her daughter in Portland.  Lucile is survived by her three children, John Davies of Seattle, WA; Mary McWilliams of Portland, OR; Rick Davies of Veneta, OR; many grand and great grandchildren; and a sister, Jane Dykgraaf of Grand Rapids, MI.

Daniel Joseph von Moos, 31, of Florence, unexpectedly passed away on March 7, 2013 at the age of 31. He was born Dec. 24, 1981 in Eugene, OR. to Steve and Susan von Moos. 
 
Daniel attended OSU and was currently studying to become an RN through Excelsior College.  He was employed at Peace Harbor Hospital and Western Lane Ambulance.  This wasn't only a job but a passion because of the enjoyment that he received working with his fellow colleagues/friends. 
 
He was passionate about working in the public care sector in which he would be following in the footsteps of his father who retired from the Eugene Fire Dept. 
 
Family was also near and dear to Daniel's heart. He spent a lot of time with his immediate family in Eugene and had a special place in his heart for his two nieces from Michigan whom he loved dearly. 
 
He recently met the love of his life, Kristina Stutz. They enjoyed spending time in Sunriver and had planned a trip to Hawaii. Kristina was usually good about taking pictures but every time they were together they were too busy laughing and enjoying each other’s company to take time out to capture the moment.
 
He is survived by his mother and father Steve and Susan von Moos, sister Michelle Johnson, brother-in-law Karry Johnson and nieces Kyra and Kayla Johnson, grandmother Harriet Davis, aunts, uncles and cousins.
 
He is proceeded in death by his grandfather’s Daniel F. Davis, Walter von Moos and grandmother Margaret von Moos.
 
A memorial service will be held at 11:00 AM Saturday March 16, 2013 at Major Family Funeral Home, 112 North A St., Springfield, OR. 
 
Memorial contributions can be made to Doernbecher Children's Hospital Leukemia/Lymphoma Foundation 1121 S.W. Salmon St. Suite 200 Portland, OR 97205

Gerald Franklin Sweet age 83, passed away on March 1, 2013 of age related causes. He was born in Taft, California to Franklin & Haidee (Kniffen) Sweet. A celebration of life will be April 28th from 3:00 to 5:00 at the Elks Lodge on 11th Street, in Eugene. An inurnment took place at West Lawn Memorial Park. 
Gerry attended California Polytechnical State University. He worked at Eugene Fastners & Supply.
He received an honorable discharge from the Army and served during the Korean Conflict.
He married Millie Stormont on February 14, 1975 in Eugene, OR., she passed away in 2008. They were married for 33 years.
He is survived by a daughter, Sharon Smith (Jerry Allen). A son, David Sweet, a step-daughter, Laurie Bressler (Rick)., two step-sons, Steve Stormont (Toni)., and Bill Stormont (Kathy). Also a brother, Hap Sweet (Bonnie). He has 3 grandchildren and 9 great-grandchildren.

The funeral will be held Saturday, March 16, 2013 at 2:00pm at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home for Eunice E. Rodden who passed away March 9, 2013 at 84 years of age.
She was born in the year of our Lord 1928 in Maysville, Oklahoma to John and Suzanna Flippo. She eloped to marry Billy J. Rodden in 1952 in Gainsville, Texas.
She was a homemaker and lifelong bowler and member of the American Bowling Congress. She had a love for many children.
She is preceded in death by her husband Billy J. Rodden and son Billy J. Rodden, Jr. Survivors include her sister Magdalene Montgomery of Pauls Valley, Oklahoma, a son Jim Rodden and daughter Vanda Hodges and her husband Scott with two grandchildren and one great-grandson.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.
Ronald Eugene Shirley Born 5-1-1957 went home on 3-9-2013. Survived by wife, 4 kids, 10 grandchildren. Service on 3-30-2013 from 12 PM to 4 PM at Life church at wayside in springfield.

Rhett A. “Rex” “Ironman” Garrick went home to be with the Lord on March 7, 2013. A Celebration Of His Life will be held on Saturday, March 16th, 11:00 AM, at Harvest Community Church, 2700 Gilham Road, Eugene. Rex’s legacy is the people he has touched with his love, generosity, kindness, wit and most important his unwavering faith. Rex loved people and loved life. He was passionate about his Oregon Ducks and an avid Seventy Sixers Fan. The best of him will live on through us and is the true measure of his life, one we shall never forget. 
Rex was born on August 13, 1942 in Hattiesburg Mississippi to Earl & Eunice Garrick. He proudly served in the US Navy beginning in 1961. He married Kelly Garrick in 1986. Rex is survived by his wife Kelly,  son Brewer and his wife Connie of Tomball, TX, son David and daughter Tricia of Grand Junction, CO and daughter Casey of Philadelphia, PA, 10 grandchildren and 4 great-grandchildren. Rex also leaves 2 sisters, Mary Walton of Hallsville, TX and Jane Brittain of Eugene. 
West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home is entrusted  with arrangements
Please sign the guest book at www.registerguard.com/legacy

Nancy L. Schreiner passed away March 1, 2013 of heart failure. Nancy was born in Eugene to Burton and Ethel Allen on Mothers’ Day, May 11, 1941. Nancy married in 1958 and raised three children. She made her career as a banker and a loan officer retiring in 2002. Nancy loved puttering around her yard, the Classical Arts, puzzles, and reading. Nancy is survived by her devoted husband John (whom she married in 1990), her mother Ethel Allen of Eugene, her three children; Michele Payne of Pleasant Hill, Michael Tentinger of Crescent, and Marian Tentinger of Springfield; two sisters; Barbara Beard and Bonnie McKee; five grandchildren and five great-grandchildren. By her request, there will be no memorial service.

Alyce Grace Miller was born in Valdez, Alaska on April 5, 1917 near the end of the Gold Rush Days.  Alyce spent her younger years between Alaska and Chehalis, Washington. She married Ira B. Miller in 1937 in Anchorage, Alaska.  They had four children.  Three Children were born in Seward, Alaska; Lynn Hoffman (deceased), Elaine Fredrickson of Sequim, Washington, and Ira (Butch) Miller of Eugene. Debbie Knapp was born in Eugene.  Debbie and Butch live on the farm that Alyce and her husband, Ira, homesteaded in 1945.

A Memorial Service will be Saturday, March 16 at the Good Shepherd Lutheran Church in Eugene at 3:00 pm, 

In lieu of flowers, the family requests donations to The Good Shepherd Lutheran Church, 85780 McBeth Road, Eugene 97405, or Sacred Heart Hospice 677 E 12th Avenue Suite N-200, Eugene.  Rest-Haven Memorial Park Funeral Home is in charge of arrangements.

Jack Gauntlett died March 6th, 2013 at his home in Creswell, Oregon, he was 74.  Born December 21, 1938 to William Wesley Gauntlett and Alice Katherine (McIntyre) Gauntlett in Toledo Oregon, Jack was raised in the Coquille/Gold Beach area of the southern Oregon Coast, graduating from Coquille High School in 1957.  Jack married Sharron Lee Parton of Newport, Oregon in 1964 and were together 21 years. They shared three sons: Greg Gauntlett, of Cheyenne WY, David Gauntlett of Taos NM, and Jason Henry Gauntlett of Asheville NC.  After working at Northwest Acceptance Corporation during the 70's, financing the booming timber industry, Jack went into business for himself in 1979 and started Alloy Trailers of Oregon, later to become Truck Trailer Sales of Eugene, and also Big Boy Toys And Accessories. Finally retiring in 2012, He was an outstanding member of the Oregon sales community with a vast network of longtime friends and clients throughout the northwest trucking industry. He was a Jaycee and also served in the Oregon National Guard.  Jack had a lifelong passion for cars and was a huge fan of racing, NHRA and NASCAR in particular. An avid collector, Jack owned countless vehicles over his life. Whether owning classics, (his favorite being Corvettes) or trading new cars, you could be certain they were always meticulously detailed. But Jack adored all motor sports, from sponsoring local stock car racing, to riding snowmobiles... He loved anything with a motor. In addition to his sons, he is survived by his brother Al Gauntlett of Portland, and three grandchildren.  A Celebration of Life will be held at Emerald Valley Resort, 600 Dale Kuni Rd, Creswell on Sunday, March 24th from 1:30-4:30pm.

Dora Mae Edwards born August 14, 1925 passed away 03/06/13 due to heart and kidney failure. Dora was a 3rd generation Oregonian born in Springfield, Oregon to Stanley & Hattie Keyes.  She married Paul Edwards in November 1944 and they had four children.
Paul Edwards was an Oregon logger for over 50 years and Dora was a stay at home mother.  Dora is survived by her sisters Virginia Darkins & Elsie Cooley, her children Lana Davis, Larry Edwards, Marvin Edwards & Dianna Bottini. 5 Grandchildren Brad, Greg, Tiffany, Nicholas & Stephanie and 4 Great Grandchildren, Gabby, Zoe, DJ & Mackenzie.  She is predeceased by her husband Paul, two sisters Hazel Laiho & Leslie Burbee & her brother Don Keyes.  
A viewing will be held at 10:00am, Monday, March 11th at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home followed by the funeral service at 2:00pm. Burial will be at Springfield Memorial Gardens following the funeral.

Roselyn Phibbs, beloved wife, mother, grandmother and daughter passed away on March 4, 2013 after a long battle with cancer.
 
Roselyn was born June 12, 1940 in Springfield, Oregon to Roald and Margaret (Wilson) Hanson. She graduated from Springfield High School in 1958 and was married to Ted Phibbs on August 23, 1959. They were married for the past 53 years and were also business partners. Rose Logging is named after her and she spent many years working as the office manager. She loved to cook. Barbeques on her beautiful patios with lots of family and friends and dinners at the cabin for the hunting gang were her specialities. She recently taught her granddaughter Josie to make homemade bread and pie crust.
 
She is survived by her husband Ted, son Tod Phibbs, daughter Shana (and Bob) Reno, grandchildren Cody and Zachary Phibbs, Josie and Justin Reno, her mother Margaret Ortis, her stepmother Signey Hanson, brothers Alex, Alfred and Albert Hanson and sister Heidi Vaughan.
 
 There will be a graveside service at Springfield Memorial Gardens on March 10, 2013 at 1:00pm followed by a celebration of life at the Walterville Grange. In lieu of flowers, please direct donations to Willamette Valley Cancer Research Center Foundation at 520 Country Club Road, Eugene, OR, 97401.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Bill Hunter of Eugene, Oregon passed away on February 27, 2013 of respiratory and kidney failure. 

Bill was born in Morton, Washington to Willard & Lois Hunter. He is survived by his wife, Tillie Hunter; daughter, Susan Barnes and son Steven Hunter; 4 grandchildren and 4 great-grandchildren. He and his wife were married for 62 years. 

Bill worked for Consolidated Freightways at various locations and came back to Eugene in 1971 to become the first manager in Eugene for Oak Harbor Freightlines until he retired in 1994. 

Bill was a member of Eugene Masonic Lodge No. 11, the Shrine Club, and Scottish Rite. He was a long time member of Shadow Hills Golf Course. Bill was a member of Barbershop singing. He was in a quartet called the “Four-Tune-Four” in Eugene in 1948. The next quartet he was in was called the “Timber Tones” in Eugene.

A memorial service will take place at the Eugene Masonic Lodge No. 11 at 2777 Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd.  (Across from the U of O football field.) on Saturday, March 9, 2013 at 2 P.M.

Funeral arrangements are with Sunset Hills Funeral Home in Eugene

Walter Eugene (Debs) Crowson was born March 1, 1915 in Stidham, Oklahoma.  He passed away February 23, 2013 from pneumonia and kidney failure.

He is survived by his children, three daughters, Judy, Pat and Cathy, three sons, Mike, Steve and Bob and numerous grandchildren, great-grandchildren and great-great-grandchildren.  He touched many lives through the years and will be missed dearly.

The family will gather at his graveside at Rest-Haven Memorial Park on March 17th at 1:00 pm

Taylor Ramsey was born Nov. 17, 1917 in Parkerville, Kansas to parents Harry H. and May Ramsey.  He is survived by his wife Millie, son Stephen (Cindy), daughter Claudia Powell (Clyde), brother Lauren Ramsey, 9 Grandchildren and 11 Great grandchildren.  He was preceded in death by his wife Frances V. Ramsey and his son David L. Ramsey.

Taylor served in the US Army during WWII and is a veteran of the D-Day invasion of Normandy on Utah Beach.  He served in Battery C of the 183rd Field Artillery Battalion.  He was awarded the Purple Heart for wounds received in action near St. Lo, France.

Following his discharge from the Army in November of 1945, Taylor became a permanent resident of Lane County.  In 1948, Taylor and Jim Waite co-founded Ramsey-Waite Company located on Franklin Blvd.  In 1953 Taylor founded United Pipe & Supply Co. Inc.  Taylor successfully ran this multi branch, multi state wholesale distribution company until his retirement in 2005.  During his career, spanning over 50 years, Taylor was known to love and care for his customers and employees at United Pipe.  Taylor never had a "Bad Day".  His favorite expression was "Keep smiling and selling".

Taylor was an active member of his community and the irrigation industry. He was Past President of the Irrigation Association (which is a national trade organization), Past President of the Eugene Chamber of Commerce, Founding member and Past president of the Eugene Emerald Rotary Club, Board member of the Sacred Heart Hospital, as well as the Eugene Water & Electric Board.

Taylor was proud of his family and friendships.  He was a staunch supporter of the Oregon Ducks, and any team where a family member was involved.  If possible Taylor never missed a game.

Because he was a Kansas farm boy at heart, Taylor would often be found on weekends tending his Black Angus cattle and Arabian Horses.  He never tired of watching the sprinklers in the field.

For years Taylor enjoyed sitting on his deck with family, friends, dog and cat enjoying the view of Fern Ridge, the lights of the city, and the distant Cascade Range.

The family suggests memorial donations in Taylor's name to either the Eugene Mission, PO Box 1149, Eugene, Or. 97440 or the Lane Blood Center, 2211 Willamette St., Eugene, Or 97405.

A Celebration of Life will be held Monday, March 18, 2013 1:30 PM at Wesley Methodist Church, 1385 Oakway Rd., Eugene, Or. 97401.  Further information can be obtained by contacting Rest-Haven Memorial Park Funeral Home 541-345-8521.

A memorial service will be held at 1 p.m. Saturday, March 9, 2013 at St. Thomas Episcopal Church, 1465 Coburg Rd. in Eugene for Rae Yvonne Paulson of Eugene, who died March 4, 2013 of age related causes surrounded by her three sons.  She was 84.

     She was born August 12, 1928, in Devil’s Lake, North Dakota to Clarence and Edna (Fifer) Schroeder.  Rae married Robert M. “Bob” Paulson on September 11, 1949 in Grand Forks, N.D.

     Rae graduated from Central High School, Grand Forks, N.D., followed by education at the University of North Dakota in Grand Forks and NMC in Havre, Montana in medical transcription on scholarship.  Following graduation, she was employed at the Grand Forks Clinic and Leigh Clinic in Grand Forks, N.D.  Rae, along with her family moved to Eugene in 1959 where she was employed with Drs. Miller, Johnston, and Maxwell, and with Drs. Serbu, Hockey, and Golden.  She was a Certified Medical Transcriptionist.

     She was a member of St Thomas Episcopal Church, a participant in the Business Women’s Class taught by the late Grace Morris, Blanche Markham Guild, AAMA, AAMT, Friends of Eugene Public Library, Mt. Pisgah Arboretum, Phi Beta Patrons, Eugene Symphony Guild, and the Eugene Country Club.  Rae enjoyed reading, sewing, gardening, golfing, and was an avid bridge player.

     Survivors include her husband, three sons, David of Brooklyn, N.Y., Daniel and John of Eugene, and four grandchildren.  She was predeceased by her elder brother, Milton of Charlotte, North Carolina.

A private family interment will take place at Rest Haven Memorial Park.

Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary

Robert Earl (Bob) Downey, age 91, passed away peacefully with family present on February 26, 2013.  Born on January 31, 1922 in Pocatello, Idaho to James Earl and Lucy Loretta (Carrico) Downey. He had nine siblings.  His mother died when Bob was two years old. He went to live with an older sister, Anna, as it was too difficult for his father to raise all ten children alone during the depression.  He grew up in Pocatello and graduated from high school there.  Bob left Pocatello when he enlisted in the Navy during World War II.  He served on a submarine rescue ship in the north Atlantic during the war.  When the war ended, he went to Bozeman, Montana and worked for his brother Bill in a dry cleaning plant.  
Bob met Donna Lee Callantine while in Bozeman and they married in 1948.  He went to a school in Arkansas to learn the dry cleaning profession and he and Donna then moved to Eugene, Oregon shortly thereafter to set up house.  They lost a son, Robert Michael, at birth in Bozeman, but welcomed a son, Randall Earl in 1951.  In Eugene, a daughter Marta Laurie was born in 1953.  Bob had an opportunity to buy his own business in 1957, which took his family to Wenatchee, Washington.  He owned and ran the Hollywood Cleaners there.  A daughter, Mary Esther (Missy) was born in 1962.  Robert and Donna were married 26 years and parted ways after selling the cleaners and returning to the Eugene area in 1973.  
It was in Eugene that Bob met Claudine (Connie) Tolleson, fell in love and married in 1976.  Connie came into the marriage with three children, Karen, Michael (Mike), and Donald (Donny), all living in the Eugene/Springfield area.  Bob and Connie moved to Mount Vernon, Washington and purchased Moonen Cleaners.  They developed a pillow cleaning business during that time and after selling the cleaners, took the pillow business on the road earning a patent on their technique and materials.  They travelled with their business into Canada, along the Pacific Coast and to Hawaii, where they purchased a condo in Kihei, Maui and began to winter there each year.  In Maui, they developed a large network of friends that have remained close to this day.  In 2009, Bob and Connie moved back to Springfield, Oregon to be closer to Connie’s children.  Bob was diagnosed with vascular dementia and moved into ElderHealth and Living, where he lived out his remaining days.  
Bob was preceded in death by his son Robert Michael, and his nine siblings. He is survived by his wife, Connie, of Springfield, and children Randall Downey, Laurie (Downey) Bornkamp, and Missy Downey (Leigh Roberts); step children Karen (Tolleson) Davis (Bill), Michael Tolleson, and Donald Tolleson (Helene); ten grandchildren and 12 great grandchildren.  
Bob was an active member of the Rotary Club, Elks Club, Lion’s Club and the Masonic Lodge.  He will be laid to rest at Pleasant Hill Cemetery in Pleasant Hill, Oregon. Services will be held on March 23, 2013 at 2pm @ Valley River A/G, 900 Robin Hood, Eugene, Oregon.  Memorial/donations may be made in his name to Boys Town, National Headquarters, 14100 Crawford St., Boys Town, Nebraska  68010 (info@boystown.org).
Many thanks to the wonderful caregivers for the care he received at ElderHealth and Living in Springfield.  We can’t thank you enough for the love and care you gave to Bob.

Maurine Levins, 93, died on March 2, 2013 of age-related causes.  She was born in Drain, OR, on April 21, 1919 to William and Mary (Krewson) Mattoon.  She married Grant S. Levins on March 21, 1936 in Drain.  They were married for 56 years.  She worked as a cook at Curtin Grade School for many years, and also worked summers at the Elkton Tree Farm.  Maurine especially loved and enjoyed her grandchildren.  She also enjoyed camping at Winchester Bay, her little dogs, and the Oregon Ducks.  She was a fan for over 70 years, and she went to all the Duck home football games in 2012 at the age of 93.  She was a member of the Sunnyvale Grange, the Drain Assembly of God, and the Duck Athletic Fund.  She is survived by her daughter, Judy Levins of Drain; 2 grandchildren, 6 great-grandchildren, and 2 great-great-grandchildren.  She was preceded in death by her husband, Grant Levins, in 1992 and her son, Bill Levins. 
A funeral will be held on Wednesday March 6, at 2:00 p.m. at Drain Assembly of God Church with burial at Drain City Cemetery.  
Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel.

Donald P. Quall of Portland, OR formerly of Eugene passed away February 28, 2013 of cancer. He graduated from Churchill High School in 1971. He served in the U.S. Navy from 1972 to 1974. He then started his career as a caregiver for Eldercare nursing home in Portland, OR. He is survived by his twin Brother Ronald Quall of Eugene, OR. A Brother Gary Quall of Longview, WA. And his mother Phyllis Quall of Eugene, OR. A Celebration of Life was held for Donald at "Our House Hospice" in Portland, OR. on February 28, 2013. 
Arrangements entrusted to West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home

On February 28th 2013 we lost our beloved Husband, Father, Grandfather, and Friend Paul Douglas “Doug” Howell in a car accident. Doug was 68 years young.  He was born in Red Mountain, California in October of 1944 to Edward and Miriam Howell.  Doug was one of seven children. He lost his first wife June Howell to cancer in 1986 and found love again in 1987. He is survived by his wife of 26 years, Tamera Howell and their children: Kirsten Ricketts, Ben Howell, Andrea Bayliss, Ryan Howard, Eric Howell, Angelique Howard and their spouses. Their seventh child Devon Howell preceded him in death. He leaves behind 14 beloved grandchildren.  He is also survived by four siblings: Tom, Jerry, Jenny, Marjorie and his father Ed. 
After working two jobs, Doug became self-employed in the salvage business.  In 1973 he started Doug Howell Enterprises and was an innovator and a pioneer in the recycling movement.  He made a career from repurposing and reutilizing many vintage buildings/structures. Many of these structures still live on today in homes and buildings throughout Lane County and Oregon.  
Doug was one of Jehovah’s Witnesses, baptized in 1961.  He loved his God Jehovah very much, and tried to be guided by Christian principles in every aspect of his life.  He was imprisoned twice in 1966 and 1967 for his Christian stand of neutrality.  He had the hope of living forever on a paradise earth, as stated in Psalms 37:11.   
Doug enjoyed travelling with his family and friends.  He was an avid diver, hiker, fisherman, and all around outdoorsman.  More than all of the travel and adventures, Doug was crazy about his grandchildren.  They gave him more enjoyment than any vacation.  
Memorial services will be held Saturday March 9 2013 at 2pm at the Kingdom Hall of Jehovah’s Witnesses in Cottage Grove.  A dinner service will follow directly after and will be held at the Dorena Grange. Arrangements in the care of Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel in Cottage Grove, OR

Pauline Wilberta Payne, 87, of Cottage Grove, OR passed away peacefully surrounded by her family into God's loving arms on February 26, 2013, of age related causes.   She was born April 6, 1925, in Cottage Grove, OR to Francis "Frank" Maxmillan and Charlotte Luella (Vanderburgh) Willis.   Pauline married James E. Payne on May 29, 1942, in Eugene, OR and they were married for 68 years.  Pauline earned an AA Degree in General Arts and a Dental Assistant Certification from Lane Community College.  She was a piano and guitar instructor, a life-long homemaker, she served on various committees, taught Sunday School and BYF at First Baptist Church.  She greatly loved and enjoyed her family, traveling, reading, music, gardening and was a member of First Baptist Church.   She is survived by her Son, Ed Payne, Bend, OR, Daughter, Charlotte Payne (Jerry Turnbaugh), Pasco, WA, Daughter, Valerie (Roger) Heegard, Cottage Grove, OR, Sisters; Orpha Hales and Barbara Watson both of Cottage Grove, OR, 3 grandchildren and 2 great-grandchildren.   She was preceded in death by her Husband, James Payne who died November 2010, and her Son, Kenneth Payne in November 2000.  A Celebration of Life will be held on March 16, 2013, 2:00 PM at the First Baptist Church, Cottage Grove, OR.  Memorial contributions may be made to the Kenneth E. Payne Memorial Scholarship Fund, COCC, Bend, OR.  Arrangments by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th Street, Cottage Grove, OR 97424.

MaryeAnn Park of Eugene, Oregon passed away February 25, 2013 of cancer. Survivors include her husband Robert Park, daughters Dana Oesch and Kimberly McDougal, son-in-law Peter Oesch, granddaughter Sophia Oesch, grandson Sebastian McDougal, and two brothers Gerald Kimmel of Carson City, Nevada and Charles Kimmel of South Carolina. 
MaryeAnn was a loving homemaker. She was a great wife, mother, grandmother and friend. She will be missed.
A memorial service will be held at Lane Memorial Funeral Home Thursday, March 7th at 2:00pm.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

MILTON STIANSON Born on October 28th, 1932. Passed away February 26, 2013 at the age of 80 years old from natural causes.

Milton was born in Summit, South Dakota to Selmer and Ethyl Stianson, he had 2 siblings, Edwin and Lola both passed on. Milton married Janet in 1956, Janet passed away 1993. He has two surviving sons, Bradley and Neal, 3 Grandchildren and 3 Great Grandchildren and his beloved Pomeranian, Bandit. Milton worked road construction here in Lane county in the 1950’s through the 1960’s before he moved to Klamath Falls, OR., where he worked for Weyhauser. He moved to Springfield, OR., in 1981. He enjoyed hunting and fishing and helping people. Milton was a man of his word, as he always said, “ All a man has is his word, and if he can’t keep that, he’s not much of a man.” He remained here in Springfield helping people and he lived a full life before his passing.

Karen Jean Clarke (Harrison) passed away at South Hills Rehab Center in Eugene, Oregon on 2/26/2013 at 1:40AM at the age of 68.
Karen is predeceased by her husband, Bert Harrison who passed away on 1/31/2013.
Karen is lovingly remembered by her son Michael Estagin and his wife Anglia of Springfield, Oregon, her son Mark Estagin and his wife Tamami of Millbrae, California, and her son Ed Estagin and his wife Joanne of Derby, Kansas.  She also is survived by her 5 grandchildren.
Karen was born on April 7, 1944. She graduated from Silverton High School in 1962. 
Karen enjoyed keeping in touch with friends and family, and playing games on her computer. 
In lieu of flowers, memorial donations may be made to Cascade Health Hospice.

Tommy Rice, 67, of Drain, OR passed away February 27, 2013.  He was born November 26, 1945, in Corcoran, CA to William Maxie and Della (Wheat) Rice.  Tommy served on the U.S.S. Yorktown in the U.S. Navy and then earned his Captains License as a commerical fisherman.  He was a Plumber for Umpqua Plumbing and was a retired fisherman.  Tommy's hobbies and interests included teaching his grandchildren the wonders of gardening, bow making, apple golf, shooting and sharing wrestling experiences.  He made sure there was a breakfast of biscuits and gravy, treats of jelly donuts, jamming with guitars and bringing coffee every morning to his wife Sandra.   No service is planned.

Kenneth Taylor of Eugene passsed away Tuesday, February 26, 2013 at the age of 82, of age related causes. 

He was born September 5, 1930, in Clackamas, Oregon to Theodore and Ann Taylor.  He married Phyllis Talley on December 10, 1950 and they moved to Eugene in 1957.

Ken worked as a service technician for A&M for 30 years.  He was a member of the Lions Club and a talented wood craftsman.

He is preceded in death by his wife,Phyllis, and survived by his brother, Carl Taylor of Nevada,  three daughters, Karen Burling, Teresa "Trish" Pierrier, and Leslie Kay Sweeney all of Eugene and six grandchildren.

If you wish to honor his memory, the family suggests donations to Hospice or Greenhill Animal Shelter.

No service is planned.  A family celebration of Ken's life will be held.

Beloved husband, father, grandfather & great-grandfather; Thomas H. Hunter of Eugene, Oregon, formerly of California, died February 25, 2013. He was born in Nevada on April 12, 1930 to John and Evelyn (Boyer) Hunter. A Funeral Mass was held in Pacific Grove, California with burial following. 
Thomas married Diane Clanin on February 17, 1956 in Las Vegas, Nevada. He served in the Air Force and was Co-Founder of Industrial Boxboard Corporation of California, Utah, Arizona & Hawaii. 
He is survived by his wife Diane of 57 years and four daughters, Jill Leach (Mike) of Pebble Beach, CA., Penni Mignano (Brian) of Tualalatin, OR., Gaye Illingworth (Mike) of Fresno, CA., and Joi McMillan (Jeff) of Newbury Park, CA. Twelve grandchildren and five great-grandchildren; Two brothers, John N. Hunter (Jodie) of Santa Barbara, CA and George D. Hunter (Judy) of Magnolia, TX. 
Many of Tom's friends in Eugene knew him fondly as "Lefty".
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.
