fields.obituary_body: Patricia (Pattie) Ann Dwyer of Eugene, OR joined the Lord on Feb. 23rd, 2013. Born Nov. 17, 1952 to Darrell & Louise Dwyer.  Survivors include her father Darrell Dwyer, brother Mike Dwyer; daughters Robin Dailey of Portland and Autumn Parks of Hollywood, FL and six grandchildren.. Celebration of life will be held at the Knights of Columbus, 1144 Charnelton Street, Eugene, Sat. March 2nd, from 3 - 6 pm. "Life began with waking up and loving my mother's face" We love you mom.

Madaline Murphy, age 71, of Eugene passed away at her home from cancer on February 22, 2013.  She was born August 22, 1941 to Jerome and Julia (Lewis) Pionk in Watertown S.D. 
She was a graduate of Webster High School in Webster S.D. On April 11, 1959 she married Allan Murphy in Grenville S.D. They shared 53 years of marriage until he passed away on June 28, 2012.
Madaline worked as a bookkeeper and accountant for close to 40 years. She enjoyed reading, being with her many friends and was active in her church.
She was a loving mother to Donna Hernandez of Talent, OR., Deborah Murphy of Yuma, AZ and David Murphy of Everett WA. She has two surviving siblings, Doris Wilkey of Watertown SD and Kenneth Snaza of Grenville SD. Madaline also leaves seven grandchildren and two great grandchildren.
A Funeral Mass will be held at St. Jude Catholic Church in Eugene on March 9 at 11:00. Arrangements entrusted to Poole- Larsen Funeral Home.

A Celebration of Life memorial is planned for a future date to honor the life of Elbert Lawrence DeLong of Eugene, Who died February 23 of congestive heart failure. He was 82. Elbert, known to friends and family as "Al" was born November 13, 1930 in Gardiner, Maine, to Bertrand and Lydia DeLong. He lived in South Gardiner, Maine, until 1951 when he joined the U.S. Air Force. His first duty station after basic training was at Fairchild Air Force Base in Spokane, Washington, where he met and married Carmella Neville in 1955. His Military duties included flight time on a B-36 reconnnaissance bomber in Washington and on Puerto Rico, underground in a silo in the Titan missle program, and he retired as an Air Traffic Controller in 1971 in Germany. Al and Carmella settled in Cottage Grove with their two children, Bruce and Libby, on his retirement. He then worked in various sales fields until his final retirement in 1995. He enjoyed his activities wit his children, grandchildren and great-grandson. His pastimes included fishing and camping, dancing, singing and playing the guitar, and listening to country music. He was a Cub Scout Leader and served as a trainer for 8 years, and was the driving force in getting the Cottage Grove BMX track built in operation. Survivors included his wife and two children, six grandchildren, a great-grandson, two brothers and several nieces and nephews. He will be missed.

John Austin Walker Cairns of Eugene, passed away on February 24, 2013 at the age of 87. He was born on October 4, 1925 to Thomas and Florence Cairns in New Ferry, England. While serving in the British Merchant Marines as a radio officer during WWII, John had a chance meeting while docked in New Orleans, LA with Patricia Ann Rinow. After a three year correspondence during WWII, John immigrated to the United States to marry Patricia to whom he had been happily wed for 64 years until his death. In 1950, John obtained his private pilot's license and from that point went on to a long and successful career as a commercial pilot for United Airlines. 
John is survived by his wife, Patricia, his two daughters; Lizabeth Laakso and Kathleen Keys, his son-in-law, Marc Laakso, three grandchildren, Alex Laakso, Brett and Holly Keys and a great-granddaughter, Lizabeth Mae Laakso. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Eleanor I. Lindamood of Eugene Or. passed away on February 23, 2013 from respiratory failure. She was 86. A memorial service will take place Friday March 1, 2013 at 2:30pm at Garden Way Retirement Home.

She was born January 5, 1927 in American Falls Idaho to Ben and Martha Neuman Isaak. Eleanor was an elegant lady who was a homemaker of three extended families. She was a devout Christian and she enjoyed entertaining friends and family. She was also an avid gardener and canner. 

Eleanor is survived by her sister Joyce Shaw; six daughters Sherry Drake of Midway Georgia; Linda Klover of Pullman Washington; Joanna Hovater; Donna Mayfield; Barbara McAlister and Rev. Diane Hooge, son John Roger Lindamood and 20 grandchildren and 45 great grandchildren.  She is preceded in death by her three husbands Elmer Moser, Don Phillips and John Lindamood. She is also preceded in death by two sons David Lindamood; David Phillips and daughter Annette Denton. 
Memorial contributions can be made to Camp Harlow.
Arrangements taken care of by Musgrove Family Mortuary

.
“Who can find a virtuous woman?  For her price is far above rubies.  Strength and honor are her clothing; and she shall rejoice in time to come …”  Proverbs 31:10

Iris Purvis Strutz of Harrisburg slipped away into God’s loving arms February 21, 2013.   Born in Turner, Oregon, to George and Nettie Mason, Iris was the youngest of three siblings, sister Pat Commons and brother  Ellis Mason.   Iris married Paul Purvis, and they owned and operated Moody Hardware Company in Harrisburg from 1952 to 1985, when they both retired.  Paul died in 1985, and in 1997, Iris married Alan Strutz and they shared her remaining years together participating in community events along with the development of the Harrisburg Area Museum.  

 Iris was one of the original members of the River Road Church of Christ in Eugene, and in later years was a member of the Harrisburg Christian Church.   She loved music, dancing, oil painting, working in the garden, and all things purple!   Iris is survived by her husband Alan Strutz, her two children, Leah Belts (Richard) and Alan Purvis (Ginger), and step children Bob Strutz (Pam) and Janice Price (Pete).  

A memorial service, open to family and friends, will be held on Sunday, March 10, 3:00 p.m., at the Harrisburg Christian Church.  The family requests that in lieu of flowers, donations be made to the Harrisburg Christian Church or the Harrisburg Area Museum.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Ronald D. Sandford of Eugene passed way 2/21/2013 of cancer. 
Survivors include sister, Eileen Karch and Brother Pete, second wife Betty, daughter Joan, husband Geary, son Larry, and wife Cindy. Step children Steve, wife Charlotte, Brenda, husband Frank. 
He will be remembered for his generosity, his outgoing personality and humor. 
No services are planned. 
Arrangements entrusted to Chapel of Memories Funeral Home.

Donald Jack King died on February 18, surrounded by family after a short period of hospice care. Don, age 90, was loved deeply by his family and was a friend to many.  He was a true gentleman, appreciated by all for his genuine warmth and sense of humor. 

Don was born in East Haven, CT on June 18, 1922. His father, Philip, was the ambitious, successful son of German immigrants. His mother, Mabel, was from a family that traced its roots back to the pre-Revolution colonies. Don was the third of their four sons. The family moved to Indianapolis in 1933, where all four brothers became Eagle Scouts. Don attended Shortridge High School, excelling in track and football. After a year of college at Butler University, he transferred to Miami University in Oxford, OH in the fall of 1941. There he majored in business administration and was a member of Sigma Chi fraternity. There, too, he met Jane Louise Stevens, the love of his life. They married on November 11, 1944, shortly before Don left for active duty with the U.S. Marine Corps. He earned the rank of Captain before leaving the service.

Don returned from active duty in the Pacific in 1945 and started his career with Pittsburgh Plate Glass in a sales position based in Columbus, OH. Daughter Jennifer Lynn King was born there in 1947. The family had moved to Springfield, OH when son Robert Philip King was born in 1950. Don put his career on hold when he was called back to active duty for service during the Korean War. Subsequently, a series of promotions led to increasing management responsibilities and family moves to Muncie, IN; Memphis, TN; Louisville, KY; Cincinnati, OH; and Pittsburgh, PA. 

Don and Jane moved to Eugene in 1984, shortly after Don's retirement from PPG Industries. They quickly settled into life in the Pacific Northwest and made many lasting friendships. They enjoyed spending time with children and grandchildren, hiking and camping, Elderhostels, travels to Europe and Australia, Duck football games, and the many cultural and arts events Eugene offers. Don was known for his creative thinking and artistic skills as a painter. He was a lifelong golfer, who had some of his best scores when he was in his 70’s. He also was an avid fan at Hayward Field track meets. 

Don was a loving father to Jennifer and Rob. He taught them the importance of striving for excellence and the value of seeing the humorous side to whatever life brings. He and Jane were great role models for how to live and enjoy life to the fullest. Married for 68 years, Don and Jane were perfect complements, spending their days together with grace and graciousness and appreciation for friends and family. They shared a sense of adventure and a joy in new experiences.

During the last year and a half of his life, Don was especially close to his tablemates at Sheldon Park—Bunky, Fred and Dr. Bob.  The family would like to express their gratitude to his caregivers and friends at Sheldon Park and the staff at Hospice of Sacred Heart. 

Don is survived by his wife, Jane; children Jennifer and Rob and Rob’s wife, Jane; grandchildren Emily, Adam (Stephanie), Sarah (James), Ben, and Dan (Anna); great grandchildren Abigail, Walter, Nathaniel, and Silas; brother Gregor; nieces and nephews, and many friends.

There will be a memorial service on Friday, March 1 at 2:00 p.m. at First Congregational Church, 1050 E. 23rd Ave., Eugene, OR 97405. The family prefers that memorial contributions be sent to the Foundation of First Congregational Church or to the Sheldon Park Employee Fund, Sheldon Park Assisted Living at 2440 Willakenzie Rd. Eugene, OR 97401,
Arrangments By Musgrove Family Mortuary.

.Wilma Gibbins 76, of Eugene, OR. passed away on Wednesday , February 20,2013. Funeral services are scheduled for March 4th at 2:00PM, 2013 at Emmaus Lutheran Church 1250 W 18th Avenue in Eugene, OR with Rev. Steve Carlson officiating. Interment will follow at 3:30PM at Lane Memorial Gardens and Funeral Home, 5300 W 11th St. Eugene, OR 97402 

Wilma was born July 16, 1936 in Hordville, NE to William and Anna (Joseph ) Meyer. She was baptized and confirmed at Immanuel Lutheran Church, Polk,NE. On November 25, 1954 she married Delbert Gibbins at St. Johns Lutheran Church Seward, NE. They moved to Eugene,OR in 1956. Wilma liked to read, travel and spend time with her family and friends.

She is survived by her children, Wanda ( Martin) Gangle, Eugene, OR, Bradley ( Cynthia) Gibbins, Springfield ,OR, and Bonita ( Mark) Vanderwall, Eugene, OR. She is also survived by 6 grandchildren, Jason ( Sierra ) Gangle, Kyle (Larissa) Gangle, Tashina and Grace Gibbins, Natasha and Marisa Vanderwall; 5 great-grandchildren, Cadence and Cassidy Gangle, Aeson and Jacob Gibbins, and Ezra Vanderwall; her sisters, Leora R Smith of Fairmont, NE and Louise Mueller of Norwood Young America, MN;  and sister-in-laws Eileen and Viola Gibbins of York, NE. She also leaves behind many nieces, nephews, and friends.

She was preceded in death by her parents; husband Delbert; brother Laverne; sister Arlene and infant sister Luella.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

fields.obituary_body: Phyllis Kautz, 90, of Cottage Grove, OR passed away Feb. 20, 2013, of cancer.  She was born on May 20, 1922, in Fessenden, North Dakota to Edward and Ida (Maixner) Scheer.  Phyllis married Harold W. Kautz, Sept. 8, 1946, in Fessenden, ND and they made their home of 62 years in Sacramento, CA.   Phyllis was a Sales Clerk for JC Penney's for 13 years and was a homemaker.  She was a volunteer for St. John's Lutheran Church and St. Luke's Lutheran Church.   She is survived by her Husband, Harold W. Kautz, Cottage Grove, OR, Daughter, Linda Stahl and Husband Michael, Cottage Grove,OR and Brother, Edward Scheer, Aberdeen, SD.  She was preceded in death by her Daughter, Elaine Monighan.  A Memorial Service will be held on March 2, 2013, 1:30 PM at the Trinity Lutheran Church, 675 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR.  Memorial contributions may be made to the Trinity Lutheran Church.  Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR 97424.

Bryce E. Chilgren of Harrisburg peacefully passed away on February 21, 2013 surrounded by his family. Bryce was born May 26, 1923 in Williams, Minnesota to Judge Albert and Kathryn Chilgren. He was the youngest of seven children. He served in the Army Air Force from 1942-1946. He married Virginia Hansen on May 22, 1950 in Baudette, Minnesota. He and his wife ran a private business for several years. He was also a barber in Harrisburg and worked for the city. During the 1980’s, he coached kidsports.
Bryce was an active member of his community and church. He was a wonderful, loving person and will be greatly missed by his family and friends. Bryce is survived by his wife; two daughters, LeeAnn Pratt (Fevrel) and LaVonne Chilgren; five grandchildren, Eric, Bradley (Chisa), Mark, Joelle (Colin) and Jocelyn (Terrence); nine great-grandchildren, Brendan, Aubree, Terrence, Olivia, Jaxon, Bryce, Selma , Evan and Koto.
A memorial service will be held at the Shepherd of the Valley Lutheran Church in Junction City, Oregon on Saturday, March 2nd at 2:00pm.
In lieu of flowers, memorials may be sent to VFW (Veterans of Foreign Wars) P.O. Box 121, Harrisburg, OR, 97446.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

A private family service will be held at a later date for Robert "Bob" Clark Peterson who passed away on Feb. 16, 2013 of pneumonia. He was 69. He was born on October 11, 1943 in Myrtle Point Oregon to Edwin and Clara Peterson. He worked as a master carpenter. Bob was an avid hunter and fisherman. He looked forward to his annual trek to Powers, Oregon to reunite with his fellow schoolmates. Everyone enjoyed Bob's sense of humor and free spirit, including his faithful dogs Max and charlie. Survivors include His life partner Jan Carrigan, a son Joey Peterson, three daughters Traci Clemmer, Sandi Patten and Katie Cloyd, three brothers Dan Peterson, Bill Peterson,and John Peterson and Nine grandchildren. Rememberances to Powers High Community Scholarship Fund PO box 479 Powers OR 97466 or Lions Club PO box 567 Powers, OR 97466

William “Bill “Stenstrom
Bill went to be with his Lord February 18, 2013, at home, at age 90.  His wife, Mildred, preceded him in death in 2005. He is survived by his daughters Milly and Marilee, 7 grandchildren and 8 great grandchildren.
 A retired Obstetrician, he also had many other accomplishments in his life including being a published author, past member of Doctors Without Borders, Toastmasters, Rotary International, Lane County Medical Association, AMA, Springfield Chamber of Commerce, and a licensed private pilot.
Bill was a veteran of the U.S. Navy; He served during WW 2 and Korea, with serving a period in the Philippines.  Starting as an enlisted corpsman and retiring in 1980 from the Naval Reserve with the rank of Lt. Commander. 
He was a global traveler, fisherman, photographer, and loved to fly his family in his airplane to foreign vacations.
A celebration of Bill’s life will be held at Springfield Lutheran Church, Tuesday, Feb 26th at 12:00 noon, reception at 1:00 PM.  Committal at Greenwood Cemetery at 3:00 PM.
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield.

Della Irnese Havranek of Eugene passed away on Feb. 20, 2013 at age 92. She was born Jan. 3, 1921 to Oran and Helen (Rigney) Spencer in Aberdeen, South Dakota.
She married Emil Havranek on Sept. 28, 1942 in Chadron, NE. He passed away June 5, 2001.
Della is survived by a daughter, Winona Carlson and her husband Richard of Springfield; and a sister Velma Samson of Portland.
A visitation will be held Mon. Feb. 25, from 11 to 5pm. at Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield.
Memorial service is Saturday March 2, 2:00pm at Church of God Seventh Day in Harrisburg.
She will be buried at Willamette National Cemetery in Portland with her husband.

In Loving Memory
Doris Rose died Febuary 19, 2013 at the age of 88. 
She is survived by 4 children, 7 grandchildren, and 5 great grandchildren.

Jason Tyler Schwab age 38, died February 20, 2013 of Renal Failure. He was born December 20, 1974, in Eugene, Oregon, the son of  Richard & Kellijean Schwab. A memorial service will be at St. Mary's Episcopal Church, Saturday, February 23rd., at 2:00.
Jason graduated from South Eugene High School, class of 92'. He then graduated from Lane Community College in Computer Programming. He worked as a Technician in the computer industry. 
He enjoyed spending time with family and loved all sports, Brazilian jlu jitsu, listening to music and movies, especially 'Top Gun' and 'Rocky'. 
He is survived by, his life partner of 13 years, Alison Russom, his parents, two sister's, Jami Schwab Granston of Kirkland, WA and Holly Herbert of Eugene, OR. and three nieces, Madison, McKenzie & Sophia Granston and three nephews, Mitchell, Justin & Patrick Herbert. memorial contributions can be made to: www.seeingeyedog.org
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Deloris M. Warren died February 19, 2013 at the age of 87.  She was born March 7, 1925 in Portland, Oregon to Vail and Sarah (McAllister) Rodie.  She graduated from Willamette University in Salem.  She married Billie Etchison in 1945 in Oregon City.  They later divorced.  She married Rae Warren in 1962 in Portland.  He died October 12, 2001.  She worked as a Teller at US Bank for many years and also for Leal Oil Company in Portland.  She is survived by her son, Greg Etchison and his wife Jan of Wenatchee, Washington, three grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.  Besides her husband, she was preceded in death by a son, Jim Etchison in 2010.  A graveside service will be held at 1:00 PM on Thursday February 28, 2013 at Willamette National Cemetery in Portland.  Memorial contributions may be made in her name to the Oregon Lions Sight and Hearing Foundation.  Musgrove Family Mortuary is in charge of arrangements.  Condolences may be made on line at www.musgroves.com.

Ferba Mae (Howes) Bisbee of Springfield passed away on February 18, 2013 of congestive heart failure at the age of 86. She was born on June 20, 1926 in Moran, Texas to Lemmie Glass Caraway and Ula Mae (Carter) Caraway. She married Frank Howes in 1948 and he passed in 1980. She married Charley Bisbee in 1991 and he passed away in 2007.
She worked with her father and brother in their bakeries and worked for Davison Bakery in Eugene before working in the Eugene Cannery for 30 years.
She is survived by 3 daughters, Iona Kline of Springfield, Bobbie Emerson of LaPine and Debra Houts of Springfield and one son Terry Howes of Fall Creek. She was the grandmother of 12 and the great- grandmother of 35. She also is survived by 2 brothers, Thomas of Florida, L.G. of Louisiana and 2 sisters, Shirley of Arkansas and Nelda of Texas.
Services will be at Lane Memorial Funeral Home on Saturday, February 23, 2013 at 2:00pm. A potluck will be held at the Springfield Veterans of Foreign Wars at 4:00pm.
Donations can be made to the Victory Tabernacle in Springfield or to the Ladies Auxiliary to the Veterans of Foreign Wars Cancer Aid and Research program in Springfield where she was a Life member. She was also a member of the Women of the Moose.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

Charity Blanche Bowers
May 16, 1915—February 19, 2013

Charity Bowers, 97, of Junction City died Tuesday at Sacred Heart, River Bend Hospital in Springfield.  Born in Prineville, the 2nd of five children of Ellsworth and Lily (Wilson) Curtis, Charity lived on a homestead until she was 5 years old when her family moved to Halsey in 1920.  She and her brother rode horseback all the way to the Valley.  She attended Grasshopper Grade School and graduated from Lebanon High School in 1933.  She attended then attended beauty school.  

She married Roy Bowers in June of 1937 in Harrisburg, and together they were grass seed farmers in the Valley, running a large farming operation with their four sons for 35 years until moving to Fort Rock in 1972.  There they raised alfalfa hay and created many fond memories with their grandchildren.  They moved back to the Valley in 1978 where they retired.  Roy passed away in 1987.

Charity was a charter member and first president of Oregon Women for Ag, was a member of the Rebecca Club and of the Harrisburg Prairie Riders.

Survivors include her sons Don and  wife Lorena, and Dean and wife Myrna of Harrisburg, Paul and wife Nancy of Fort Rock, and Robert of Junction City; 15 grandchildren, 23 great grandchildren, and 1 great great grandchild.  She was preceded in death by her husband Roy; brothers Lewis, Pat, and Morris; and sister Martha.

A celebration of Charity’s life will be from 1-4 pm Sunday at the Harrisburg Museum.  Contributions may be made to the Harrisburg Fire Dept, Linn Benton Women for Ag, or the Harrisburg Museum c/o Fisher Funeral Home, 306 SW Washington St., Albany, OR 97321.  Online condolences for the family may be posted at www.fisherfuneralhome.com.

Frances M. Payne

Frances went home to be with her heavenly Father and beloved husband Marvin on February 15, 2013. Frances was born on November 04, 1923 in Corvallis, Oregon. She was next to the youngest of eight children born to Joseph and Hedwig (Steger) Rohner.

As a young woman she worked at an ice cream parlor and a photo shop. She met the love of her life, Marvin Payne, when he was in the 3 C‘s stationed at Camp Arboretum. When he returned after his service in WWII in 1946, they married. In 1950 Marvin was hired by Springfield Municipal Power and they moved to Springfield to raise a family that eventually totaled eight children.

Frances was busy during her married years being a wonderful wife, mother and active church member, and she also obtained her GED at age 54. After Marvin’s death in 1985, she became more involved with St. Alice Church as a choir member, Altar Society volunteer, Carmelite auxiliary member and member of the Willamalane choir, the Sharps and Flats. Frances enjoyed traveling, especially trips to the Oregon Coast. She took a trip to Japan by herself to visit her son Greg, who was stationed there while serving in the Air Force. Her other hobbies and joys were crossword puzzles, singing and playing the Autoharp and all things family.

Frances was predeceased by her husband, Marvin O. Payne; her parents four sisters, one brother and granddaughter Christine Payne. She is survived by children Melinda Langdon (Darrel); Michael Payne (Francine); Paul Payne (Sheryle); Timothy Payne; Angela Carmen (James Gregory); Daniel Payne (Sheila); Rebecca Bigelow (Gary) and Gregory Payne (Atsuko). She also has 10 grandchildren and 1 great-grand child. Other survivors include brother Paul Rohner; sister Hedy Peterson and numerous cousins, nieces and nephews.

She was loved by all who knew her for her friendliness, beautiful smile and steadfast faith in God. A Funeral Mass will be held on Monday, February 25 at 11 a.m. at St. Alice Catholic Church in Springfield.  In lieu of flowers contributions can be made to St. Alice Church or the Carmelite nuns.

Dick, as he has always been called, was born in Mr. Carmel, IL. To Tom Henry and Olive Irene Puryear. He and his twin sister, Ann, were the youngest of the five children in the family, though Ann never tired of reminding her twin that he was older than she was. As a young child, whenever he was asked what his name was, he answered “Dickie Poho”, a name his adult children often called him. As a teen, Dick worked at the A&P grocery store in Mr. Carmel and when not working, found time to swim in the Wabash River in his birthday suit. 
Dick served in the SeaBees during WWII and then was recalled during the Korean War. After the service, he worked as a welder for the power and electric company in Mt. Carmel. 
When his first wife died, he moved to San Diego with his son, Tome, and worked as a milk distributor and then as a plumber. Dick married Barbara in 1960 and their family grew with the addition of four daughters. 
In 1979, at the family winery (the garage) in San Diego, Dick began a hobby which became his “passion” and subsequently earned him the title of “Wine Master.” He taught many of his friends in San Diego and in Oregon how to grow and harvest the grapes and the highlight of the week was the Friday afternoon “wine tasting sessions” with his students. He planted a small vineyard on his property, which along with the fruit from the apple and pear trees, yielded vintage wines and earned ribbons at the Lane County Fair and the Newport Wine Festival. 
But Dick’s ultimate pride was his family. He is survived by Barbara, his wife of 52 years, son Tome of Kennewick, WA, daughters Juli of Belize, Central America, Marcella of Sandy Valley, NV, Pamella Gallo of Watsonville, CA and Valerie Jonas and son-in-law, Geoff of Franklin, WI, as well as 7 grandchildren and 8 great grandchildren, his sister, Ann and brother, Tom and brother-in-law, Jerry all of San Diego. 
A Memorial Mass will be celebrated on Saturday, February 23rd, at 11 AM at St. Catherine of Siena Catholic Church in Veneta.  A “celebration of life” is planned during the summer for out-of-town family and friends.

Lucille A. Bowman

July 2, 1920 - February 3, 2013


Lucille A. Bowman passed away Feb. 3, 2013 in Santa Rosa, CA., at the age of 92.

Lucille was on born on July 2, 1920 in Lorane, Oregon to James and Susie Skelton.  She lived her early childhood in the Lorane and Elkton area.  She and her family moved to Santa Clara, Oregon where she attended school.  Her favorite subject in school was basketball.  Upon finishing her schooling, Lucille attended Beauty College in Eugene, Oregon where she graduated and obtained her beautician license.  Lucille opened up her first beauty shop when she was 17 years old.  Her career as a beauty operator was to span a period of 40 years during which time she owned beauty shops in Oregon and Illinois.  


Lucille married Clifton C. Bowman on April 22, 1940, at the First Congregational Church in Eugene, Oregon.  They were married 61 years and lived the better part of their lives in Lane County, Oregon.


Survivors include her son and daughter-in-law; John (Jack) S. Bowman and Pat Bowman; four grandchildren: John C. Bowman, Mary Ann Blanchard, Tiffany Herbert and Matthew Findley; four great grandchildren: Jake Bowman, Taylor, Mackenzie and Matthew Herbert; one brother, Thomas A. Skelton.   She was preceded in death by her husband, Clifton and a grandson, Gary.


Lucille enjoyed life to the fullest.  She was an avid fisherwoman, hunter and story-teller extraordinaire.  Lucille loved family gatherings and enjoyed preparing mounds of delicious food to the delight of everyone.  After retiring as a beautician, she was very proud to be a member of the Daughters of the American Revolution.  At most family gatherings and reunions she was regarded as one of the family historians and loved by all.   


A Celebration of Life for Lucille will be held Sunday, February 17, 2013, at 03:00 PM, at the Emerald Community Fellowship (Formerly Emerald Baptist Church), located at 631 E. 19th Avenue, Eugene, Oregon.  Memorial contributions may be made to the American Heart Association in her memory.
Arrangements entrusted to West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home.

Thomas William Lane of Harrisburg, OR died February 6, 2013 of congestive heart failure at the age of 76.  He was born April 20, 1936 in Boise, ID to George O. Roger and Evelyn Blanche (Wood) Lane.  He attended elementary school in several different Idaho schools and graduated in 1954 from Mohawk High School in Marcola, Oregon, his family having moved to Oregon in 1950.  He married Nellie Prickett on June 28, 1957 in Marcola, Oregon.
  They moved to Salem where Tom had started his life-long career with Oregon Department of Forestry as a dispatcher.  In 1961 a promotion to Forest Inspector prompted a move to Gold Beach which lasted until 1968 when he became District Deputy State Forester of the Western Lane District at Veneta.  1977 brought a move to Roseburg where he served as Southern Oregon Area Director.  In 1984 he was promoted to Deputy State Forester in Salem where he served until his retirement in 1989.  During his tenure he was instrumental in the passage of the Oregon Forest Practices Act and the insurance system to cover forest fires.  After retirement he was privileged to serve the Emergency Fire Cost Committee for a number of years.
  Early years brought much enjoyment in fishing, camping, hunting, water skiing and other outdoor activities.  With the onset of his heart problems, he loved going to Reno and other casinos.  He tended his greenhouse and gardens with care, but his greatest pleasure came from his sons and grandchildren.  Watching grandchildren's athletic events was a favorite past time.
  Tom is survived by his wife of 55 years, Nellie, his four sons Thomas, Jr. (Ruth) of Pendleton; Robert of Eugene; Michael (Annette) of Oakland, OR and Douglas (Brenda) of Junction City.  His nine grandchildren Andrew of Eugene, Tyson of Oakland, Cassandra of Oakland, Matthew of Eugene, Kerri Jo of Junction City, Amanda of Eugene, Jonathan of Junction City, Daniel of Red Bluff, CA and Thomas III of Pendleton.  Also surviving are his sister, Sally Roberts of Winston and brothers Kenneth of Sweet Home and Darrell of Rainier, WA, as well as numerous nieces and nephews.
  At his request, no funeral service will be held.  A memorial service will be held at a later date.  Remembrances in his name may be made to Keep Oregon Green, P.O. Box 12365, Salem, Oregon 97309, the Oregon Forestry Museum, 2600 State Street, Salem, OR 97301, or a charity of choice.  Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home.  Online condolences may be made at www.musgroves.com.

fields.obituary_body:
Mary Lou Hanna

1931-2013

Mary Lou Hanna, 81, passed away Thursday, February 7, 2013 of cancer. She was born October 10, 1931 in Beaver, Oklahoma; the daughter of Merl & Margaret Watts. A graduate of the UO with a master’s degree in music, she taught orchestra for over 30 years. She was an active church member, elder, volunteer, gardener, and enjoyed camping and hiking with her family. Survivors include children Daniel, Margaret, and Sandra Hanna; her brother Merl Watts; and Geoffrey Wampler. Her memorial service followed by a reception will be held at 11:00 a.m., Friday, February 15, 2013 at Northwood Christian Church.

Bill E. Lewis of Springfield passed away at home on February 6, 2013 at the age of 79.  He was born in French Camp, CA.  Bill served in the US Air Force with the Strategic Air Command, then went on to dam construction and later in to property development.

Bill is survived by his wife of 56 years, Anita, daughters Cynthia Cargile, Janet Simington and Bea Anne Allaire, 6 grandchildren and 1 great grandchild.

A "Remembering Bill" celebration will be held Saturday, February 16, 2013 at 11 am at the Mohawk Community Church with lunch to follow.

Memorials can be made to Oregonians in Action, the Mohawk Community Church or Wesley United Methodist Church.
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield.

Isabel Taylor, 94, died Feb. 6 at her home in Dexter, Oregon.  She was born on Sept. 26, 1918 in Gorham, North Dakota Paul and Ann Kordon.  
She is survived by a daughter, Patricia (Laverne) Medlock of Springfield, OR; 7 grandchildren and 4 great-grandchildren.  	
She is preceded in death by her husband, Floyd, son, Wayne and daughter, Rita.
A celebration of life will be held at 1:00 PM on Tuesday Feb. 12th at the Springfield Elks Lodge. 
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home in Springfield.

Margaret Ruth Elspas Wade passed away on 2/7/13 after a brief fight with pneumonia.  She was 98.  Margaret was an independent, positive soul with a never ending sense of humor.  Margaret was a life long Eugenian.  She was born to Marshall "Red" Elspas and Nettie Fern Nestle Elspas on January 11, 1915.  She was the second of 3 children and the last to leave this world.  She graduated from Eugene High School and went on to become a cosmetician.  She owned and operated 3 hair salons; The OK Salon, The Golden Key in the Atrium Building, and The Beauty Mark in the Old Mill in Springfield.  After retiring, she fulfilled a life long dream of traveling to Europe, particularly Germany and Israel.  She was at the Berlin Wall when it was torn down.  In retirement, she also became a Senior Companion with Senior and Disabled Services.  When her vision failed and she was not able to continue as a Senior Companion, she helped initiate a telephone program, calling and checking on disabled seniors and notifying families when needed.  Her work with Senior and Disabled Services lasted 20 years.  Margaret was predeceased by her son Michael Glen Wade and is survived by her daughter Mary M. Anderson of Springfield.  She is also survived by 5 grandchildren; Mathew Michael Wade, Leah Fern Wren, Christina Ann Greer, Amy Lynn McDonald, and Andrew Delmar Greer; and by 4 great grandchildren.  "Grandma Mugs" will be missed.  

Funeral arrangements entrusted to Lane Memorial Gardens.

Celia Anderson passed away Jan. 22, 2013 at the age of 97, of age related causes. She was born Sept.27, 1915 in Pleasant Hill, Oregon, to parents, Robert F. Hoffman and Stella Mae (Sutton) Hoffman. She lived in the Eugene area most of her life. 
She and her brothers and sister grew up on a farm and attended schools in Pleasant Hill. Later she worked and lived in Eugene, where she met and married Charles 'Chuck' Anderson on July 5, 1942. Shortly thereafter, Charles joined the Army Air Corps in WWII and Celia followed him to his state side stations. She enjoyed seeing new places and had no problem finding work everywhere they went. After the war ended they returned to Eugene. They enjoyed 62 years together before Charles passed away in 2004. Celia and Chuck both loved to fish the Oregon streams and lakes and they did so for many years. Celia also enjoyed sewing, painting, gardening, arts & crafts, bible study and trips to the Oregon coast. Rock hounding along the Oregon beaches was another favorite. She was a homemaker most of her life, except for a time in real estate during the early 1960's.
She had one sister Elva and three brothers, Floyd, Paul, and John. All preceded her in death. 
Survivors are a son, Mark Anderson of Eugene and a step-son, she considered a son, Andy Anderson of Coarse Gold, CA.
The last five years she resided at Farmington Square of Eugene where she enjoyed living and meeting new people. She loved and considered the staff there as her extended family.
A Memorial Service will be held at Eugene Friends Church, 3495 W. 18th, Saturday, February 16th at 3:00 P.M. 
In lieu of flowers, contributions may be made to the Eugene Friends Church or to a favorite charity.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

On February 7, 2013 our beautiful mother, grandmother, great grandmother, great-great grandmother and friend passed away peacefully in her sleep. Viola Hedwig Madie Schenk Gilmore was born on March 13, 1913 in Sanborn, Minnesota to Anton and Soffie Schenk. She was the oldest of seven children and grew up on the family farm in Brown County, Minnesota. Vi completed the eighth grade and worked hard cooking meals, milking cows, gathering eggs and helping raise her siblings. 
On March 13, 1933, Vi married William Gilmore in Stately, Minnesota and began her adventures as a wife and mother. Bill and Vi packed up their belongings and traveled West to visit the World's Fair in San Diego, Californina. They drove up the coast and stopped along the way to find a good place to settle. The couple had two daughters, Betty and Jean. They lived in Seattle, Washington, Portland, Oregon, Boise, Idaho and McMinnville, Oregon before moving to Eugene, Oregon in 1959. Vi worked as a homemaker, as a bookkeeper at a dry cleaner and for 22 years as an Avon Representative, where she earned the highest score for numerous sales campaigns. She loved to knit, crochet, play cards, dominoes and travel. 
Vi is survied by daughter, Betty Brown, of Beaverton, Oregon. Also survived by four granddaughters; Keri Hegwood of Rock Hill, South Carolina, Sherrie Warthen (Alan) of Springfield, Oregon, Terrie McFadden (John) of Cheshire, Oregon and Julie Gellings (Ray) of Beaverton, Oregon. Vi had eight great grandchildren; Nicholas, Kortnay, Lydia, Paula, Allison, Shelley, Noah and Kelsey. She had three great-great grand children; Eli, Emily and Kamron. 
She is preceded in death by her husband, William Glen Gilmore (1997), the love of her life, and her youngest daughter, Jean Marie Allison Prince (2010).
Musgrove/Englands Mortuary is in charge of arrangements. 
Services will be held on February 23, at 11:00 at Musgrove Family Center, 1152 Olive Street, Eugene, Oregon. Private inurnment to follow at Sunset Hills Memorial Gardens.

Francis "Frank" McDonald died Feb. 6, 2013 at the age of 85.  He was born Jan. 3, 1928 in Maldan, MA  to Richard and Cathrine (Lombard) McDonald. He served in the Navy during WWII. He married Eva Kmec on May 20, 1960 in North Bergen NJ.  They came to Eugene in 1963.  He is survived by his wife and five daughters; Anna McDonald, Frances McDonald, Catherine McDonald, Alice McDonald, Margaret McDonald-Mulone, two sons-in-law, Davide Mulone and Doug Williams and 5 grandchildren.
Recitation of the Rosary, at 6:00 PM, Monday February 11 at Poole-Larsen Funeral Home with visitation beginning at 4:00 PM. The funeral Mass will be at 12:15 PM, Tuesday February 12 at St. Mary Catholic Church.

fields.obituary_body:
Joseph Allen Van Cura
January 28, 1931 - February 4, 2013
Joseph A. Van Cura of Eugene died Monday, February 4th, at Sacred Heart RiverBend in Springfield of lung cancer. 
Joe was born in Bayshore, New York on January 28, 1931, the only child of Joseph and Dorothy Van Cura. Joe graduated from East Islip Union High School in NY, where he was known as Pepi by his family and friends. He married Eileen J. Nowak in June, 1952. When the Korean War broke out, Joe enlisted in the army where he achieved the rank of corporal and served in Korea. After the war, Joe entered the meat cutting industry and started his own butcher shop in East Islip.
In 1970, Joe and his family drove across the country leaving NY and settling in Cheshire, OR where he was employed as a meat cutter at Waremart and other grocery stores in Eugene and worked there until his retirement.  Joe and Eileen divorced in 1984.  Joe remarried Christina Murphy in 1986.
His leisure time included yard work, traveling, and sports. He had an easy going demeanor and a great sense of humor.
He is survived by his wife Christina, his four children (Laura Caldwell, Joe Van Cura, Linda Tucker, and Lois Ames), step daughter (Susan Murphy),  daughter and sons in law, Janice Van Cura, Walt Tucker and Phil Ames, step daughter in law Terry Murphy, 11 grandchildren, four step grandchildren, four great grandchildren, and six step great grandchildren. One son in law, Richard Caldwell, his step son, Larry Murphy, one granddaughter and one step granddaughter preceded him in death.
He will live on in the memories and hearts of his family and friends.
Arrangements entrusted to Musgroves Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home.

Rosalie Kethcart went home to our father on February 1, 2013 at the age of 82. She was born on June 3, 1930 in Hood River, Oregon. She married her soul mate Vernon Kethcart on August 9, 1946. He died on December 7, 1985. 
Rosalie was a homemaker and loved camping, road trips, watching Nascar, reading & spending time with her grandchildren. She had a heart of gold and a kind and compassionate spirit. She had a great sense of humor and the ability to bring a smile to anyone’s face. Rosalie was a special woman and will be deeply missed by all. 
She is survived by her two daughters, Darlene Kirby of Las Vegas and Norma Haaby of Puyallup, Washington. She had 9 grandchildren and 18 great grandchildren. 
We will all miss her beautiful smile and loving embrace. 
Remembrances to The Alzheimer’s Association.
Arrangements entrusted to Musgroves Chapel of Memories Funeral Home.

Charles "Charlie" Jacobs, 91, of Creswell, OR passed away February 6, 2013 of age related causes.  He was born May 13, 1921, in Shell Lake, WI to Charles and Myrtle (Long) Jacobs.   He was in the US Army and served in World War II and was a logger for Weyerhauser.  Charlie enjoyed singing, playing guitar and the organ and loved Gene Autry.  He was a member of the Weyerhauser Retiree Breakfast Club.  He married Mary Ann Mazurek on June 25, 1941, in Pine City, MN.  Survivors include his Daughter, Charlotte Williams, Creswell, OR, Daughter, Vonda Coburn, Poteau, OK, Daughter, Dorothy Owens, Lake Tapps, WA, Half-Sister, Joan Hanacek, Trego, WI, Half-Sister, Karen Jacobs, Minneapolis, MN, Half-Sister, Linda Van Beek, Iron Mountain, MI, Half-Brothers; Bob and Art Jacobs, 13 Grandchildren, numerous Great-Grandchildren and Great-great-Grandchildren.  He was preceded in death by his wife, Mary Ann Jacobs, June 6, 2007, and Son, Richard Charles Jacobs in 2008.  No services are planned.  Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR 97424.

Juliette Warner died February 5, 2013 at the age of 82 of breast cancer. She was born April 14, 1930 to Emile & Francisca (Temboury) Crevel in Malaga, Spain. As a young teenager she lived in Orleans France, during WWII. She met her future husband, Allan Warner, while working at Stars & Stripes on the Army base he was stationed at. They married July 26, 1954 and she became a homemaker. Upon Allan's discharge in 1955 they moved to Falun, Wisconsin and in 1971 moved to the West Coast.
She is survived by her three daughters, Karen Warner of Springfield, OR, Carole Warner of Eugene, OR, Tessa Warner of Springfield, OR and a son, Gregory Warner of Huntington Beach, CA., a sister, Therese Crevel of Paris, France; ten grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
A private celebration of life will be held at a later date.
Memorial Contributions can be sent to Sacred Heart Hospice.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Dorthy Schultz passed away on February 4, 2013 at the age of 77. She was born August 18, 1935 in Twin Falls Idaho to Almus and Betty Petersen Price. Dorthy married Wayne Schultz April 3, 1959 in California. Dorothy was a homemaker.  She is survived by her two daughters Jennifer Sterling of Tacoma WA. and Dana Wagner of Eugene OR. and sister Betty Clough of Texas. A private family graveside inurnment will take place at Willamette National Cemetery in Portland OR.

Esther Ione Bailey, 90 of Springfield, died February 3, 2013 of natural causes. A celebration of life will be held from 1:00pm to 4:00pm February 16th at the Springfield Elks Lodge.
She was born October 19, 1922 in McLean, Nebraska to William and Alma (Meier) Schaefer. She moved to Oregon in 1936. Esther married Earl George Bailey December 24, 1939 in Pleasant Hill. He died December 29, 1989.
Esther graduated from Pleasant Hill High School. She moved to Veneta in 1949, where she was a homemaker and owned the Veneta Floral Shop. She moved to the Eugene/Springfield area in 1972. Esther enjoyed gardening, fishing at Siltcoos Lake, camping, traveling to the coast and spending time with her grandchildren. She was a member of Valley Methodist Church in Veneta.
Esther is survived by four sons, Eldon (Shirley) Bailey of Springfield, Erwin (Mary) Bailey of Salem, Oregon, Edward (Gloria) Bailey of Springfield, and Edgar (Cathy) Bailey of Springfield; a daughter, Ernita (David) Quick of Pleasant Hill; eighteen grandchildren; thirty great-grandchildren; and seven great-great-grandchildren.
She was preceded in death by her grandson, David C. Bishop, on January 31, 1997.
Arrangements Entrusted to Lane Memorial Funeral Home in Eugene.

Robert A Winsor passed away February 2, 2013 at the age of 73. Bob was born October 22, 1939 to Thelma and Alan Winsor. He served in the Army from 1957-1960. Bob met his wife Joan in Eugene and married in February of 1961. They resided in Eugene where he ran his own business for 25 years. They retired to La Pine and recently returned to Eugene. 

He enjoyed fishing, hunting, traveling, camping, gardening and spending time with his family and friends.

He is survived by his wife Joan, two daughters Monique (John) Souza, Denise (Gary) Tingey, brother Jim Winsor and sister Carole Harpole.  He has four grandchildren, Jeremy Dodd, Johnnie Souza and Blake and Randy Tingey. He also has two great grandsons. His sister Jo Laaksonen precedes him in death. A memorial service will be held Sunday February 10th at 1pm at the Musgrove Family Center 1152 Olive Street Eugene.

Allen Douglas Harlor, Jr, "Buz Harlor" of Eugene passed away on February 4, 2013 of metastatic bladder cancer, he was surrounded by his family. He was born on March 23, 1936 in Columbus, Ohio to Margaret Flynn Harlor and Allen Douglas Harlor, Sr. Buz attended The Ohio State University where he graduated with a M.D. and found the love of his life, Jane Bowers Harlor. They married on June 13, 1959. Buz and Jane moved to Eugene in 1966 with three kids in tow and with two more children soon to be on the way. Buz joined Island Park Pediatrics in Springfield in 1966. Around that time Buz co-created the NICU in the Eugene/Springfield Area. He then moved his Pediatric Practice to Peace Health in 1987 where he worked for 46 years, until his retirement in 2012. Buz initiated and led many local, state and national efforts in support of the advocacy for children. Dr. Buz worked tirelessly to ensure that those who did not have a voice were heard at every level. He will forever be remembered as a loving and devoted husband, father, Papa, brother, friend, mentor and physician. His incredible impact on the lives of many is immeasurable. 
Buz is survived by his "lovely lady" Jane and five children, Cynthia Sue Sjostrand, Kathleen Jane Stringfield, Elizabeth Claire Wathen, Christina Lynn VanBuskirk and Allen Douglas Harlor, III. He is also lovingly survived by 11 grandchildren as well as four sisters, Jean Thomas, Barbara Fitzgerald, Sally Myers, and Connie Magee.
The slopes of Mt. Bachelor will remain undistrurbed and the fish of the McKenzie River will remain free for another day.
A memorial service will be held at St. Mary's Episcopal Church in Eugene, Oregon at 2 p.m., February 9, 2013. 
In lieu of flowers the family ask that donations be made to: Children's Miracle Network in memory of Dr. Allen Harlor, Sacred Heart Foundation P.O. Box 10905, Eugene, OR 97401.
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Robert Bullard Jr died February 5, 2013 of age related causes at the age of 81. He was born June 16, 1931 in Minneapolis, Minnesota to Robert & Vina (Bole) Bullard. He married the love of his life, Betty on May 19, 1953 in Fairmont, Minnesota.
A Memorial Service is planned at Bethesda Lutheran Church, Sunday, February 17th.@ 3:00 P.M.  A Private Inurnment will be at West Lawn Memorial Park. 
Robert was a Certified Public Accountant and served in the U.S. Navy in the Korean War. 
He was a youth hockey referee, was involved in Rotary, was President of the Chamber of Commerce for the city of Campbell, California. He attended Our Saviors Lutheran Church in Santa Clara, CA., where he served as Treasure for over two decades; served on the church council, sang in the choir and was an adult sponsor for the youth group.
He is survived by a son, David of Eugene and two daughters, Nancy Bullard Werner of Esslingen, Germany and Claire Herbert of Santa Cruz, CA., and six grandchildren. 
He was preceeded in death by his wife Betty. 
Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

fields.obituary_body: Michael "Mike" Blomquist, 46, of Cottage Grove, OR  passed away January 29, 2013.  Mike was born November 5, 1966, in Eugene, OR to E. Philip and Carole (Spence) Blomquist.  He graduated from Cottage Grove High School in 1985.  He later attended UTI Technical Institute where he earned his certification in heating and air conditioning.  Mike worked for Marshall's Heating and Air for 27 years.  Family came first to Mike, he was a devoted father and husband.  Mike enjoyed camping, riding 4 wheelers, hiking, family vacations, spending time with his wife and children, watching his daughters sporting events and loving on his dogs.  He was a member of the Riverside Community Church of God.  Mike married Missy Graves on May 20, 1995, in Cottage Grove, OR.  He is survived by his Wife, Missy Blomquist, Daughters, Sierra and Mikaela Blomquist, Parents, Phil & Carole Blomquist, Father-in-law, Louie Graves, Brother, David Blomquist and wife Michele, Brother, Jim Blomquist, Brother-in-law, Tony Graves, all of Cottage Grove, OR and numerous Nieces, Nephews, Aunts, Uncles and Cousins.  A Funeral will be held on Friday, February 15, 2013, 2:00 PM at Riverside Community Church of God, Cottage Grove, OR followed by burial at Fir Grove Cemetery.  Memorial contributions to help with funeral expenses and daughters' future needs may be made to the Mike Blomquist Memorial Fund at US Bank, 29 North 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR  97424.

Roger Stone, 88, of Eugene, OR passed away on Jan. 26, 2013 of age related causes. He was born to Karl and Genevieve Stone in Reedsport, OR. Roger grew –up in the Eugene/Springfield area and graduated from Thurston High School. After serving in WWII and attending the U. of O. he married his high school sweetheart Patricia Shough. 
The majority of his work life was spent in retail sales. In retirement, Roger and Patty spent a good deal of time at the Oregon coast where they enjoyed salmon fishing. 
Roger was a very special husband, father and grandfather and will be greatly missed by his family. He is survived by Patty, his wife of 66 years, a sister Charlotte Rankin of LaGrande, OR, son Jeff Stone of Portland, daughter Teresa Myrmo (George) of Eugene, daughter Cheri Endicott (Lynn) of Lake Tahoe, NV, six grandchildren and eight great grandchildren. 
A Memorial Service will be held on Monday, February 18th, 2013 at 1:00 pm at West Lawn Memorial  Chapel, 225 S. Danebo Ave. Eugene, OR. 
Arrangements entrusted to Musgroves at West Lawn Memorial Funeral Home.

Hazel M. Straw died on January 27, 2013 at the age of 98 of age-related causes. She was born January 14, 1915 in Antelope, Oregon to Fred and Clara Simmons. No service is planned as per her request. 
She was preceded in death by her first husband, Melvin E. Paul, whom she married on August 5, 1944. During her many years of marriage to Melvin, they enjoyed fishing on the Suislaw River and going south to Hemet, California every winter where they spent time with their many friends. Hazel then married Allison Straw in 1998, whom also preceded her in death.
Hazel graduated from Thurston High School. She worked for Chet’s Frozen Foods for many years where she was not only a devoted employee, but a wonderful friend to many of her co-workers before and after she retired. 
She is survived by a son, Jerry Moon of Portland, a son Douglas Paul and daughter-in-law Sue of Eugene; seven grandchildren, thirteen great-grandchildren and one great-great-grandchild.
She was preceded in death by three brothers, Glen F. Simmons, Chester J. Simmons, and George W. Simmons; one sister, Nellie (Babe) Louvring; and a step-son, Eugene Paul of Portland.
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home.

Daniel Ray Minyard,  52, passed away at his home on January 31, 2013. A potluck celebration of life will be held Saturday, March 9th from 2-5pm at 42072 Hwy 58 in Lowell at the home of Kim and Casey Owsley.
Dan was born to Buddy and Jeanene Minyard.  He was an avid Nascar fan and always had on his cowboy boots.
He is survived by four children, Kimberlee Owsley, Tricia Minyard, Travis Minyard, Kyle Minyard and their mother Tacey Minyard; eight grandchildren, three brothers, five sisters and many nieces and nephews.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Longtime Springfield resident dies.
Services will be held at Springfield Memorial Funeral Home, 7305 Main Street on Saturday, February 9, 2013 at 10:00 am for Lorraine Prociw who passed away on February 3, 2013.  	
She was born in Jamestown, North Dakota on November 27th, 1921 to Benjamin Eugene Squires and Ellen Nancy (Miller) Squires.  She was the youngest of 12 children.
At age 11 months Lorraine’s family moved from North Dakota to Colfax, Washington. In 1925 when she was 4 years old, her family came to Springfield, which at that time consisted only of a few blocks from Mill to 10th Street and from Main to C Street.  Everything outside of this boundary was country.  There were floods every winter until the dams were built.
Lorraine watched Springfield change from bean, hop and hay fields, walnut, filbert, peach and apple orchards and berry patches into freeways, shopping centers and housing developments.  Those were the days teenagers would go out and work in the fields and orchards to earn money for school clothes for the coming year.  Swimming in the river kept us out of trouble and we had loads of fun.  Great times.
She attended Springfield schools starting as a first grader the year Brattian School opened in 1927.  Lorraine attended middle school at the old Lincoln Jr. High school which stood where the present high school now sits.  She was in the last graduating class that graduated from the old high school which is now the administration building in 1939.
Lorraine married William Prociw in 1938 in Vancouver, WA.  He passed away in 1955 in a logging accident.
She worked at Agr-Pac, her sister’s restaurant, several insurance agencies and retired in 1985 from Oregon Medical Laboratory which is now Peace Health Labs.
Lorraine loved to travel and upon retiring traveled on three cruises, three trips to Hawaii and visited Graceland and Washington D.C.  She also took many short trips with the senior center. Lorraine loved to golf, read, embroider, work in her yard, watch Atlanta Braves baseball games and was a long time Elvis fan.  She loved to spend time with family, including her church family of New Life at Wayside of which she was a member of.
She was also preceded in death by her parents, eleven siblings, a daughter Nancy Ann, grandson Kevin and numerous nieces and nephews.
She is survived by two sons, Dennis Eugene and wife Nancy and William Darrell and wife Lynda; two grandsons, Jeff and wife Leona, and Nick and wife Christina; three step-grandsons, Michael, Ronnie and Cory ; six great-grandchildren and 1 step-great-grandson.   
In lieu of flowers, please give in memory to New Life at Wayside, Lane County Youth for Christ or to your favorite charity.
Arrangements entrusted to Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Wayne A. Olson of Eugene died February 2, 2013 at the age of 56.  He was born October 9, 1956 in Ukiah, California to Darrold and Bernice (Pearson) Olson.  He worked for the Pearl Buck Center for many years.  He is survived by his father and his sister, Karen Frasnelly, both  of McMinnville.  A private service will be held.  Arrangements by Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Geneva Cronk was born February 20, 1936.  She passed away peacefully at her home, January 8, 2013.  Services were held at a previous date.

She graduated from Springfield High School in 1954. Geneva was a Bookkeeper and CPA.

She is survived by her husband of 57 years, Richard Cronk of Springfield, two sons, Bill Cronk of Fort Hood, Texas and Terry Cronk of Oakland, California, who were also both in the military academy at one time; sisters, Kay Pawlowski of Colvillle, Washington, Cleta Goggins and Vivian Bartholomew of Springfield, and Phyllis Craytor of Pleasant Hill.

She will be truely missed by her friends and family.

Bob George passed away on January 29, 2013 at the age of 80.  A funeral mass will take place Friday February 8, 2013 at 11am at St. Paul Catholic Church in Eugene. Inurnment will be Friday February 8, 2013 at 2pm at Mt. Calvary Cemetery in Eugene.  Bob was born March 15, 1932 in San Jose CA. to Joseph and Virginia George.  He graduated from Bellarmine High School in San Jose California.  He received his Bachelor of Science Degree from Santa Clara University in 1955. Bob was in the ROTC from 1953-1955, Army Active Duty from 1955-1957. He was stationed at Ft Lawton, Seattle Washington, where he was with the U.S Army Missile Battery Station. He was discharged January of 1963 as a Reserved Commissioned Officer of the Army. He enjoyed a successful career as a project manager in multiple developments associated with resorts and golf course communities.  His career took him from the Santa Clara Valley in California   to Maryland spanning over 40+ years.  He enjoyed traveling, woodworking, home designing and spending time with his family. He also enjoyed owning and driving many different corvettes over the years.  Bob is survived by his children, Wayne George of Seattle Washington and Lloyd George of Eugene Oregon. He has 3 grandchildren all of whom will miss him dearly

David A. Duff of Monroe, formerly of Eugene and The Dalles, died January 31, 2013 at the age of 90 of esophageal cancer. No service is planned at this time.
David was born June 25, 1922, to Moler and Bessie (Fenner) Duff in Columbus, Ohio. He graduated from high school and joined the Navy in World War II. He saw combat in the Pacific Theater and served in the Aleutians. He married Helenmae Meyers on May 15, 1945. They moved to Seattle where David served as a boiler maker for Great Northern Railroad. They later moved to Cascade Locks where he trained at Bonneville Dam and worked as a Control Room Operator at McNary and The Dalles Dams.  He retired as Chief-of-Operations for The Dalles and John Day Dams.
David enjoyed fishing, camping, tying flies, playing cards, golf, good food, but most of all he enjoyed people, especially family.
He is survived by his wife of 67 years, daughter Jackie (Duff) and son-in-law Randy Crowson of Monroe, daughter Alice (Duff) and son-in-law David Houghtaling of Schenectady, NY, four grandsons, Damain Crowson of Grants Pass, Jason Crowson of Sacramento, Bradley Crowson of Cheshire, Paul Houghtaling of Santa Rosa, California, and four great-grand children. He was preceded  in death by an infant daughter Janet Elaine.
Memorial Contributions may be made to Cascade Health and Hospice Solutions. Arrangements by Murphy-Musgrove Funeral Home. Condolences may be made online at www.musgroves.com.

fields.obituary_body: George William Cunningham, 74, passed away on February 1, 2013, in Cottage Grove after a short illness.  He was born on June 12, 1938 in Grayson, Louisiana.  The family moved to Ft. Bragg, CA in 1945.  George served his country proudly as a Marine from 1955-1960.  He spoke often of his service time in Japan and the South Pacific.  He retired after 34 years as a mechanic at Lane Transit District in Eugene.  He loved to fish, and going to the coast to do so was a favorite pastime.  He also was an amateur photographer who found an opportunity to take a picture wherever he went.  He leaves behind a wife, Patricia; sons Weston, Adam, Russell, Robert, Randy, David, Burton, and Michael; daughters Deena, LeeAnna, and Penny; 20 grandchildren and 13 great-grandchildren.  In lieu of flowers, the family requests that donations be made in George's name to The Wounded Warrior Project.com.

Nadyne Lamb, 75, of Cottage Grove, OR passed away January 31, 2013 of age related causes.  She was born November 30, 1937, in Eugene, OR to Marvin and Neva (Eastburn) Shaw.  Nadyne graduated from Cottage Grove High School.  She was a bank teller for the First National Bank.  Family was everything to Nadyne, they were always #1.  She enjoyed painting and crafts and was a member of the Church of Christ of Cottage Grove.  Nadyne married Bruce Lamb on August 17, 1957, in Cottage Grove.  She is survived by Son, Chris (Valerie) Lamb, Eugene, OR, Son, Scot Lamb, WA, Son, Pat (Kellie) Lamb, Cottage Grove, OR, Daughter, Candace (Candi) Lamb, Morgan Hill, CA, Brothers; Igene and Eldon Shaw both of Cottage Grove, OR and 9 Grandchildren.  She was preceded in death by her husband Bruce Lamb on April 28, 1993.  A Funeral will be held Saturday, February 9, 2013, 1:00 PM at Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel and private family interment at Fir Grove Cemetery.  Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Funeral Chapel, 123 S. 7th Street, Cottage Grove, OR.

Willard Lucas was truly a man of the river. Born and raised on the rugged Rogue River in Southern Oregon he claimed to have built his first boat at the age of three. He was an experienced river guide in his teens and went on to proficiency on many well known white water streams. He ran the Rogue, Illinois, Oyhee, and McKenzie in Oregon and the Middle Fork of Salmon River of Idaho numerous times. When not running rivers Willard honed his skills as a boat builder and many of his "McKenzie River" Dories are still out on the water even though the last one was built in 1976. In 1976 Willard and his wife, Maryanne took over management of the Lucas Pioneer Ranch and Lodge at Agness, upon the death of his father Larry Lucas. There they provided unique hospitality to river travelers until retirement in 1998. Willard truly loved the Wild Rogue Country that had been the center of his life since infancy. It was always on his mind as he retired to Eugene due to health reasons. Willard followed his beloved wife, his high-school sweetheart, in death late Thursday, January 31st. Maryanne had gone ahead of him to be with the Lord in April of last year. 
Willard was born Feb. 28, 1927. After his growing up years in Agness, he attended Myrtle Point High School until enlisting in the Navy in May of 1945, eventually serving on the Island of Guam, until being discharged in July 1946. A semester at the University of Oregon convinced Willard that "studies" were not his thing. He would eventually spend time working in local mills and even a stint as a Eugene Patrol Officer. But the river kept calling him and thus he spent most of his working years on the water or in his boat shop, or serving traveler's on the river. 
Willard is survived by his children; Melinda Mross & Gene of Eugene, Larry Lucas & Echo of Eugene, Nancy Tullius & Gregg of Salem, & Patrick Lucas & Patricia of Beijing, China. His grandchildren; Joseph Mross of Eugene, Laurie Cox of Eugene, Bethany Cole of Los Angeles, Michelle Provost of Atlanta, Tiffany Lucas of Fallbrook, CA., Chrystal Plum of Jefferson, OR., Cielle Lucas of Seattle, Kyrie Lucas of Beijing, Alaia Lucas of Beijing, Saret Lucas of Beijing, and by great-grandchildren; Andrew Mross of Eugene, Gabriel Evans of Fallbrook, Joshua Miller of Jefferson, OR., & Adrian Cole of Los Angeles. Willard is also survived by three sisers; Corlyss McCullough of Walterville, Donna Bosman of Eagle Point and Larryan Gerondale of Elizabeth, Colorado. 
A private celebration of life will be held February 10th. A public service is scheduled for July 20, 2013 Gold Beach, Oregon. Go to www.lucaslodgeoregon.com for more information. 
Dad you have now crossed over your biggest, most powerful river. We all know how much you wanted to see Mom again. We will miss you, but will look forward to seeing you both again on the other shore. 
Arrangements entrusted to Musgrove Family Mortuary.
Please sign guest book at musgroves.com.

Angela Hart of Eugene died January 28th at the age of 35.
She was born on  December 17, 1977 in Springfield and graduated from Springfield High School in 1996.  She then served in the United States Air Force until 1999.  Angela married Jeff Hart on August 5, 2000 and the couple has lived in Eugene where they have been raising their family.
She is survived by her husband Jeff: two sons, Tyler and Andrew: parents, Mary and Dennis  Snow of Salem: brother Doug Stockton of Eugene: brother Will Snow of Yakima, WA and was preceeded in death by brother Mitch Stockton of Eugene.  
A memorial service will be held Saturday February 9th at 2pm at Bethesda Lutheran Church at 4445 Royal Ave. Eugene, OR 97402.  Funeral arrangements by West Lawn Funeral Home.  Condolences can be made online at www.Musgroves.com

On January 29, 2013, our beautiful and loving mother, grandmother, sister, and aunt left our world.  Barbara Jean Hatleli was born on August 30, 1930 in Ottumwa, Iowa, to Lloyd Francis Kendall and Josephine Cecilia Patkin Kendall.  She grew up in Ottumwa, Iowa.  On November  7, 1958, she married Elert Orville Hatleli.  They moved to Eugene and she was a homemaker for years.  She devoted her entire life to her family as they were most important to her.   Later in life, she was a caregiver at Cascade Manor for many years.  She travelled to Mexico, Sweden, Germany, London, Denmark, and the Czech Republic (the latter two being her favorite.)She loved sports of all kinds, especially her beloved U of O Ducks. She had a most beautiful smile and the biggest heart.  
She is survived by daughters:  Sanya Brown of Ashland, OR; Elizabeth Ann Kupper (Bob) of Eugene, OR; Cindy Leighton (Glenn) of Eugene, OR; Kathy Rasmussen (Christian) of Portland, OR; Linnea Sanchez (Carlos) of Austin, MN; and Karen Carlson (Jay) of Austin, MN.  And sons, Randy Hatleli of Eugene, OR; Bobby Hatleli (Rochelle) of Austin, MN.   Also survived by 19 grandchildren:  Stefanie, Brandon, Aurora, Jacob, Scott, Casey, Alexander, Sophie, Ken, Troy, Jeff, Theresa, Adam, Dustin, Christopher, Andrea,  Jerod, Tracy, and Tina.   She is also survived by sisters, Audrey Guthrie of Sacramento, CA, and Lloydean Rump of Agency, IA, and numerous nieces and nephews.  
She is preceded in death by her husband, Elert Orville Hatleli (1990), the love of her life, and we know our parents are in heaven dancing to Proud Mary.  Also preceded in death by her step-son, Bruce Hatleli.
Musgrove Family Mortuary is in charge of arrangements.  Service will be held on February 9th at Noon at Lane Memorial Gardens, 5300 W. 11th, Eugene, OR.  Viewing will be from 11 a.m. to Noon.  Private burial to follow.  Contributions may be made to the Wounded Warriors Fund in memory of Barbara.

John "Jack" Winslow, 81, of Cottage Grove, OR passed away January 30, 2013.  He was born October 21, 1931, in Roseburg, OR to Marion and Hilma (Hendrickson) Winslow.   Jack graduated from Grants Pass High School, Oregon State University and graduated with a BA from Southern Oregon University.  He served in the National Guard and taught 6th grade for the Eugene School District.  Jack was a Realtor for 50 years in Land Development/Building and Timber Management in Lane and Douglas Counties and developed 2 Springfield subdivisions.  While in Springfield Jack was President of the Jaycees, a member of the School Board and a Junior First Citizen.  He is a member of the First Presbyterian Church of Cottage Grove.  Jack enjoyed hunting, fishing, boating, recreational traveling with kids, grandkids and friends.  Citizen.  He was married to Banti Robinson for 57 years.  Survivors include his wife, Banti Winslow, Cottage Grove,OR,  Son, Chris (Linda) Winslow, Creswell, OR,  Son, Kent Winslow, Vida, OR, Sister, Marilyn Tullius, Oakland, CA, Sister and brother-in-law, Nina and Ken Kivett, Coburg, OR, Grandchildren, Carrie Garner, El Paso, TX, Kim Winslow-Reuter, Eloy, AZ, Steven Winslow, Salem, OR and special friend and business partner, Jim and Ardis Belknap.  He was preceded in death by Son, Craig Winslow.   A Celebration of Life will be held Monday, February 11, 2013, 1:00 PM at the First Presbyterian Church, Cottage Grove.  Arrangements by Smith-Lund-Mills Chapel, 123 S. 7th St., Cottage Grove, OR 97424.

Ben Green, 71 of Creswell, passed away January 27, 2013, from complications of Alzheimer's Disease.  Born on March 31, 1941 to Seth and Hazel (Wood) Green in Rochester, MN.  Ben proudly served his country in the US Navy as an aircraft mechanic on the USS Intrepid aircraft carrier.
While still in the Navy Reserves, he started working with Continental Airlines as a mechanic until 1983.  Ben spent the remainder of his career as a Senior Mechanical Test Conductor for TRW, in their space and defense program.
 Ben married Arlene Stampfli in 1976, in Los Angeles, where they lived for 29 years. Retirement brought them both to the beautiful Creswell area in the Fall of 2005.  Ben and Arlene were happily married for over 36 years.  Ben is survived by his wife, Arlene of Creswell; a son, Terry Green of CO; daughters Julie Storjohann of AZ and Michelle Banks of TN; a sister, Carolyn Walker and a brother, Robert Green, both of CO; six grandchildren and two great grandchildren.  A Celebration of Life is pending.
In lieu of flowers, the family requests that contributions be made to The Alzheimer's Association, in Ben's memory.  Arrangements by Poole-Larsen Funeral Home.

Mary “Hazel” Slaughter of Eugene died January 30, 2013. She was 89. A funeral followed by the burial will be held at 2:00pm Saturday, February 2nd at Lane Memorial Gardens and Funeral Home.
Hazel was born December 28, 1923 in Glencoe, Oklahoma to Armand and Della Dean. She married Ralph L. Slaughter January 16, 1943 in Wichita Falls, Texas. She and Ralph moved to Oregon in 1960. Hazel worked as a cook in public schools. 
She was preceded in death by her husband, Ralph, who passed away in April of 2010.
Survivors include three sons, Vern, Ray and Dale Slaughter, all of Eugene; ten grandchildren and twelve great-grandchildren. 
Arrangements by Lane Memorial Funeral Home in Eugene

fields.obituary_body:
Robert "Bob" Englund passed away Jan. 24, 2013 at the age of 79. He was born in Hendrum, Mn. 
His parents died at an early age, and he continued to live in the Hendrum area with local
families until he graduated high school.  He was the oldest of five siblings. 
He served in the Air Force from 1951-1955. He was a Korean War Veteran.
He was married to Jean (Chesterman) Englund in 1954.  After his military discharge in 1955
they settled in Springfield, Or. 
He initially worked at Weyerhaeuser, then began his career in the heating business.
He worked for Crombie Fuel Co., Automatic Heat Co., and finished his career with Marshall's
Heating & Air Conditioning.  He worked for Marshall's for 22 years .
Upon his retirement in 1995 he enjoyed his grand children, along with  gardening, hunting and fishing.
Bob was divorced from his wife, Jean in 2004, who survives , along with two children:  Bob Jr. and his wife , Pam, of Springfield.
Carrie DeWitt and her husband, Allen, of Terrebonne.
A daughter, Laurel Englund preceded him in death in 2002. 
Grandchildren: Stefanie Chase and her husband, Scott, Kimberly Wing and her husband , Nick, all of Springfield. Lexie DeWitt of Bend and Joshua DeWitt of Terrebonne.
Great Grand children: Halle and Abby Wing of Springfield.
Bob is also survived by his brother, Richard Englund of Eugene, and his sisters, Greta Rinerson of San Jose, Ca. and Ingrid Englund of Springfield.
He was preceded in death by his brother Jim Englund of Springfield. 
A Memorial Service will be held Feb. 8 at 1 p.m. At Camp Creek Church, 37535 Upper Camp Creek Rd., Springfield. A potluck dinner will follow.
Memorial gifts in Bob's honor may be made to Meals on Wheels or the Eugene Mission.
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home Springfield.

Albert Pachl of Springfield, Oregon died January 27, 2013 at the age of 82. He was born December 3, 1930. A Funeral Mass will be held Friday, February 1, 2013 at 1:00 PM at St. Alice Catholic Church in Springfield, Oregon. A Rosary will be at Musgrove Family Center in Eugene, Thursday, January 31st, at 7:00 PM. 
Memorial Contributions can be sent to Alzhiemers Association.
Arrangements entrusted to Musgrove Family Mortuary.

Edwin "Ray" Hess Jr died at the age of 72. He was born to Edwin Ray Hess Sr and Beverly Jane (Willick)Hess. He is survived by his wife of 38 years Matild Hess and daughter Julia Hess of Eugene OR, daughter Erika Gabba of Salem OR and 5 grandchildren.
Arrangements by Major Family Funeral Home.

Mr. Hatton was born in Bakersfield, California and moved to the Marcola area at a young age. He graduated from Marcola High School in 1942. He attended the University of Oregon. On January 23, 1945 he married Rosemary Aubin in Marcola. Mr. Hatton served in the US Navy during WWII and was honorably discharges as a Lieutenant (JG). He worked as a millwright, manager and engineer for Giustina Lumber Co, Roseburg Lumber Co, Georgia Pacific and Gregory Forest Products. Survivors include his wife Rosemary; daughter Jean Ira of Blue River, Oregon; son Wayne Hatton of Redmond, Washington; brother Rich Hatton of Vancouver, Washington; 4 grandchildren and 7 great grandchildren. Memorial services will be held Saturday, February 2, 2013 at 3:00 pm at Oak Park Assisted Living in Roseburg, Oregon. Please visit www.wilsonschapeloftherosesfh.com.

fields.obituary_body: Evelyn "Evie" Lipe-Russell, 85, died January 27, 2013 of age-related causes.  She was born on June 27, 1927 to Harry and Ruth (Reese) Keeney in Spearfish, SD.  She worked as a CNA at LA County Prison Hospital in Loma Linda, CA.  Evelyn was married to Oren Lipe for 45 years until his death in 1991.  She later married Edgar "Bud" Russell, and they were married for 21 years.  She enjoyed hunting, fishing, cooking, collecting cookbooks, and attending church.  She is survived by daughter, Rebecca McDaniel of Boise, ID; daughter, Sue (Rick) Swetz of Lancaster, CA; daughter, Debra (Mike) Fulp of Woodstock, GA; daughter, Melinda (Kenny) Burrows of Palm Dale, CA; daughter, Mary (Doug) Laws of Eugene, OR; son, Nathan (Nancy) Lipe of Broken Arrow, OK: stepdaughter, Gwen (Martin) Paletta of Snohomish, WA; sister, Thelma Orr of Drain, OR and sister, Annabelle Ferguson of Twin Falls, ID.  She was preceded in death by first husband, Oren Lipe in 1991, and grandson, Kelly Lipe in 2007.  A funeral will be held on January 31, 2013 at 1:00 p.m. at Smith-Lund-Mills Chapel in Cottage Grove.  There will be a  visitation from 4-6:00 p.m. on Jan 30, also at SLM Chapel.  Burial will be at Drain City Cemetery in Drain.

Jack L. Sager of Springfield died January 25, 2013 at the age of 78. No service is planned.
He was born January 23, 1935 in Eugene to Carl and Myrtle Sager. He married Beverly Strom on March 13, 1953. Jack worked as a log scaler for Weyerhaeuser until retiring after 46 years.
Survivors include his wife Beverly of Springfield; a son, Gary of Frisco, Texas; two grandsons, Gabe of Frisco, Texas and Levi of Eugene; and two  great-grandchildren, Shelby and Garrett, both of Frisco, Texas.
Jack was predeceased by two sons, Dennis and Mark.
Arrangements by Springfield Memorial Funeral Home.

Angeline Stephenson of Eugene, Oregon died January 27th 2013, at the age of 87. She was born January 2, 1926 in Detroit, Michigan to Anglelo & Georgia (Souleotis) Paulos. 
A funeral Service will be held Wednesday, January 30, 2013 at 11:00 AM at St. George Greek Orthodox Church. 
Angeline was a High School Graduate. She married Jimmy P. Stephenson on March 3, 1951 in Hollywood, California. She was a Homemaker and prior to her marriage, she was a Dental Assistant.
